column16: An ambitious renewables target has been set, seeing 22GW of renewables capacity added by 2030, saving 300 billion cubic meters of gas. Sectoral goals have also been detailed and include a 2020 target of 4.5GW of clean energy that is unlikely to be met. Algeria may yet scale down its ambitions in light of the large gap between installed capacity and its objectives. A feed-in tariff has de facto been replaced by tenders. Yet problems with auctions have been numerous, including successive delays and the ultimate cancellation of a 4GW tender. A PV tender held in early 2019 was undersubscribed, with only eight bidders. The lack of progress is in large part due to stringent local content rules, restrictions on the involvement of foreign actors and uncertainties about access to finance.

Angola's electricity demand is predominantly met by large hydro. In 2018, the technology accounted for 60% of Angola's 5.3GW of installed capacity. The country aims to add 800MW of renewable energy capacity (500MW of biomass, 100MW of solar, 100MW of wind and 100MW of mini-hydro) by 2025, under the government's energy strategy "Visao Angola Energia.' The $23-billion energy strategy for 2018-25 aims to reach 9.9GW of total capacity, and boost electricity-access rates from around 34% in 2018 to 60%. By this time, natural gas is to meet 20% of generation, hydro will account for 64%, while 8% will come from other renewables. Of the 9.9GW of new build, just under a third will be developed through public-private partnerships. Angola has no substantial incentives such as feed-in tariffs or auctions to promote renewable energy deployment, though it has signaled its intention to eventually do so via its "Bet on Solar Energy Program", which aims to tender a total of 200MW of solar, divided into five 40MW lots, by 2022.

Benin's authorities are opening up the country's electricity sector to private investors in a bid to increase supply and competition. They are doing so via a number of legislative reforms. On April 13 2018, the country's parliament adopted an amended version of the international agreement on the Benin-Togolese Electricity Code. As a result, the country's utility CEB (Benin Electric Community) lost the single buyer status that it has enjoyed since 1968, and is in charge of energy transmission. Furthermore, in June 2018, Benin's National Assembly adopted law number 2018-18 regulating climate change, and February 2018 saw the creation of the UC/PDER, Entity in Charge of Renewable Energy Policy Development. In parallel, the Millennium Challenge Account II (MCA II) ' a foreign aid agency backed by the U.S. government ' is on a four-year mission to help the government develop new energy projects.

Historically, Botswana has lacked the legal framework and incentives to develop its renewable energy industry, with the National Energy Policy remaining in draft form since October 2009. An ambitious tender for 100MW of solar PV capacity announced in 2017 was cancelled in May 2019. The tender is expected to be re-issued and re-defined as an IPP project, with investors to become 100% owners of the plants. The stability of these tenders is questionable as a previous tender in 2015 also failed to move forward even after attracting more than 118 bids. Import and tax incentives apply to a wide range of manufacturing goods and there are no specific provisions for the renewables industry. The awareness of these incentives also remains low.

Burkina Faso has very limited clean energy policy. A few tenders have been held for small-scale solar projects and the government recently announced 155MW of solar capacity to be tendered with several other small projects also in the pipeline. Otherwise speaking, there is no auction program, feed-in tariff or net metering scheme in place or planned for the near future. The country aims to have a share of 50% renewables in its energy mix by 2025, up from just under 19% in 2018, so the planned solar tenders will help to bring the country closer to its target. Burkina Faso offers tax exemptions on solar panels. However, the complementary equipment is not tax exempt, which somewhat limits the incentive.

Burundi's Electricity Law, last updated in 2015, establishes rules for the development of new generation sites, including the possibility of public-private partnerships, and specific regulation for hydro power plants. The country's rural electrification program is planned mainly around grid extensions and decentralized solutions. The country has a specialized Rural Electrification Agency, which aims to plan and develop projects to electrify isolated areas. The only effective support for renewables developers in Burundi is import-tariff exemptions for solar and wind equipment established by the East African Community, of which Burundi is a member. There are no fiscal incentives or other policy instruments such as feed-in tariffs. There are no specific legal tools to discourage fossil fuels. Burundi has committed unconditionally to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 3% compared to a business-as-usual scenario for 2030, as part of its nationally determined contribution.

Cameroon has committed to securing 25% electricity generation from renewable sources by 2035, as part of its nationally determined contribution (NDC). In 2019 small hydro and solar accounted for just 4.5% of Cameroon's installed capacity, so there is a long way to go to achieve the target. The government aims to reach it through a renewable energy law, which would introduce a mandatory auction or tendering process, set renewable electricity purchase tariffs, and clarify rules around the purchase of renewable electricity. No draft has been announced as of yet. The only effective support for renewables developers in Cameroon is that equipment benefits from VAT exemptions. Other fiscal incentives, such as import duty waivers, are not consistently implemented. The utility, Eneo, has begun to procure tenders for solar.

The Central African Republic has little in the way of implemented or upcoming clean energy policy. Despite the vast majority of electricity generation stemming from small hydro plants, the country has no clean energy targets to supplement or maintain these penetration levels. Additionally, there are no auctions, feed-in tariffs or other incentives. Given the dire security situation in the country, this is not surprising. Officials are keen to develop policies in order to incentivize more independent power producers to become active.

Chad has been slow to set up renewable energy incentives. As a first step, the government created the Agency for the Development of Renewable Energy (ADER) within the Ministry of Petroleum and Energy, which is accountable for renewables-based electrification, among other responsibilities. The government has not set a national target regarding renewable energy deployment or passed any further supporting policies. Nevertheless, the 2019 revision of the country's finance law includes a provision on clean energy. This provision stipulates that any equipment relevant to the generation and promotion of renewable energy be exempt from import duties and value-added tax.

The Republic of the Congo has little to offer in terms of clean energy policy. The country has neither implemented legislation intended to incentivize the development of renewable energy projects, nor set a specific target that it seeks to achieve. The policy agenda is focused upon managing the emergence of a new state utility and maximizing the country's large hydro potential, while clean energy is pushed to the margins.

The Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) had its first democratic transfer of power since independence in January 2019 after a controversial election held in December 2018. The election saw President Felix Tshisekedi emerge as the winner. Although he won the popular vote, his party failed to win a majority in the National Assembly and Senate, leaving it under the control of former president Joseph Kabila's FCC party. On August 20 to 22, 2019, the president held the country's first electricity forum to source inputs into the country's energy policy and strategy. The key focus of the government is increasing accessibility to electricity to about 30% by 2030.  The DRC's low energy requirement and dependence on hydropower is not conducive to the development of clean-energy policy to encourage renewables build. Tax incentives for renewable energy projects are the sole area where policy directly benefits the industry.

Cote d'Ivoire has set an ambitious 42% renewable energy target by 2030, which is marred by the fact that only 16% is to be accounted for by renewables other than mid-to-large hydro. That said, no such clean energy capacity has been commissioned to date. Clean energy tenders have been held since 2013, but only the first of the winning projects is starting to near completion this year. Tax incentives have been implemented for solar, with a halving of VAT to 9% and import duties waived for panels, but enforcement at customs is nevertheless erratic. Neither is there any supportive policy in place for off-grid project development at anything above a solar kit-level. Mini-grids are not allowed due to the government's focus on electrification through building out transmission lines.

Eritrea has little renewable energy policy in place. The country aims for renewables to account for 70% of electricity generation by 2030, as part of its NDC, but does not yet have any enabling framework to help it achieve this goal. As a further measure, it plans to improve power sector infrastructure to reduce transmission and distribution losses by at least 50% by the same year. However, there are a lack of incentives for renewable energy developers and very little transparency on existing regulations.

Ethiopia's 4.3GW generation fleet, of which nearly 90% comes from hydro, is among the cleanest and largest in Sub-Saharan Africa. The country has far greater ambitions though, setting a goal for 17.2GW of power capacity by 2020. Despite over 8GW of large hydro in the development pipeline, Ethiopia will fall far short of its target. The roll-out of several policies in the near term should still make clean energy investment attractive in the country, however. A public-private partnerships law will allow independent power producers to negotiate power purchase agreements directly with the state-owned utility, Ethiopia Electric Power. The country also expanded its Scaling Solar tender, initially for 250MW, to 750MW, indicating a desire to diversify the country's clean energy mix.

The government originally set a target of 10% renewable energy generation in Ghana's energy mix by 2020, but it was pushed back to 2030. The current level of renewable energy penetration remains very low and it is unlikely to increase dramatically in the near future. The government that took power in January 2017 reviewed all renewables PPAs approved under the country's feed-in tariff program, and canceled or deferred some of them. This is because Ghana had excess power generation capacity compared to demand, and the government wanted to stop paying for power unnecessarily. The feed-in tariff program exists in theory today, however, it is unlikely developers can access this any longer.

Guinea offers no policies to incentivize clean energy development, partly as a result of its many rivers and the government focus on tapping into an estimated 6GW of hydropower potential. Promising developments include the creation of the rural electrification agency, AGER, in 2017. The creation of the agency has been slow off the mark, however, with a board of directors only having been established in June 2019. State utility EDG's mandate must also be more clearly defined. A long-awaited reform of the 1993 Electricity Law has now been drafted, although has yet to be validated. In an effort to restructure state utility EDG, Veolia has been managing the utility since 2015, with no definite end in sight.

In December 2018, President Kenyatta said that Kenya planned to attain '100% green energy consumption by 2020'. Meanwhile there has been no legislative action to set such a target. This non-binding target appeared to include large-hydro, which accounted for more than 30% of the country's generation in 2018, and is difficult to achieve within the timeline. Still, Kenya is gradually increasing its non-large hydro renewables by adding solar, wind and geothermal. The government no longer offers a feed-in tariff for these technologies after more than 4GW of capacity applied, which the grid system cannot absorb. The country is in the process of shifting from a feed-in tariff scheme to an auction-based one, but no further details have been announced even though parliament approved a draft bill in August 2018.

The Lesotho Energy Policy (2015-2025) provides a strategy for the energy sector but has not been formally adopted, creating uncertainty over the status and plan for the sector. A draft renewable energy framework policy has also been developed, including mechanisms for procuring both off-grid and on-grid renewable energy, but this has not yet been adopted either, adding to an uncertain investment climate. There are no specific regulations for off-grid renewables deployment. The country has set ambitious electricity-access targets of 40% of the population by 2020, renewable energy being one of the main tools proposed to achieve this.

Liberia introduced energy targets in 2009 for 30% of electricity and 10% overall energy consumption to originate from renewable sources by 2030, which is not overly ambitious given the country's heavy reliance on hydropower and its large solar resource. 
No policy mechanisms, such as feed-in tariffs or auctions, have been introduced ' making it difficult for renewable energy development to prosper. Developers must instead reach a bilateral agreement with the state-owned utility if seeking to supply the main grid. PPA guidelines for independent power producers are being developed.
The Rural and Renewable Energy Agency was established in 2015 and microgrid operators have since become active across several communities formerly without access to power. A dedicated microgrid policy is currently under development.

Madagascar has a handful of relatively unambitious clean energy policies in place. By 2030, the government aims for 85% renewable energy in total generation, to be achieved primarily through hydropower. However, progress toward this target is slow, with the current share of renewables in generation standing at 55% and few clean energy projects of scale in the pipeline. The most recent developments include commissioning of the country's first utility-scale solar project in mid-2018, in addition to a call for tenders in early-2018 for 25MW of solar with energy storage, supported by the World Bank's Scaling Solar program. Further policies include a reduction in corporate income tax for renewable energy investments ' equivalent to 50% of the country's total investment so far in clean energy.

Historically, 90% of primary energy has come from burning biomass in Malawi and only 3% has been met by electricity. Trees are cut down to make charcoal, leading to concerns about deforestation and worsening the effects of climate change. In the National Energy Policy (NEP) of 2003, the government announced a target to meet 7% of primary energy demand with renewable generation by 2020. This was not an ambitious goal, especially given the timeline. The updated NEP of 2018 further delayed this target, taking it to 7% by 2030. The National Renewable Energy Strategy of 2017 sets out steps that the government can take to promote grid-scale renewables, mini-grids, off-grid solar and bioenergy. However, this is not a binding piece of legislation.

Mali has several clean energy policies in place ' making it further advanced than some neighboring countries. As part of its National Action Plan for Renewable Energy, it aims to increase the share of renewable installed capacity, including medium and large hydro, to 59.25% by 2020. Clean energy currently accounts for one quarter of Mali's total installed capacity, so the country has a way to go to achieve its target, especially given the dominance of hydropower. Mali also offers exemptions on import duties and VAT for solar equipment. A stand-alone feature in the region, the rural electrification fund subsidizes investments in off-grid projects by up to 80% for projects valued at a maximum of $500,000, which is a key factor in boosting Mali's vibrant off-grid market. The subsidies should theoretically incentivize the development of capital-intensive technologies such as solar, but most operators have been relying on diesel so far. Solar-diesel hybrid projects are however becoming more popular.

Mauritania's government has rolled out little in the way of incentives to deploy clean energy. Nevertheless, renewable energy currently accounts for 29% of total installed capacity, so the country has comfortably overshot its 20% goal by 2020. A public procurement system is in place, with the national utility, Somelec, issuing bids for renewable energy-related projects since 2013. However, there are persistent problems about the irregularity of tender announcements and procedures. A law on public-private partnerships was issued in July 2017, in an effort to promote independent power production, but its implementation remains incomplete.

Heavily dependent on fossil-fuel imports for its energy needs, Morocco has ambitious targets of 42% of its generating capacity to be renewable by 2020, and 52% by 2030. At the time these targets were announced in 2009, Morocco had only 280MW of wind capacity. By the end of 2018, renewable capacity had grown to 1,220MW of wind and 711MW of solar. Wind and solar will need to reach 2GW each by 2020 to meet the target. Timely commissioning of the remaining pipeline of tenders will see Morocco meet its goal. Seen as key to securing energy independence, whilst reducing expensive fuel imports, the renewable sector has received strong state support. The first 400MW of hybrid solar thermal and PV of the Noor-Midelt projects was announced in 2018. The winning consortium, led by EDF, bid a price of $70/MWh, which includes five hours of storage for dispatch into the evening peak.

Mozambique has taken early steps toward development of clean energy alongside ample donor support. A lack of regulatory clarity and follow-through, however, as well as competing priorities, continue to restrain development. Longer-term priorities include several large hydroelectric power projects, such as the 1,500MW Mphanda Nkuwa dam. Still, near-term efforts are focused on natural gas and coal-fired generation facilities, as well as two solar projects, one of which was commissioned in July 2019. Scatec's 40MW Mocuba PV Plant is Mozambique's first utility-scale solar project. A second, Neoen's 40MW Metoro PV Plant, remains under development. Mozambique created its renewable energy feed-in tariff (Refit) in 2014, intended to apply to PV, wind, biomass and small hydro projects from 10 kW to 10MW. However, the scheme has not come into force and there are no permitted tariffs for off-grid projects. There are no auctions in Mozambique currently, but there is a program that is under development, Proler, that aims to launch four pilot tenders by 2021, three for solar and one for wind, of 30-50MW each.

In 2015, Namibia introduced its feed-in tariff program (Refit), which opened up its previously vertically integrated power sector to privately owned renewables projects. Under Refit, Nampower (Namibia's state-owned utility) has signed contracts for 70MW of solar capacity between 14 counterparties. As of 2019, 45MW of the 70MW contracted have been commissioned. 
Nambia's power sector regulator has suggested that it would stop awarding Refit contracts, and instead switch to tenders to procure additional capacity.
Two renewable projects totaling 41MW have been awarded through tenders to date. Five unsolicited independent power producers (IPPs) have signed PPAs with Nampower.
In its 2019-2023 business plan, Nampower pledged to spend an additional $338 million to add 220MW of renewable power to the grid, and another 70MW that will be procured from IPPs. This would represent a 50% increase in Namibia's installed capacity.

Niger is unlikely to succeed in its aim to reach its target for 27% share of renewable energy in installed capacity by 2020, given that its current share is just 5% and the country offers little in the way of clean energy incentives. The government also aims to connect 15% of the population to off-grid renewables by 2020. In September 2017, an import duty exemption for renewable energy components was passed, although the list of exempted equipment is subject to regular review and is inconsistently applied. Since 2016, tenders for renewables projects have been issued and these specify that projects must ultimately to be transferred to the state utility Nigelec.

Nigeria has a handful of clean energy policies, including an ambitious target to achieve 30GW of power generation by 2030, of which 30% is expected to come from renewables.
The country's failure to provide a stable electricity grid has created a fertile environment for the decentralized off-grid PV sector to develop. In 2017, Nigeria introduced supportive mini-grid regulation, making it easier for developers to build projects of 100kW to 1MW in size. BNEF estimates that there is 20MW of distributed-PV installed to-date. Building projects with capacity in excess of 1MW often requires time-consuming approvals, such as a generator license. 
In the on-grid space, the 14 PV developers who signed utility-scale PPAs in 2016 have stalled, due to discrepancies in guarantees or risk measures that the government needs to make, with no certainty as to when or if these will actually be built.

Rwanda's 100% electrification target has been a key driver for Rwanda's energy sector growth. Originally set at 70% by June 2018, the country was forced to increase the target to 100% to be met by 2024. Nonetheless, Rwanda has shown unprecedented progress for Sub-Saharan Africa. By the end of 2018, the country had reached and electrification rate of 51%, compared to 10% in 2010. The national strategy aims to reach the 2024 target via 52% on-grid connections and 48% off-grid solutions, such as solar home systems and mini-grids. REG, the national utility, says that currently 37% of households are connected to the national grid, whilst 14% access electricity is via off-grid solutions.

Senegal has set itself a target of 15% renewable energy by 2025, which will be met as soon as 2020. The objective will likely be raised to 18% by 2023, a revision expected to be confirmed by 2H 2019. Clean energy auctions have been held, the most recent being the World Bank-backed 'Scaling Solar' tender. The auction saw 60MW of PV awarded for the rock-bottom price of $0.038/kWh. Further policies include VAT and import duty exemptions for solar panels. For now, VAT waivers are provided on an ad-hoc basis for utility-scale projects pending the release of an equipment list, due for 2H 2019. Finally, a new program will introduce a tariff paid out for all excess energy generated over 20 years for residential biogas and solar.

In 2017, the parliament of Sierra Leone ratified the country's renewable energy policy for 79.7% and 84% of final energy to come from renewables by 2020 and 2030, respectively, but there has been little progress since then to implement supportive policies to achieve these targets.
The government has not introduced any auctions or feed-in tariffs to encourage private power producers to build clean energy projects and there is a lack of progress as a result.
Sierra Leone's energy mix consists largely of biomass and hydropower generation, although a large amount is currently supplied by diesel ships moored off the capital, Freetown. The proportion of oil and diesel-powered generation could theoretically be replaced by solar power if more effective incentive mechanisms were introduced.

Somalia's power sector is severely under-developed due to years of conflict and political instability. Most electricity in urban areas is supplied by localized, privately-run mini-grids. Local independent electricity service providers typically own both power generation and power transmission infrastructure. The country's relatively small 100MW installed base consists primarily of diesel generators and in most cases, consumers buy directly from the mini-grid at high prices. The country is divided into regions with no central administration overseeing the energy sector, while the self-declared independent Somaliland has its own energy ministry. Consolidation is occurring among many independent power producers but there is a concerning lack of regulation around this. Many international organizations, including the World Bank and USAID, are active in Somalia and are working to help establish a regulatory framework to incentivize additional investment in electricity infrastructure.

Once the benchmark of success, South Africa's renewables auction program is facing a protracted policy stalemate. In April 2018, Energy Minister Jeff Radebe signed power-purchase agreements for the 27 outstanding renewable energy projects from Rounds 3.5 to 4, after three years of delays. So far, 6.4GW of renewables capacity across 102 projects has won support through the scheme. Future plans will be driven by the updated Integrated Resource Plan (IRP), which outlines the country's planned generating capacity, and is currently sitting with the labor union, Nedlac. The March 2019 draft IRP closes the door to new nuclear power capacity until 2030, but also imposes limits for renewables technologies. In fossil fuels, the government has plans to procure more coal and gas capacity through dedicated IPP programs.

South Sudan does not offer any specific clean energy incentives, nor has it submitted a Nationally Determined Contribution in the framework of the Paris Agreement. The country lacks a clear energy policy altogether, with the only relevant previous piece of legislation being the 2011 'South Sudan Strategic Development Plan'. This sets out electrification targets and was in force until 2016, but a new official plan has yet to succeed it. The country's ongoing fragile security situation and unrest has diverted governmental focus away from clean energy deployment.

Sudan does not yet offer any clean energy incentives. A public-private partnership (PPP) law, renewable energy act and import-duty exemptions for solar components have been in the planning for some time, but are stuck at various stages along the legislative pipeline. Furthermore, the 2001 Electricity Law is due to be overhauled, but little progress has been made to date. Aside from Sudan's plan for renewables to account for 20% of generation by 2030 as part of its nationally-determined contribution, the government has not explicitly issued any further national objectives. With no utility-scale renewables commissioned to date, Sudan still has a long way to go to deploy clean energy.

Tanzania's energy policy is underpinned by three targets: 2021 goals for 4,915MW of power generating capacity and a 50% renewables generation mix, and a 75% electrification target in 2025. However, since setting these targets in 2016, Tanzania's installed capacity has increased to just 1,461MW, fossil fuels still make up 60% of generating capacity and the country has a 33% electrification rate. Two tenders announced in September 2018 for 150MW of solar and 200MW of wind would have gone a long way in reaching both targets, but both were canceled. The country has a standardized power purchase agreement structure for projects smaller than 10MW ' this will need to be adapted to large-scale projects in order for Tanzania to come close to reaching its targets.

Togo passed its first renewable energy development law in July 2018, which aims to reach 50% renewables in the national energy mix by 2030. The government also published a roadmap to reach 100% electrification by the same year, thanks to the addition of 108MW of renewable energy projects including solar PV (50MW), hydro, 315 mini-grids and the distribution of 550,000 solar kits. The country is in the process of setting up an open, transparent and easy-to-navigate regulatory framework. The renewable law, published in August 2018, came a year after the launch of the AT2ER (Agence Togolaise d'Electrification Rurale et des Energies Renouvelables), and was followed by a series of decrees detailing the rules that renewable energy project developers should follow.

Tunisia aims to move toward a cleaner power matrix and jump from 3% of renewables generation in 2016 to 12% in 2020, rising to 30% by 2030. Two separate auction regimes (authorization for smaller projects and concession for larger projects) are the main instruments to achieve the objectives. Under the authorization regime, the government contracted 64MW of PV capacity in 2017 and 70MW in 2018, whilst a further 70MW is under tender. Under the concession regime, Tunisia announced in 2018 that it will contract another 500MW of wind plants, and contracted 500MW of PV in 2019. Project deadlines vary between 1H 2021 and end-2022 and the winners will secure a 20-year PPA with the state-owned utility STEG. In addition, retail electricity consumers in Tunisia that have renewable energy facilities can connect and deliver surplus generation to the grid, in return for payment from STEG.

Uganda has achieved its renewable energy generation target and is set to achieve its renewable capacity target by the end of 2019. The country currently generates more than 90% of its power from renewable sources, including large hydro and biomass. Uganda currently has more than 1,000MW of renewables connected to the grid and expects to have more than 1,700MW commissioned by the end of 2019. Uganda's highly-successful Global Energy Transfer feed-in tariff (GET FiT) program launched in 2014, becoming the first competitive auction program for renewables in East Africa.

Zambia is a politically-stable country with a fairly light-handed regulatory framework for energy, although it has non-cost reflective retail tariffs. The country has ambitions to diversify its power mix and improve access to electricity, and its policies reflect this. In mid-2016, Zambia's Scaling Solar program awarded 81MW in its first round, yielding some of the lowest solar prices in sub-Saharan Africa. Both winning PV projects, the 34MW Ngonye and 56MW Bangweulu, begun commercial operations in 2019.  However, the next Scaling Solar auction round is on hold, pending the completion of a cost of service review of the state-owned utility, Zesco. Zambia also awarded 120MW of PV capacity under the first round of the GETFiT scheme, with a second round due in 2019-20 for 100MW of small hydro. Along with the planned dissemination of 500,000 solar home systems and installation of 350,000 solar water heaters, Zambia is taking positive steps toward increasing access to modern energy services and meeting the growing demand for electricity.

Zimbabwe's target to reach 1GW of renewables by 2025 (excluding large hydro) is ambitious, given that the country is essentially starting from zero renewable generation at present and it also faces ongoing issues with unmet demand and load-shedding. The target is not officially in place and is therefore non-binding. Solar is the most promising form of renewable generation and several IPPs have signed PPAs. In July 2019, the government announced that all new construction projects in the country must include solar. This should significantly boost the solar market going forward. ZPC, the central utility, has plans for a 300MW solar project, which would be the first renewable project in its portfolio, but progress has been slow.

Afghanistan's renewable energy policy targets the development of 4.5GW-5GW of capacity by 2032. The policy is divided into two terms - Term 1 (2015-2020) which aims at creating a favorable environment for the growth of the renewables sector and Term 2 (2020-2032) which will actually achieve the capacity targets. Going by current growth, the targets are very ambitious, given that the Term 1 deadline is coming up in just two years. There are no feed-in tariffs, subsidies or rules and regulations for the renewable energy sector - all these were a part of Term 1 goals but there hasn't been any success in achieving them.

Aiming for a 21% share of renewable energy in power generation by 2020 and 26% by 2025, Armenia's target is very ambitious given the current share of 13%. While the country is likely to achieve its small hydro capacity targets, it is a long way off from meeting its onshore wind, geothermal and solar PV targets. Since 2007, Armenia offers a technology-specific feed-in tariff with a 15-year power purchase agreement to incentivize clean energy deployment. However, these tariffs are quite low, with the wind tariff recently halved, thereby stalling project discussions with developers. Renewable energy equipment is exempt from customs duties and the value-added-tax may be adjourned for up to three years following an official request. Commercial and residential self-generators can utilize their own electricity and feed excess power into the grid, selling at 50% of residential prices (or even 100% in the case of small hydro). This was limited to 150kW until 2018 and increased to 500kW in 2019.

Azerbaijan's renewables market is still in the early stages of development. The country has set itself a low target for build-out by 2020, which can be achieved with four projects that are currently planned or under discussion. Feed-in tariffs are negotiated on a project-by-project basis, as rates paid by the state-owned utility for renewables generation would otherwise make investment unprofitable. Oil and gas companies, which have long operated in Azerbaijan, may well be among the most serious contenders in the medium-term. Larger utilities from abroad have been slow to show interest in investing in renewables in the country.

Bangladesh has an ambitious policy to increase the renewable energy generation share to 10% by 2020, including large hydro, from less than 2% in 2018. It will need 2GW of renewable projects to meet this target, and is also promoting a net-metering policy to spur investments in the rooftop solar segment. The development of projects on the ground, however, is very slow as independent power producers struggle to secure land for setting up plants and right-of-way to build transmission lines. Some renewable projects have secured fairly generous feed-in tariffs set by regulators, but delays in getting project approvals means that most of these may be cancelled. Regulators want to conduct auctions to build projects in a solar park but, so far, little progress has been made.

Cambodia has few clean energy policies in place today, and there are no incentives such as feed-in tariffs or net metering which could support residential or commercial solar. However, the Asian Development Bank has been working with Electricit Du Cambodge (EDC) to help launch a pilot solar auction to procure 100MW. On February 13, 2019, the EDC invited bids for the first leg of the auction: a 60MW project in Kampong Chhnang province. Another 40MW will be tendered in late 2019 or in 2020.

TThe world's largest power market is undergoing a series of changes that will impact both generation and retail. For renewable energy, generous feed-in tariffs that were the norm for much of the past decade are coming to an end. Build out of subsidy-free capacity and competitive auctions to allocate the remaining subsidy will be the two separate tracks driving new build in 2019 and 2020, after which subsidies are likely to be completely eliminated. Retail liberalization now allows wind and solar assets to sell power ' albeit for a short duration of less than a year ' directly to large-end users. A renewed push for the 'prosumer' (producer+consumer) model will allow 1.6GW of distribution-grid-connected projects to serve neighboring loads.

India was the world's largest renewables auction market in 2018. Auctioned capacity for solar and wind was at 19GW, a significant ramping up since 2017, as the country aims to reach 175GW of installed renewables by 2022. Wind capacity addition of 2.3GW in 2018 was 44% lower than 2017, partly due to a switch from feed-in tariffs to reverse auctions in early 2017. On the other hand, solar saw its best year-to-date with 9GW(AC) being installed in 2018 across utility-scale projects, rooftop solar and off-grid solar. Renewables policies have generally been stable but the government has had to balance competing objectives of achieving low tariffs, indigenization of the value chain and increasing the share of renewables.

Indonesia aims to generate 23% of its total electricity from new and renewable energy sources by 2025, up from around 9% in 2018. New and renewable energy sources, however, also include technologies like nuclear, hydrogen, coal bed methane, gasified coal and liquefied coal. Nevertheless, this target is ambitious, given the low levels of finance committed to renewables in the recent past. The Electricity Supply Plan (RUPTL) 2019 sets goals to add 6.1GW of hydro, 4.6GW of geothermal, 4.1GW of solar, 3.5GW of pumped storage and 1.7GW of other renewables over 2019-28. New solar and wind projects are to be awarded through a limited tender process. Bid prices are restricted to 85% of the regional generation cost, if it exceeds the national average. If the regional cost is less than the national average, tariffs can be negotiated between the national utility Perusahaan Listrik Negara (also known as PLN) and the developer. The process to participate in the tender is not clear and there is little clarity on the template of the power purchase agreement. Additionally, the renewable energy projects have to be under a build-own-operate-transfer (BOOT) model. These policies have increased risks and have rendered renewable energy projects less attractive to investors.

Kazakhstan has a goal of generating 3% of its electricity from renewable energy sources by 2020, increasing to 10% by 2030. The country offered feed-in tariffs to promote renewables development, but under the coaching of European Bank for Reconstruction and Development (EBRD), the International Renewable Energy Agency, and the United States Agency for International Development (three institutions that have advised the country on how to speed the development of renewable energy penetration or are lending money with which to do so), it has migrated to an auctions-based system. While nearly 1,000MW of capacity was auctioned in 2018, a second year auction only seeks an additional 255MW. Ambitious renewable energy targets are inconsistent with policy to contain future tariff increases. Without passing on high renewable energy costs, funding these subsidies will remain a challenge.

Kyrgyz Republic generates less than 2% of its power from renewable energy sources (excluding large hydro), but aims to increase this share to 10% by 2021. The main policy enabling this is its 'Forty Steps to a New Era' program, which calls for the construction of 11 new small hydro power plants, with a capacity of about 160MW, over the next three years. Small hydro plants are able to take advantage of a feed-in tariff offered by the energy regulator and are exempt from most value-added tax and customs duties. The country only has about 80MW of small hydro installed now. Large hydro accounts for nearly 80% of Kyrgyz Republic's installed power capacity. Around 45% of country's power plants are operating beyond their useful life and would need replacement over the next few years.

The government of Laos has billed the country as the 'battery of Asia', eager to capitalize on its abundant hydroelectric resources and small population to export energy to its larger, fast-growing neighbors. Accordingly, it has focused its attention on building large hydro power plants that, in many cases, send power directly across its borders to Thailand or Vietnam. The government is targeting a 30% share for non-hydro renewables in the power mix by 2025. EDL-Gen Solar Power Company was established in 2015 with the aim of building 100MW of solar by 2020. This will not be enough to achieve the 30% target. The government has not announced any further strategies yet on how it is planning to achieve the target.

Malaysia passed the Renewable Energy Act in June 2011, and followed it up with the Renewable Energy (Feed-in Approval and Feed-in Tariff Rate) Rules in the same year. Solar PV, small hydro, biomass and biogas projects were allowed to apply for feed-in tariffs. In 2016, the government announced rules for auctions of large-scale solar power projects (greater than 30MW capacity). The country has been able to hold three rounds of auctions to date. In 2018, Malaysia announced that it targets 20% of its electricity generation from renewable energy sources by 2025. In May 2019, the minister for Energy, Science, Technology, Environment and Climate Change, Yeo Bee Yin, said that Malaysia is also looking to adopt a more ambitious goal of moving to 100% renewable energy, without specifying a timeline for this goal. The new targets are ambitious, but lower than those set by other countries across the world. Successive governments have however ensured continuity in the country's push to promote renewable energy.

The government aims to reach 20% renewable energy generation share by 2023 and 30% by 2030 ' a significant leap from the 2018 level of 7%. The legal foundation was laid by the Law on Renewable Energy (2007), while the National Renewable Energy Program (2005-2020) provided official targets and incentives for global investors in the sector. The principal incentive is the relatively generous feed-in tariff (Fit): the price paid under the power-purchase agreement negotiated with the National Dispatching Center. In addition, such FiTs are denominated in U.S. dollars and paid in tugrik, based on actual exchange rates, helping eliminate currency risk. Tax exemptions are also available for solar PV and wind turbines.

Myanmar adopted a National Electrification Plan that calls for 50% electrification by 2020 and 100% by 2030. Progress has however been slow, with electrification rate reaching only 40% by 2018. The country does not have a renewable energy target or policies in place, but is in the process of drafting a new law to aim for 8% share of renewables by 2020, and 12% by 2025.

Nepal established the Alternative Energy Promotion Centre (AEPC) in 1996, with an initial focus on household supply, such as small hydropower access and biogas for cooking. The renewable energy policy was introduced in 2006, followed by the National Rural and Renewable Energy Program in 2012, targeting 25MW mini and micro hydro, 600,000 solar home systems as well as setting goals for biogas, water pumps and solar cookers. The subsidies started in 2012 were generous and ambitious, but the program has not added much capacity in the renewables sector. On the contrary, high subsidy rates have prevented the country from attracting complementary investments on the basis of market. The policy in force today ' Renewable Energy Subsidy Policy 2016 ' is relatively stable and clear for market entrants. Technologies qualifying for subsidies include mini- to small-hydro, solar PV, solar thermal, biogas, biomass, wind and solar-wind hybrid systems. It provides different levels of subsidy to areas with national grid access and off-grid installations. The rates are rarely adjusted, and not cost-reflective. No auctions or power market is in place. Many plans have been initiated to attract investments, but progress has been slow.

Pakistan has seen a rapid expansion of renewable energy since 2015, with some projects built under the bilateral China-Pakistan-Economic-Corridor (CPEC) initiative, which is driving Chinese funding to infrastructure projects in Pakistan. The government led by Prime Minister Imran Khan seems to be committed to the CPEC and clean energy, with an ambitious new target of 30% generation from renewables by 2030, and a further 30% from large hydro. The previous government had already decided on moving to an auctions-based regime instead of relying on feed-in tariffs, but little action has been taken on this initiative to date.

Two major laws ' the Electric Power Industry Reform Act (Epira) and the Renewable Energy Act ' have incentivized growth of renewables in Philippines. However, the implementation of these laws has been slow, and the energy targets that were part of these laws were missed. The country now aims for 15.3GW of renewables capacity by 2030, and total generating capacity of about 65GW by 2040.
A feed-in tariff has spurred over 1GW of renewable energy installations, and behind-the-meter policies have achieved 50MW of distributed resources. In July 2019, the Department of Energy said that the implementation of Renewable Portfolio Standards (RPS) would be fast-tracked, which will likely spur renewable energy adoption.

The Singapore government has set goals to reduce emissions intensity, improve energy efficiency and expand solar PV installations. It is targeting up to 2GWp of installed solar capacity by 2030, of which around 200MW had been set up by the end of 2018. Much of the development is constrained to rooftop and floating solar as the city-state's lack of land resources (indicated by the high population density) has proved an obstacle for ground-mounted grid-scale development. Solar rooftop tenders have delivered over 116MW installed capacity across nearly 1,500 public housing blocks.

Sri Lanka recently approved a long-term electricity generation plan (2020-2039) which includes new coal plants, the preferred option of the utility Ceylon Electricity Board, and also envisages new gas and renewable energy plants, which is what the regulator Public Utilities Commission of Sri Lanka or PUCSL favored. The new generation plan increased the proportion of renewables and decreased the proportion of coal slightly, while doubling gas capacity compared to the last plan submitted in 2018. This indicates that gas might be what the country would settle for to balance interests of different parties. Sri Lanka's grid is isolated - having no connections with any of its neighbors yet - which also impacts future planning.

Taiwan's feed-in tariffs helped expand renewable energy capacity to 8.8GW by the end of 2018. The new administration, which came to power in 2016, launched an aggressive energy transition plan to phase out nuclear by 2025 while adding 25GW of renewables. Though most of the residents were in favor of extending the life of nuclear power in a referendum at the end of 2018, the administration is keeping to its promise of phasing out nuclear by 2025. Lucrative offshore wind feed-in tariffs (FiT) have attracted major European developers and financiers from Taiwan and overseas. The government's proposed steep cuts to 2019 FiT rates, though subsequently softened, demonstrated material revenue risks. Solar installations exceeded 1GW in 2018 on the back of strong rooftop promotion programs, though long-term challenges in land acquisition for utility-scale projects remain.

Tajikistan generates less than 2% of its power from renewable energy sources other than large hydro, and aims to increase this share to 20% by 2030. To support this goal, the government has called for the construction of small hydro and solar power plants and granted value-added tax and excise duty exemptions to renewable energy investors. Though these segments have yet to take off, its utilization of clean energy remains notable. Large hydro, for example, accounts for over 80% of Tajikistan's installed power capacity. The country's power system however fails to meet its electricity demand, particularly in winter months. Winter electricity shortages become severe due to high heating demand, a sharp reduction in imports of electricity and gas, and over-reliance on hydropower, which operates at a very low capacity in winter due to the freezing of rivers.

Thailand is the regional leader in total installed renewable capacity in Southeast Asia (SEA). It was the first country in SEA to implement a feed-in premium intended to spur investment and development of renewable energy projects. The generous feed-in premium and subsequent feed-in tariff programs implemented by the government successfully supported the growth of the renewables industry. By the end of 2018, cumulative installed solar capacity totaled 2.8GW and wind capacity slightly exceeded 1GW. The latest power development plan covering 2018-2037 targets an additional 18.6GW of renewable capacity in the next 20 years, with solar accounting for most of the addition, at 10GW. The country's Alternative Energy Development Plan (AEDP) is currently under revision.

Turkmenistan relies almost exclusively on natural gas for its energy needs. The state-owned utility, Turkmenenergo, controls all segments of the power market. The economy slowed down further in 2019, and the lack of financial resources is placing additional pressure on an already fragile system. While the government participates in some international forums for energy with the apparent intent of becoming more sustainable, it is not able to implement any changes or plans due to the condition of the economy.

Uzbekistan has a small renewables target for 2030, which it is on track to meet. However, this is not yet supported by legislation that would offer stable renewable energy growth. The regulatory framework is being worked on with the help of development institutions and there is no framework for feed-in-tariffs or auctions at present. A few renewable energy projects are being planned and interest is supported by the notable potential for changes in policy. Projects at present are negotiated with government authorities on an ad hoc basis. The country has agreed to build its first nuclear power station, with Russia's Rosatom, which once completed, will offer stability to a weakened power network.

Vietnam's revised Power Development Plan VII (PDP) targets 6.5% of electricity generation from renewables in 2020 from an earlier goal of 4.5%, and raised the 2030 target to 10.7% from 6%. In terms of capacity, the plan has a conservative target of 850MW of solar and 800MW of wind in 2020, but scales up to an ambitious 12GW solar and 6GW wind in 2030. 
To spur development in wind and solar, feed-in tariff (FiT) schemes were introduced. A wind FiT was first introduced in 2011 at $78/MWh, which failed to incentivize development. It was revised in September 2018, increasing the onshore wind FiT to $85/MWh and introducing an offshore wind FiT of $98/MWh, with a commissioning deadline of November 1, 2019. The Ministry of Industry and Trade (MOIT) first introduced a solar FiT of $93.5/MWh in April 2017. The scheme expired on June 30, 2019 and the industry is awaiting the announcement of the FiT mechanism post June 2019.

Albania's national electricity target for clean energy is 38% of demand by 2020. Given its reliance on hydropower and a paucity of planned solar or wind projects, Albania's ability to meet this target is overly reliant on the unpredictable hydrological cycle. The country's 2017 National Renewable Energy Law seeks to incentivize solar, wind, and small hydro generation through feed-in tariffs. Self-generation incentives have been promised, but details are lacking in the absence of secondary legislation.

Bosnia and Herzegovina (BiH) is split into two political entities ' the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina and Republika Srpska. The two regions have separate governments and determine energy policy independently. Each region has a separate feed-in tariff. These schemes have only encouraged the build-out of smaller plants. State utilities have negotiated deals for larger wind farms directly with government. Self-generation is encouraged by offering a premium for the electricity produced. The country also has a target for renewable energy share in gross final energy consumption set through its National Renewable Energy Action Plan submitted to the European Commission. The country aims to reach 40% renewable energy by 2020. The target has already been surpassed due to BiH's significant large-hydro capacity.

Renewable energy installations in Georgia are driven by winter supply constraints and energy diversification concerns rather than the need to reduce carbon emissions. Most of the country's electricity is produced from hydro and natural gas. There are plans for 600MW of wind projects, but these are in the approval stages. The government introduced a residential net-metering program for small-scale solar, but uptake has been limited. Most policy activity in the power sector is market liberalization to align with European Union requirements. The process is under the control of the Georgian National Energy and Water Supply Regulatory Commission (GNERC), the independent energy regulator.

In April 2017, the Republic of North Macedonia amended its National Renewable Energy Action Plan, lowering its target to source 28% of generation from renewable sources by 2020 to an achievable 24%, due to a recalculation of historical biomass use in their baseline. It also pushed the original 2020 target to 2030. The country has moved to feed-in premiums for large solar projects, while wind and small hydro projects are eligible for feed-in tariffs. A government-supported feed-in-tariff is the price that is paid to a generator per MWh fed into the grid, a feed-in-premium is a much smaller amount paid per MWh fed into the grid. A feed-in-premium is meant to supplement other revenues that a generator is assumed to be receiving, such as a power price from the free market. Electricity offtakers are required to purchase the producers' generation for the agreement's duration. Small-scale solar projects await the publication of rules with details on how they will be compensated for supplying electricity to the grid.

Moldova's 2013 National Renewable Energy Action Plan targets an overall 17% share of renewables in 2020 final energy consumption, with 10% of electricity demand met by renewable energy sources. It has enacted a tender-for-renewables policy under which the first power auction was to occur by the end of 2019. The government has incorporated the European Union's third energy package and adopted legislation and regulations to meet the requirements of the Energy Community, a group of southeastern European nations seeking to join the European Union's energy market and grids. Renewables benefit from exemption from the value added tax (VAT) on import, purchase and installation in Moldova. Clean energy self-generation incentives are restricted to net metering in limited cases.

Russia aims to increase the share of renewable energy in power generation from under 1% currently to 2.5% by 2024. In 2013, the country launched an annual renewables auction program to support solar, wind and small hydro. The target was originally set in 2009, at a more ambitious 4.5% by 2020, but this was revised down in 2013. Though the policy is due to expire in five years, it is widely expected that support for renewables will continue beyond 2024. The auctions are accessible to all, but a local partner is required for international firms. So far, they've attracted domestic and international players. However, much of the capacity awarded so far has not actually been built yet.

Since 2016, Serbia has offered a feed-in tariff to support wind, solar, biomass, biogas, hydro and geothermal. The feed-in tariff has been high enough to trigger capacity additions, but there are technology caps, to curb excessive build-out and ensure a manageable subsidy budget. Solar caps will be reached, albeit thanks to a low limit of 4MW for rooftop solar and 6MW for ground-mounted installations. Meanwhile, the larger wind cap, at 500MW is also expected to be met: 50% has already closed financing and the remaining 50% is expected to follow and be commissioned by 2020. The country is also planning renewable auctions, although their introduction has now been delayed until 2020. The feed-in tariff scheme has been extended twice to cover the gap.

Turkey has ambitious renewables targets across sectors ' it aims to reach 20GW of installed wind capacity, 5GW of solar and 1GW of geothermal by 2023, as well as 34GW of hydro. A boom in unlicensed solar development saw Turkey reach 5GW installed PV capacity by the end of 2018, while the 1GW geothermal target was reached in 2017 due to a generous feed-in tariff. While wind growth has been steady, the 20GW target would require the installation of more than 2GW a year of additional capacity, and policy support has been inconsistent. The site-specific 1GW Yeka auctions have yet to deliver any capacity, with cancelations and delays characterizing the process so far. The feed-in tariff is also due to expire after 2020, with no visibility on support for renewables after that point.

Ukraine aims to reach an 11% share of renewables in power generation by 2020. A generous feed-in tariff, tax incentives for the import of renewables-related equipment and a break on corporate tax for sales of electricity from renewable sources have spurred a surge in build since 2017.  Ukraine's new Electricity Law, which came into full effect in July 2019, establishes an ongoing framework to spur the growth of renewables and features a tender/auction program expected to start in late 2019. The law also liberalizes the power market, clarifies the offtaker's role and establishes a framework for standardized power purchase agreements.  This has boosted investor confidence, which was undermined by political instability over the past decade and territorial conflict with Russia.

Argentina published in 2015 the Law 27.191, in which it implements incentives and targets for renewables. The law created the Trust Fund for the Development of Renewable Energies (FODER) and provided tax incentives such as a VAT tax rebate and accelerated depreciation. According to the law, Argentina should have met 8% of its power demand with clean sources in 2018. The country fell short, serving 2.5% of its demand with renewable electricity. The policy established a gradual increase in the target each year, reaching 20% by 2025.
Under Resolution 281/2017, Argentina also established that large power consumers (>300kW) need to comply with targets established by Law 27.191 and may enter into bilateral corporate power purchase agreements. Projects subscribed to the scheme receive priority of dispatch. Following Law 27.191, the country implemented a series of renewable power auctions, RenovAr, to spur the development of clean energy projects. As of November 2018, RenovAr tenders have contracted a total of 4.7GW of renewables projects at large-scale. In May 2019, the country held a mini-tender aimed to small-scale projects and awarded 259MW of renewable projects across the country.

Bolivia has no comprehensive clean energy policy. Its National Development Plan 2017-2020 commits to a total installed capacity of 4.9GW by 2020, with a 1.4GW expansion in hydro capacity, 411MW of new wind, biomass, geothermal and solar and 1.1GW of new combined cycle and gas generation. In its Intended Nationally Determined Contribution to the U.N. Framework Convention on Climate Change, Bolivia commits to a goal of increasing its share of 'alternative' energy (wind, biomass, geothermal and solar) and other sources of energy (combined cycle) to 9% in 2030, up from 7% in 2017. In 2014, the country published Decree 2048 to encourage clean energy development.

Since 2009, Brazil has implemented reverse auctions to contract new clean energy generation capacity to supply the regulated utility market. The country pioneered competitive auctions, which led to over 28GW of renewable energy contracted, despite a tender hiatus from May 2016 to December 2017. Auctions started again in late 2017, and six rounds were held between December 2017 and October 2019. Sharp competition among project developers resulted in the lowest average solar auction price ever recorded in Brazil of $17.5/MWh in July 2019. In terms of other renewables incentives, retail electricity customers may install self-generation facilities, connect to the grid, deliver surplus generation and obtain compensation in the form of a subsequent billing credit. Distributed PV capacity reached 1GW in June 2019, doubling from 508MW at year-end 2018. However, the boom has prompted a rethink about appropriate regulation and retail tariff design and the country's regulator, ANEEL, is reviewing net metering rules.

Brazil attracted almost $56 billion in new asset finance for clean energy plants in 2009-18, by far the largest amount in Latin America over the period. Wind alone accounts for 54% of the total, while solar attracted 8%. The solar share should increase as developers secured almost 2.5GW in contracts in the 2017-19 auctions. Brazilian national development bank BNDES has played a major role in the development of the country's renewable energy market. The bank is the top global lender to clean energy, having disbursed $23.5 billion for renewable energy projects (excluding large hydro) between 2009 and 2018. However, the bank had changed the methodology it uses to calculate interest rates. Those are now slated to increase gradually for new loans until 2023 when they reach par with commercial levels. Between now and then, we expect BNDES's contributions to fade somewhat as private capital takes a more prominent role.

Retail electricity prices (in local currency terms) jumped an average of 81% between 2010 and 2018 for the three customer classes of commercial, industrial and residential. This was mainly due to inflation and decreased hydropower generation. In 2018, Brazil's retail tariffs were among the six highest in Latin America, at $195/MWh for commercial, $168/MWh for industrial and $196/MWh for residential. Commercial and industrial (C&I) customers with power demand greater than 500kW are eligible to purchase electricity from Brazil's deregulated wholesale market. Consumers with demand between 500kW and 3MW choosing this option must purchase wholesale power generated from incentivized renewable sources, including wind, small hydro, biomass and solar.

Brazil has the largest power market in Latin America, with total installed capacity of 162GW in 2018. The country's size, plentiful resources and conducive policies have made Brazil the region's main renewable energy market and one of the top 10 in the world. Its matrix remains highly reliant on hydropower, which accounted for roughly 65% of the country's generation in 2018. The heavy reliance on one source came at a high cost in 2014: a prolonged drought put Brazil's water supply and energy matrix into stress, exposing the market to costly generation from fossil-fueled plants. The hydro crisis emphasized the country's need for generation diversification. Auctions and net metering will continue to be crucial policies to develop Brazil's power sector. In terms of structure, the power market is fully unbundled and fairly evenly split between state-owned and private-sector players.

Latin America's largest economy is restrained by tepid growth as it limps back from a deep recession in 2015-16. Brazil's GDP expanded just 1.1% in 2018, and growth has remained near 1% for the past two and a half years. Sluggish growth is expected to persist through the end of 2019, with annual GDP growth forecast cut from 2.4% in March to 0.8% in September. Unemployment remains high, productivity lags and public debt has risen. Inflation has grown slower than anticipated and is expected to end 2019 at 3.6% vs. a target of 4.25%.

In October 2018, Brazil elected former military officer and far-right politician Jair Messias Bolsonaro of the Social Liberal Party (PSL) as its 42nd president. After a polarizing campaign, the results represent a repudiation of traditional politics in the country and of entrenched corruption, as well as a reaction to high levels of violent crime and ongoing economic woes. Bolsonaro's focus on the energy sector as a key driver of growth and development, as well as his emphasis on partially privatizing state-owned companies and regaining investor confidence could bring a bright future for renewables in the country.

El Salvador's government is focused on diversifying its power matrix and reducing its oil dependency by adding renewable energy capacity. Since 2013 the country has held three auctions, contracting 285MW of renewable capacity. It offers income and import tax exemptions to clean energy projects and guarantees priority dispatch to electricity generated from renewable sources.

To incentivize the development of renewable energy projects on the country, Guatemala has a net metering program which compensates renewable energy self-generators. It also has a target of generating 64% of electricity from renewable sources by 2032. 
In May 2019, Guatemala launched a tender for 110MW of solar generation. However, due to lack of feasibility studies and inconsistencies in the two bidders' proposals (Total Eren Guatemala S.A and Corporacin Klondike S.A.), the tender was canceled in August. The government intends to repeat the exercise but has set no timeline.

Improving access to energy has a central role in Haiti's president Jovenel Mose's program. Mose has abolished import duties on wind and solar generation products as well as solar appliances. The government has adopted the Scaling-up Renewable Energy in Haiti plan (SREP), with the advice of the Climate Investment Fund, and is preparing its first renewable energy law. 
In terms of utility-scale power generation, grants and projects have focused on restructuring Haiti's national power company Electricit d'Haiti (EDH). On a smaller scale, microgrid projects are appearing across the island. On September 13, 2019, the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) launched a tender for the construction of three microgrids in Capotille, Vallires and Mont-Organis cities, as part of its Rural Electrification and Women Empowerment project.
On January 18, 2018, Haiti announced it is opening its generation, transmission and distribution sector for private participation in eight regions of the country by awarding concessions. As of the end of September 2019, the government had opened pre-qualification process for companies interested in providing power services in Miragone, Les Cayes and Caracol.

Honduras' Country Vision Plan 2010-2038 establishes a 60% target of renewable energy generation for 2022. Generation from solar energy has more than doubled from 2015 levels, reaching 993GWh in 2018, or 11% of generation. Decree 70-2007, published in June 2007, guarantees priority dispatch to electricity generated from renewable sources. Renewable energy is also eligible for exemption from taxes on income, import value and sales.

Jamaica seeks to decrease its oil dependency and improve its energy security by diversifying its electricity mix. It was the Caribbean's first country to hold clean energy-only auctions. The country's National Energy Plan 2009-2030 calls for 20% of its electricity generation to come from renewable sources by 2030. Private utility Jamaica Public Service (JPS) has responsibility for generation, transmission, and distribution on the island (the government owns 20% of the company). Other players may enter the market as independent power producers (IPPs) and sell electricity to JPS.

Energy reforms in Mexico that have transformed the power sector have also included strong support for renewable energy. Mexico in 2012 established a mandate to generate 35% of power from clean sources by 2024. It set up a Clean Energy Certificates (CEL) market in 2014, the main incentive for clean energy. The clean energy target began at 5% in 2018 and will increase gradually to 13.9% in 2022.
Implementation of key policies remains a work in progress. Competition in the qualified supply and wholesale markets is in its infancy. The CEL market only entered into force in 2018, posting supply far below mandated levels. Certificate market demand, essentially a proxy for the total GWh of renewable power that will need to be delivered for Mexico to meet its clean energy goals, is expected to total approximately 13.7 million CELs in 2018, rising to 16.5 million in 2019 and 21.4 million in 2020, according to projections from the Secretariat of Energy (SENER). 
After three successful long term renewables auctions over 2016-17 featuring record low prices and contracting a total of 19.8TWh of clean power, 1.8GW of firm capacity, and 20.6 million CELs, President Lopez Obrador canceled Mexico's fourth long-term clean power auction in January 2019. While the new president's electricity plan shows support for renewables in general, his election has cast uncertainty over the sector.

Nicaragua's Ministry of Energy and Mines updated in January 2017 the national Plan for Electric Generation Expansion 2016-2030, with a non-binding 73% renewables generation target (including large hydro) by 2030. The plan also establishes interim renewables goals of 55% by 2018 and 64% by 2023. In 2018, the country reached a 58% share, with wind and geothermal the most representative renewable sources with 17% each. Renewable energy developers enjoy a full range of tax breaks, including import duty, VAT and income tax exemptions. Furthermore, on January 2018, the government of Nicaragua approved rules for net metering. It allows self-generators of up to 5MW of installed capacity to sell surplus electricity to Nicaragua's distribution companies.

Panama's efforts to promote the development of renewable energy projects includes tax incentives, such as the exemption from VAT and import duties, and an income tax credit that varies from 25% to 50% of the project depending on its size. Panama also has a feed-in tariff program that pays a 5% price premium to renewable electricity generators and a net metering system that allows renewable energy self-generators to accumulate credits in kWh up to 25% of their production. 
In February 2018, the Electric Transmission Company (ETESA) announced that, due to changes in the law, there will be no specific tenders for renewable energy. Instead, all kinds of generation will compete with each other. Furthermore, ETESA said that each technology will be evaluated based on its pollutants and their associated costs.

With nearly all of its electricity demand met by three large hydro plants totaling 8.8GW, Paraguay has had little incentive to develop a policy framework for other energy sources. In fact, the country exports more electricity than it consumes. The only clean energy policy incentive in Paraguay is a biofuel blending mandate for gasoline and diesel.

Technology-specific auctions have been essential for renewables deployment in Peru. In 2008, under decree No. 1002, the government established auctions to contract on-grid renewable capacity every two years. Since then, four auctions have been carried out, resulting in 71 project developments totaling 1.34 GW of biomass, small hydro, solar and wind. Peru also offers priority dispatch to clean energy plants and 20% accelerated depreciation for renewables projects.
Peru held an auction for off-grid solar in November 2014 to contract up to 500,000 off-grid PV systems. Ergon, the only winner, announced that will develop 150,000-200,000 systems by 2034, when the investment contract expires. As of July 2019, Ergon had commissioned nearly 134,000 systems. Peru was among the first countries to hold off-grid energy auctions.

Uruguay is the Latin American country with the highest penetration of clean energy generation. In 2018, 36% of the total power produced in the country came from wind and solar plants. This is a result of strong clean energy policies and the launch of the National Energy Plan, which established that 15% of the country's energy supply should come from renewable sources by 2015. Furthermore, the plan mandates the addition of 300MW of wind capacity and 200MW of biomass to the national grid by the same year. The goal was achieved one year before the target date and in 2015 the country had 857MW of wind and 425MW of biomass installed. In 2018, Uruguay's proportion of clean energy on the national grid was of 44%, excluding large hydro.

Egypt hopes to reach 20% renewables in electricity generation by 2022 (although this target was pushed back two years later than initially planned). Renewables build is finally gathering momentum. Support programs have helped spur development: despite a less-than-successful first round, the feed-in tariff, which has now closed, secured some 1.5GW of PV capacity. The tenders for engineering, procurement & construction contracts have been responsible for most renewables deployment to date because they have principally been attached to cheap financing from international development banks. In contrast, the tender scheme for build-own-operate (BOO) contracts has faced delays and changing specifications, while the bilateral and net metering systems have seen little-to-no uptake, principally because of the low electricity tariffs. The most recent auction program replaces the feed-in tariff, and the first round began in 1H 2018 for a BOO contract to build 600MW of PV capacity. Consortia comprising one global renewables player plus a local player dominated the bidders.

Iraq aims to generate 10% of its electricity from renewable sources by 2020 under the country's Integrated National Energy Strategy (INES). The Ministry of Energy is unlikely to achieve this target having already fallen behind on its plan: it has identified 13 potential locations for developing PV projects in Baghdad, Anbar and four other provinces as part of its investment strategy. The ministry offered a 15-year fixed feed-in tariff of $35/MWh and has outlined 2.7GW of potential PV projects. However, unclear investment and operation laws in the electricity sector and a lack of support from international financial institutions are deterring investment in renewables.

Jordan's National Energy Strategy plan aims for the country to generate 10% of its energy needs from renewable sources by 2020. Since launching, the plan has already seen 1,328MW of renewable projects come into operation, 636MW of which in 1H 2019. Following the completion of a third auction round in October 2018, the government suspended the program to give time to National Electric Power Co. (Nepco) to complete a new power sector plan reviewing the technical feasibility of integrating a larger share of renewables. Despite this temporary freeze linked to grid capacity constraints and the introduction of a 35% local content requirement in round three, stable policies and transparent incentives have allowed Jordan to become a regional leader in renewable energy.

Kuwait's 2030 Energy Strategy sets out to secure 15% of electricity generation from renewable energy sources by 2030. Even though the energy mix remains largely hydrocarbon-based, progress has been made in the past years with the deployment of solar (both PV and solar thermal) and onshore wind projects. And more larger-scale projects are either under development or in the pipeline. The 15% target is achievable if the government continues its efforts in investing and supporting renewable energy. The development of renewable energy is in line with the country's overall goal of freeing up fossil fuels for more value added sectors like oil refining and petrochemicals, which makes the policy more likely to be stable and consistent.

Lebanon aims to generate 12% of electricity from renewable sources by 2020, have 5GW of renewables installed and a 30% share of renewables in final energy consumption by 2030 under the National Renewable Energy Action Plan. It has made headway toward this target, with 380MW of solar and wind projects signing PPAs to date. However, administrative bottlenecks have delayed financial close and the start of construction. The tenders for 300MW of PV-plus-storage and 500MW of onshore wind projects were under instruction as of September 2019. Government support for renewables is stable ' the elections in 2018 maintained the political status quo, and renewables benefit from cross-party support. The downside to this is that there is little chance the severe underinvestment and frequent blackouts that plague the power sector will be addressed soon.

The Sultanate has ambitious plans to transition to a cleaner and more sustainable energy policy, with a target of 16% of electricity generation derived from renewable sources by 2025 and 30% by 2030 (starting from close to zero in 2018). Several renewable energy projects have been announced, tendered or are under construction, including utility-scale solar and wind plus a smaller waste-to-energy plant. In addition, incentives and an implementation plan are in place for a rooftop solar PV rollout among residential customers. Relative to other countries in the region, Oman has lagged behind in its implementation of diversification policies. The move to renewables is motivated by financial opportunity around selling its fossil fuels in the market rather than a climate-conscious focus.

Saudi Arabia has ambitious plans to develop clean energy, as embodied in its National Renewable Energy Program (NREP). This strategic initiative falls under the country's Vision 2030, and aims at increasing renewable energy capacity to 9.5GW by 2023, from 142MW currently, as part of its roadmap to diversify the domestic power supply and catalyze economic development. In early 2019, the solar component of the policy was expanded by almost four times: it is now targeting 20GW of solar by 2023 instead of 5.9GW, and as much as 40GW by 2030. As part of phase one of the NREP, the country's first utility-scale solar project in Sakaka, totalling 300MW, was awarded in 2018. In January 2019, EDF and Masdar won a contract to construct a 400MW wind plant in Dumat Al-Jandal. In 2019 alone, Saudi Arabia has invited bids for over 2GW of solar capacity.

The U.A.E. has set itself the goal of reaching a 50% share of renewable energy in the generation mix by 2050. Given the federal structure of the country, individual emirates have each determined their own objectives. Abu Dhabi and Dubai are shooting for 7% by 2020; both have also put renewables projects up for bidding. Dubai, for instance, issues tenders for renewables projects as part of its Clean Energy Strategy 2050, which aims to source 75% of power generation from clean energy by this century's halfway point. Despite the U.A.E.'s reputation as a regional trailblazer for clean energy, the country has not put in place any renewables incentives ' progress to date has largely been driven by state-backed projects.

The government of the Palestinian Territories has prioritized renewable energy as a means of meeting growing demand and circumventing limitations on land use and access. However, its 2020 goal of 130MW of renewables capacity is too ambitious, as just 18MW had been installed as of 2018. However, a generous feed-in tariff and net metering scheme are designed to incentivize rooftop solar.
