Palestine does not have any currently operational large-scale power plants and thus relies on electricity imports, mainly from Israel. The emphasis on renewables is considered a means of achieving greater energy independence.

Qatar aims to procure 200-500MW of solar energy by 2020. This represents about 5% of the national power demand. The target is ambitious given that the first renewable projects in the country are yet to be built. This means not only setting up the generation plants, but also amending and piloting new energy laws to accommodate the technology in a nation that has abundant alternative sources of power and no sustainability mandates. Pre-bids have been received for the proposed projects. While deployment might slip to 2021, there are further plans to expand solar capacity to 750MW.

Most renewables capacity consists of small-scale PV installations of around 15-20MW. The domestic clean energy industry attracted investments totaling $557 million over 2006-18, but no sizable deals have been concluded over the last four years. Finance has been lackluster for a number of reasons, including a national focus on developing new gas plants while modernizing the existing power fleet. Actors bidding into auctions must do so with a local partner and finance must be domestically sourced ' a challenge as Algerian banks remain reluctant to back clean energy undertakings, despite their involvement in a handful projects over past years.

With an energy sector dominated by large hydro plants, Angola has not received significant investment in utility-scale clean energy plants in recent years. However, its 2025 energy strategy will require substantial investment in renewables, much of which is likely to come in the form of concessional financing.

The MCA II plans to invest $375 million to modernize Benin's electric power sector and the government of Benin will contribute an additional $28 million. Although no large-scale renewable project is yet present in Benin, at least 75MW of solar PV is planned. The MCA II launched a tender for the construction of four PV projects totaling 50MW in July 2019. These will be developed under the build-own-operate-transfer (BOOT) model and will sell power to the country's state-owned utility Socit Beninoise d'nergie Electrique (SBEE) under a 20-year PPA.  In December 2017, the French Development Agency (AFD) financed the 25MW 'Defissol' PV project, which is planned to come online by the end of 2020. On top of new solar developments, the program hopes to restore the 500kW Y'ripao Dam, and install a second turbine to increase production to 1MW.

Only one grid-scale renewable energy project has been commissioned in Botswana to date ' the 1.3MW solar PV project located close to Phakalane. It was financed through a $12.5 million grant from the Japanese government. This is the only utility-scale renewable project to be financed in the last five years, making the current share of foreign investment stand at 100%. Botswana is open to foreign investment, but many project developers are unable to prepare the project proposals that meet the criteria necessary to attract international finance, according to the World Bank.

The largest clean energy investments to take place in Burkina Faso in recent years were the 33MW Zagtouli PV plant, commissioned in 2017, and the 15MW Essakane PV plant, which came online in 2018. Together, these deals totalled $115 million of investment. The Zagtouli project, which signed a PPA with Sonabel, Burkina Faso's utility, was supported by the EU and the AFD. The Essakane plant has a PPA with gold miner Iamgold and is partly financed by Banque Internationale pour le Commerce, l'Industrie et l'Artisanat du Burkina (BICIAB), a BNP Paribas Group subsidiary, suggesting that commercial actors are also willing to invest in solar in Burkina Faso. Additional actors are slowly entering the market in the context of the government's 155 MW solar programme, including French companies Quadran, GreenWish, GreenYellow and Urbasolar and Belgian companies, Syscom, Naange and Soltech.

There has been significant under-investment in the energy sector. As a result, the country has an extremely low electrification rate of 10% nationally and less than 2% in rural areas by end-2018. The country has also opened its energy sector to privatization. Uptake of this opportunity has been limited, but one notable investment in 2017 included a 7.5MW solar plant, in which Gigawatt Global signed a 25-year PPA with the national utility, Regideso. Other foreign investment in the energy sector in Burundi has primarily been made by the development banks. In 2019, the World Bank, European Bank for Reconstruction and Development, European Union, African Development Bank, Burundi's government and national utility Regideso raised $270 million to start building the 50MW Jiji-Murembwe hydro power plant. Investment in rural electrification is being undertaken by the Burundian Agency for Rural Electrification. The objective of this entity is to develop and implement rural electrification projects, including small-scale hydropower, solar and wind energy.

There are no examples of domestic commercial banks investing in renewable energy projects. The majority of finance that is available is from international creditors, mainly based in China. Of the renewable technologies, large hydro has received the most clean energy investment in Cameroon, with almost 8GW either announced or having secured financing as of September 2019. Some small-scale solar projects have also closed financing in recent years, particularly for rural electrification, but investment in megawatt-scale projects has yet to gain traction. Cameroon is open to private finance. The biggest investors have been international organizations such as the World Bank, which financed $784.5 million in 2018 for the Nachtigal hydropower project. Investors from China, including firms such as Eximbank, are active in Cameroon's hydro and solar sectors.

Clean energy investment has neither been a top priority for the state, nor has it been readily available. The majority, if not all, of clean energy financing has come from international development banks and Chinese companies, which are increasingly active in the country. Projects to date have focused on updating the existing infrastructure and generation assets, rather than expanding the fleet of clean energy generators. For instance, the China Gezhouba Group Corporation is involved in modernizing the Boali II hydropower plant, among other projects. This emphasis on upkeep as opposed to new-build is due to the ongoing conflict within CAR, which has destroyed much of the energy infrastructure, in addition to the lack of maintenance by indebted state-owned utility Enerca, as well as the general absence of supporting policies and financial means.

There are hardly any investments in clean energy in Chad, with all finance to-date exclusively coming from outside the country and disbursed at concessional rates. There are less active financiers than in neighboring countries, with the main actors being the EU, the World Bank and the Islamic Development Bank. After a delay of two years, the 60MW Djermaya Solar plant was the first utility-scale renewable energy project to be announced in the country in 2018. The EU is backing the project with a 6.35 million-euro ($7.3 million) grant. Funding is scarce. Indeed, the difficulties in securing financing were partly behind the repeated delays that affected Vergnet's 1.1MW wind farm at Amdjarass, which finally came online for initial testing in late-2017.

Renewable energy investments in the Congo remain few and far between. China Gezhouba Group and Sinohydro have been investing in hydropower projects, such as the 19.5MW Liouesso plant, as well as two prospective major dams in Sounda and Chollet. However, the plants have run into environmental and technical issues, making their future unclear. Finance for potential renewables initiatives would likely come from international donors, such as the French Development Agency, the African Development Bank and the World Bank, which have been involved with rural electrification projects in the country.

Investment in clean energy projects in the DRC has been limited for a number of reasons. The lack of a proper legal instrument to define the energy sector discourages investors from funding new projects. In addition, the dominance of the highly subsidized, state-backed company, SNEL, in the generation, transmission and distribution of power make the investment climate less competitive. The absence of government regulation and energy policy on renewable energy does not encourage long-term capital investment in the renewable energy sector. Hydropower remains the dominant form of energy generation, given the country's significant river resources ' notably the Congo River. The few announced solar projects are small-scale and linked to commercial mining activities or the telecoms industry.

Recent clean energy investment has largely been limited to large hydro. The 275MW Soubr dam, which began generating power in 2017, was backed by an 85% commercial loan with the Export-Import Bank of China. The country's first commissioned PV project reached financial close in October 2018. Germany's KfW Group will provide 36.7 million euros ($40.7 million) for the 37.5MW solar PV Boundiali project, which should be completed by the end of 2019. Currently, local financial institutions do not finance renewables and clean energy investment is likely to remain reliant upon concessional finance given the sector's immaturity.

Eritrea has so far attracted very little foreign investment. There is no framework for public-private partnerships, nor incentives to attract international interest. Following the historic peace summit with Ethiopia in July 2018, and the subsequent reopening of the border, relations between the two countries are gradually normalizing, which could create a more attractive business environment to investors. The only investments in clean energy to date are Aggreko's 29.5MW diesel-solar hybrid project at the Nevsun mine, UNDP's 0.825MW wind pilot in Assab, plus two solar mini-grids by Solarcentury (1.25MW) and E-Tech (2MW). Aside from Solarcentury's announcement of a further 12MW of PV capacity, there are no other clean energy projects in the pipeline.

The majority of clean energy investment in Ethiopia has gone to hydro, which makes up nearly 90% of power generating capacity, though wind and geothermal have also received investment in recent years. This investment has also been inconsistent year-on-year, usually correlating with the development of a large project. A lack of foreign currency reserves, due to high expenditure on big infrastructure projects, means domestic commercial and development banks play a much smaller role in the growth of the country's clean energy industry compared with neighboring countries. International development banks are picking up the slack ' traditional players like the World Bank, the Danish Energy Agency and the Japan International Cooperation Agency (JICA) all have boots on the ground and are actively involved in Ethiopia's clean energy market.

Clean energy investment has stalled over the last couple of years as the government embarked on the PPA review, which delayed most renewables projects. The majority of investment in renewable energy in Ghana has come from foreign sources, with the largest solar project (20MW) financed by Chinese investors. New investments into utility-scale renewables would be limited in the near term as the government is unlikely to approve new projects under the feed-in tariff scheme. On the other hand, the distributed solar sector startups have attracted some investments. These include PEG Africa, a pay-as-you-go solar company, and Redavia, an on-site solar financier and developer.

All energy investment to date has come from outside of Guinea due to the limitations of domestic finance. There have been no more than a few residential solar panels and mini-hydro plants installed, while capital has been directed instead into large hydro projects. The most notable investments to date are China Exim's $1.3 billion package for the 450MW Souapiti dam, Sinohydro's $812 million for the 294MW Kouokutamba dam and Sintram's $400 million for the 100 MW large hydro project. Further investments target electrification efforts, rebuilding the country's distribution network and investments in four new interconnector lines. Despite the lack of non-hydro renewables to date, there is growing interest in investing into solar PV projects, and several MoUs have been signed with private sector actors.

Clean energy investments in Kenya have been sporadic in the last decade, sustained by a small number of financings for geothermal and wind projects. Kenya recorded $1.4 billion of total investment in 2018, the highest since BloombergNEF started tracking it. This includes $233 million for Actis Kipeto Wind Farm from Overseas Private Investment, and $143 million from Kreditanstalt fr Wiederaufbau (KfW) and Agence Franaise de Developpement (AfD). The majority of financing for large-scale renewable energy projects came from development financing institutes and donor organizations. The distributed energy startups such as pay-as-you-go solar companies, microgrid and on-site energy developers received financing from more diverse financiers, including strategic investors, commercial banks and utilities.

Some 90MW of renewables are under development, with power offtake agreements in place. The 20MW NEO1 Solar project has been financed by the African Development Bank/World Bank, and the 70MW NEO2 Solar project has been financed and developed by the China's Exim bank. If they are completed, they will more than double Lesotho's fleet size. Lesotho's current installed capacity features 76MW of hydro, so it will retain a fleet that is 100% carbon free.

The lack of a transparent and uniform policy framework has hindered clean energy investment in Liberia. Commercial lenders are yet to enter the market, leaving only concessional agencies to support the limited roll-out of rural electrification projects. Independent renewable power producers are not active, despite policy allowing project operators to sell power to the state-owned utility. However, the country has attracted some foreign private-sector involvement; most notably Manitoba Hydro International, which led the refurbishment of the Mount Coffee Hydropower Plant under tender from the Liberia Electricity Corp.

Clean energy investment in Madagascar is so far limited, with the main source of finance coming from international development institutions. French developer Green Yellow developed the aforementioned 20MW PV plant, with support from the World Bank. In addition to development finance, domestic companies are joining forces with international partners in order to develop projects. For example, Switzerland-based meeco Group announced in mid-2019 plans to develop two 45-kilowatt solar installations in cooperation with Madagascan companies Groupe Filatex and Enelec.

Malawi's government has not yet made any clean energy investments. Almost all investment in the sector has come from abroad and renewable developers operating in the country are all subsidiaries of overseas companies. International development banks are a popular source of capital. Overall, investment doesn't seem to be growing, which could be due to high inflation and volatile exchange rates disrupting investor confidence. Malawi seems willing to experiment technology-wise, as PPAs have been signed for solar, wind and small hydro. Solar is the most commonly funded technology, and a PPA was recently signed for the country's first floating solar plant.

Most clean energy investments in Mali are international and concessional in nature, with a focus on off-grid projects. For example, the World Bank's hybridization program from 2014 to 2020 has a budget of $44 million, and a $19 million hybridization project by the Abu Dhabi Fund has been launched from 2015 to 2021. Moreover, the Islamic Development Bank in conjunction with Morocco's l'Office National de l'Electricit et de l'Eau Potable is building two solar plants with a capacity of 1.3MW and 1.5MW respectively. In early-2019, the Green Climate Fund and West African Development Bank announced a 4.83MW solar mini-grid project, which they are supporting with $38.9 million. In the case of Akuo's 50MW Kita solar project, a domestic commercial bank, Banque Nationale de Developpment Agricole du Mali, was involved in its financing, but this is the only case of commercial finance to date.

The government has overseen a steady increase in clean energy capacity since 2013 and has heavily relied on concessional funding, often from Persian Gulf donors. Highlights include the completion of several large PV projects, such as the 50MW Toujounine PV plant commissioned in November 2017, of which the Arab Fund for Economic and Social Development (AFESD) provided the majority of the project's $53 million total cost. Similarly, the AFESD is financing the development of the 100MW Boulenouar wind farm. Donors such as the French Development Agency and the EU are also active in clean energy through their efforts to improve electrification, notably the five-year RIM DIR program at a total cost of $13.4 million.

Moroccan solar tenders have stipulated storage requirements, in order to displace expensive generation from fuel oil currently used to meet Morocco's high evening peak demand. Concessional finance from the World Bank's Clean Technology Fund (CTF) has been key in kick-starting the Moroccan solar thermal industry. CTF and CTF MDB (co-financing) have totalled $1.3 billion across the Noor I-III and Noor-Midelt projects. This financing has in turn attracted a further $3.3 billion from MDB and development banks. Developer finance and assumed equity make up the remaining $874 million of the Noor solar thermal projects as of 2018. In contrast, Moroccan wind projects have been successful in attracting significant amounts of commercial finance. Lured by Morocco's world-class wind resource, commercial finance has provided some $894 million of the disclosed $1,762 million invested in the wind sector since 2011. Total investment in the Moroccan wind sector is expected to reach $3.7 billion by 2020

Mozambique has historically relied heavily on its large-hydro resources, with the broader power fleet seeing little investment over recent years. More recently, investment has been directed to developing the domestic natural gas sector, which has grown rapidly since 2015. In terms of clean technology, the last decade saw Mozambique receive limited investment in biofuels and small, but growing inflows into solar. Only international and national development organizations have financed Mozambique's clean energy sector. As of mid-2019, no commercial bank had provided investment to large-scale clean power plants in the country. The country's rural electrification agency, Funae, has developed mini-grid and pico-solar pilot programs in partnership with German aid agency GIZ and recently signed an agreement with Ignite Power to install individual solar energy systems in 300,000 homes in remote areas of the country. This will reach 1.8 million people over the next three years, and help the country achieve its objective of universal energy access by 2030, established via the Energy for All project (Projecto de Energia para Todos).

Solar PV is proliferating at a very rapid pace in Namibia, having roughly doubled its capacity each year between 2014 and 2018. Solar PV currently represents 13% of installed capacity. Solar PV's relatively low cost and high capacity factors have meant it has eclipsed investment in the wind fleet, which is comprised of two projects to date.
Most of the equity investment in energy projects built after 2015 has been put up by foreign companies such as Spanish IPP Alten Energias Renovables and Canadian Solar. Pipeline projects are owned by other international stakeholders such as EDF and Innosun. 
The government recently introduced ownership share rules that limit foreign equity ownership. For example, to qualify for Refit, each project has to allocate at least 30% ownership to disadvantaged local groups.
Debt has been provided by local Namibian banks as well as a diverse set of international development banks such as the African Development Bank, France's Association of Fundraising Professionals, and the Green Climate Fund.

International donors are the primary form of financing of renewable in Niger, because domestic banks do not fund these projects. The EU and AFD have joined forces on two such undertakings, spending a combined 28.5 million euros ($33 million) on a 20MW solar plant at Gorou Banda and 32 million euros on a yet-to-be-developed 19MW solar-diesel plant in Agadez. Other finance to date has mainly targeted electrification efforts such as the World Bank's $50 million National Solar Electricity Access Project (NESAP). Noteworthy funders in the off-grid space include the African Development Bank, the Islamic Development Bank, the West African Development Bank and the Abu Dhabi Fund for Development.

The Rural Electrification Agency (REA) is now commissioning projects under its Energizing Education Program (EEP), providing power for nine universities (seven will run on PV and two on gas) with funding for phase I ($29.7m) coming from Nigeria's sovereign green bond issued in 2017. The REA secured a further $350m loan through the World Bank and $200m (from the AfDB) for the Nigeria Electrification Project (NEP), totaling $550m. EEP phase 2 (19MW of PV) will receive $105m of this fund.
On the off-grid side, Daystar Power secured $10 million of equity finance to build 20kW-plus commercial and industrial projects in 2019, provided by Vera Capital and Persistent Energy Capital. Arnergy secured $9 million of equity finance to assist them in achieving their goal of 100MW of PV and 350MWh of lithium-ion storage by 2023, led by Breakthrough Energy Ventures. In 2018, the Bank of Industry (BOI) launched a 6 billion naira ($16.5 million) fund dedicated to solar projects.

Investment in clean energy in Rwanda has been volatile, despite consistent year-on-year growth in electrification. Most historical on-grid investment has been in hydro, natural gas and solar, but national utility Rwanda Energy Group (REG) has halted all permitting for future on-grid generation due to a current oversupply. Most future investment in Rwanda's energy market is expected to go toward the expansion of the grid to manage this oversupply, and to off-grid companies working with communities that will not have grid access in the near future. The financing matrix has been dominated by donor groups, most notably through a 200 million-euro loan from the European Union and the World Bank's Scaling Up Renewable Energy Program.

Recent years have seen an influx of renewables investment in Senegal and the Scaling Solar auctions will make a further contribution to helping the sector develop. Bid prices achieved in the auctions are indicative of the sector's growing maturity, even factoring in the power price depression due to the de-risking measures applied to projects. The aforementioned Tabia N'Diaye wind farm, which will be fully commissioned in 2020, was financed by $378 million of U.S. and Danish concessional funding. The sector will likely continue to rely on such development finance in the near-term.

Sierra Leone's economic recovery has been volatile since the country was declared ebola-free in 2016 and investment in new power generation has yet to pick up following the crisis. 
Concessional finance is the predominant source of capital to the sector, with funding from the World Bank and African Development Bank going to rural electrification projects and little private sector involvement. 
There is progress, however, in the pico-solar industry with the entrance of new companies. Some commercial lenders are now willing to finance larger projects that sell to the state-owned utility through a PPA.

Somalia owes significant debt to a number of international financial institutions, making it ineligible for international development aid and concessional financing from many other sources. Most international power sector investment in Somalia comes through short- and medium-term grants. A number of international organizations are undertaking large-scale projects focused on the power sector and energy security. Somalia also receives significant remissions from its diaspora, and in some cases, power producers can fund projects directly through this kind of investment.

Clean energy investment in South Africa has risen and fallen in line with the rounds of its auction program. Particularly high totals have occurred in years when winning projects reached financial close. In total, it attracted $20.5 billion between 2004 and 2018. The years 2014-17 averaged just $1.4 billion each, as the auction scheme was on standby, but 2018 saw more than $3.8 billion invested after the government finally signed PPAs for rounds 3.5 to 4. Two-thirds of the 2004-18 total was spent on solar projects, but this share compared to wind is skewed somewhat by capex-heavy solar thermal project investment. South Africa has the most diverse mix of investor types in a region typically reliant upon concessional finance for renewables projects. Of the $20.5 billion of asset finance since 2004, 45% has come from commercial banks and another 8% from private equity.

The growth rate of clean energy investments has been non-existent in recent years, with the majority of money invested directed at electrification projects by international aid organizations and foreign governments. Only 1% of the national population currently has access to electricity. The lack of transmission and distribution infrastructure further impedes any growth in clean energy investment. In contrast to the minimal installed capacity to date, there is a pipeline of large-scale energy infrastructure projects, most notably 2.1GW of large hydro. Many of these projects, however, are still lacking financiers.

Developers face difficulties in securing finance first and foremost in Sudan. There are no domestic banks which offer loans to developers investing in clean power, and years of international isolation coupled with crippling debts and a dire security situation have left international financial institutions reluctant to bankroll renewable energy projects. Difficulties in attracting donors has therefore translated into a lack of utility-scale renewables build-out. Although several projects have been announced, including 250MW of solar PV and four utility-scale wind farms totalling 320MW, all have struggled to secure funding and have therefore been cancelled or downsized. Investments have been limited to rural electrification schemes, with the United Nations Development Program and the government implementing separate initiatives to expand energy access through distributed renewables.

Like many Sub-Saharan African countries with inconsistent clean energy build, investment in Tanzania's clean energy space is sporadic. There is a healthy presence of international donor agencies like USAID, the World Bank and the African Development Bank, along with a number of domestic and international commercial banks. However, the Tanzania Electricity Supply Company (TANESCO) is an unreliable offtaker, sometimes compensating counterparties months late, and the government continues to support fossil fuel development and large hydro, such as the 2.1GW Stiegler's Gorge hydro project that is under development. So long as these two factors remain constant, renewables investment in Tanzania will continue to limp along.

There has been no clean energy utility-scale project in Togo yet, but existing rural electrification programs have received both international concessional finance and domestic commercial finance. The government is partnering with off-grid companies to offer solar home systems to rural customers, such as an agreement signed with BBOXX to deliver more than 500,000 PV systems to the rural population over the next five years under the so-called Cizo electrification program. Greenlight Planet, a U.S. company, signed an agreement to deliver more than 300,000 solar home systems under the same scheme, which has the support of local bank Union Togolaise de Banque (UTB). In 2018, the government signed an agreement with German Corporation GIZ, to accelerate rural electrification through training programs.

Tunisia has received little investment in utility-scale clean energy so far, but that is poised to change as over 1GW of auction-winning projects are expected to be commissioned by end-2022. International development banks have been the main debt providers for Tunisia's clean energy plants. The country's Fond de Transition Energetique (FTE) will invest 2.13 billion Tunisian dinars ($730 million) in energy transition projects over the next decade. The budget has grown significantly, from 177 million Tunisian dinars between 2006 and 2015.

Uganda continues to develop its abundant hydro resources, pushing the power sector further down a low-carbon trajectory. The country's outlook for procuring other renewables such as wind and solar is more mixed. Uganda organized a successful feed-in tariff program that led to development of the region's largest solar projects outside of South Africa. However, government decisions to contract several massive hydro projects have raised concerns about oversupply and dampened appetite for future wind and solar procurement.

Investment in Zambia's clean energy sector has shown positive growth in recent years. Between 2017 and 2018, the first Scaling Solar auction round attracted some $91 million of new asset finance, and the latest GETFiT round is expected to attract around $100 million in additional financing for small-scale PV projects. The country has received both international concessional and commercial support, notably from the Export-Import Bank of China that provided $130 million of debt, although the availability of finance from local debt providers has been limited.

Solar is the most commonly funded form of renewable energy, however overall investment in clean energy is low. Most of the capital for funding renewable development comes from foreign investors, but many are growing wary of risks. Renewable energy investors have asked for policy changes, such as more relaxed licensing rules for small producers. Prior to 2018, all businesses in Zimbabwe were required to be majority owned by a local, which dissuaded foreign participation in the renewable market. Overall economic stability is also a concern. The government outlawed all foreign currency in July 2019 and reintroduced the Zimbabwean dollar as the only form of legal tender. The Zimbabwe dollar was wiped out a decade ago due to hyperinflation and there are worries that this will recur.

All the renewable energy projects in the country have been supported by international donors. The World Bank and the Asian Development Bank have been the biggest contributors. There has not been much private sector involvement. The majority of investments have been made in the hydropower sector and although there are large plans to expand solar, nothing has come to fruition yet. Term 1 had set goals to provide incentives such as interest subsidies, soft loans, tax exemptions, etc. to increase private sector participation: this will need to happen before the end of 2020 to stay in line with the targets set.

Investment in renewable energy has been gradually increasing over the last few years, especially for solar PV installations. In terms of utility-scale projects, Spain's Fotowatio won Armenia's first large-scale auction to develop the 55MW Masrik-1 solar PV plant in 2018, financially backed by the 'Scaling up Renewable Energy Program' (SREP) and the World Bank. Developers Acciona and Access Power are exploring the development of large-scale wind projects; discussions have ostensibly stalled, however, following the slashing of the wind feed-in tariff from $0.09/kWh to $0.05/kWh in 2019. Since 2016, Armenia's energy ministry also manages a Renewable Resources and Energy Efficiency Fund to provide concessional financing for small-scale clean energy and energy efficiency projects.

The growth rate of renewables investment has been very small and largely focused on onshore wind and some solar. Investments have been supported by international development institutions, as have many of the regulatory and legislative reforms aimed at stimulating investment. Financing has been made available to local banks through the development institutions. Royal Dutch Shell and Equinor have expressed interest in supporting or investing in renewables development in the country. Their existing experience in Azerbaijan means that they have a distinct advantage due to their familiarity with the relevant power authorities.

Clean energy investment in grid-connected projects is starting to pick up in Bangladesh ' money is also flowing into some rooftop solar projects being developed by garment export companies. Apparel manufacturers are responding to pressure from purchasers in the U.S. and Europe that aim to decarbonize their supply chains. No wind projects have been installed in Bangladesh in many years. This could change, but land constraints, high equipment costs and lack of domestic supply chain are deterrents. Almost all renewables financing is provided by domestic lenders that in turn have access to credit lines from multilateral institutions and development banks. Infrastructure Development Company Limited or Idcol is the biggest recipient and disburser of renewable financing.

Like its neighbor Laos, Cambodia has directed power sector investment toward large hydro and coal-fired power plants, as well as transmission and distribution, to support its electrification target. Non-hydro renewables investment has been very slow to take off. However, a drought in 2019 that caused wide-spread blackouts for months in a row, made the government change direction. In February 2019, a 100MW solar tender kicked off, and in July 2019 the government approved another 140MW of solar projects, so investment is expected to increase rapidly now. There are few Cambodian banks or other financial institutions with the ability to support renewable energy projects at present, although some small banks, with assistance from Japanese parent companies, are hoping to increase the availability of domestic financing with capacity building.

China's decade long clean energy investment growth rally was interrupted in 2018 as major policy revamps slowed the speed of wind and solar installations. As the market awaits new policies, the first half of 2019 saw a further 39% dip in renewable energy investment to $28.8 billion, the lowest figure for any half-year period since 2013. BloombergNEF expects the solar auction in July to lead to a rush of new PV project financing, as well as several large offshore wind deals in the second half, to lift investment. Overall, China's clean energy investments are likely to stabilize, if not decline slightly, in the coming years on the back of stable new wind and solar installations.

Clean energy investment in India totaled $15.9 billion in 2018, with solar accounting for over 50%, followed closely by wind. This was 15% lower than 2017 as the costs of renewable energy projects continued to decline. BNEF tracked disclosed mergers and acquisitions deals of $2.8 billion in 2018 with a diverse mix of investors. The buyers include pension funds, domestic power producers, oil majors, Indian conglomerates, private equity firms and large foreign utilities. Initial public offerings though have taken a backseat as the major independent power producers such as Renew Power and Acme Solar Holdings have deferred plans after securing regulatory approval.

Indonesia has seen very limited investment in solar and wind power, with geothermal accounting for around 90% of the $800 million raised in 2018. The first large-scale wind and solar power projects in the country were commissioned in 2018. The projects were developed by Vena Energy, AC Energy and UPC Renewables, and financed by Overseas Private Investment Corp. and the Asian Development Bank. There is interest from commercial banks to participate in the renewables market but their involvement has been limited due to lack of investment-grade projects.

Since 2010, renewable energy has grown from 136MW (largely small hydro) to 530MW, with 80% of that capacity split between small hydro and solar photovoltaic systems. Onshore wind makes up the balance of renewables. Foreign institutions investing alongside the EBRD have contributed to the majority of new renewable projects.  One of the key priorities for the EBRD is supporting Kazakhstan's efforts in regulatory reform, addressing utility tariff setting and expanding renewable energy. Kazakhstan, in 2018, replaced its feed-in tariff with renewable energy auctions. The auction program, however, was pared back in 2019. The tenge depreciated 14% against the U.S. dollar in 2018, and currency risk continues to be a challenge for renewable developers, as well as for the bankability of the power purchase agreement with the Financial Settlement Company.

Kyrgyz Republic has not seen substantial investment in clean energy. The generation tariffs were designed to ensure investment recovery in up to eight years, but even this did not boost renewable energy installations. The country's installed small hydro capacity has remained flat in recent years and the deployment of other renewables, such as wind and solar, has been negligible to date. The World Bank and the Asian Development Bank are active in Kyrgyz Republic, and have provided grants to support various governmental clean energy and energy efficiency initiatives.

The power market in Laos is currently oversupplied with carbon-free hydroelectricity, leaving little incentive for the government or local companies to invest in non-hydro clean energy technologies. The bulk of recent investment ' in large hydroelectric facilities and a single coal-fired plant ' has been financed by Thailand and Vietnam for their own consumption. Only one 10MW solar project has been built to date in Laos, by a local company (EDL-Gen) but with significant support from international partners. China, Thailand, Japan and Vietnam are dominant players in the market. There is little to no domestic concessional financing available, and few banks in the country have the capacity to finance power projects.

The various policy initiatives like feed-in tariffs and auctions, along with tax and other incentives like the Green Technology Financing Scheme, have contributed to the growth of clean energy investments. About $0.5 billion went into renewable energy projects in Malaysia in 2018. Solar projects continue to garner the most interest, and biogas and small hydro have good potential, whilst biomass consists of mostly legacy assets. In June 2017, the country also issued the world's first green sukuk (Islamic) bond, which was used to finance large-scale solar projects awarded under the first auction for that technology. Investments could pick up in the next few years on the back of various auctions that the government holds from time to time, and the new scheme to promote rooftop PV projects.

Mongolia could potentially supply 8,000TWh of wind power and 5,000 TWh of solar power per year. However, renewable energy investment has grown slowly in Mongolia, amounting to just $200 million over 2010-16. Then 2017 set a new record, at nearly $100 million, with a mild slowdown again in 2018. Due to the nascent state of the renewables sector, the majority of investment has come from international development banks and foreign governments. The single largest investor is the European Bank for Reconstruction & Development (EBRD), responsible for a cumulative investment of $120 million. The largest local developer is Newcom Group. If the country is to meet its renewable energy target, it will need an extra push for new investments in the coming years.

Myanmar's clean energy investment has been dominated by overseas concessional finance from the World Bank and Asian Development Bank. Besides, utilities from China, Europe and Southeast Asian countries are investing and developing renewable energy projects in Myanmar.

Various funds have been set up by the government for the development of renewables, such as the Central Renewable Energy Fund and the Small Hydro Power Fund. However, the authorities admit that the lack of mobilization of credit and high dependence on subsidies has been hampering further investments in renewable energy. Nepal has huge potential for hydro, while some wind and solar power is installed. International donors such as World Bank, Asian Development Bank and United Nations Development Program (UNDP) have financed projects in the past, and policies and subsidies have been introduced to promote foreign direct investments as well. The country needs to attract more than 28 trillion rupees ($268 billion) in foreign capital to the energy sector by 2045, as quoted in Nepal's 2017 Investment Summit. China is becoming a new major investor in Nepal, with its own hydro technology and funding.

The total installed capacity of solar, wind and biomass is set to cross 2,000MW by the end of 2019. Wind has dominated Pakistan's renewable energy market, while investment in utility-scale solar has been slow to follow. Rooftop PV installations have picked up pace as a means to avoid frequent power shutdowns and save on electricity costs. Overseas investors active in Pakistan's clean energy sector include Three Gorges from China and Zorlu Enerji from Turkey. Most projects rely on some form of concessional financing.

The Philippines has seen scattered renewables investment. Geothermal and hydro initially made up most of the build, but spiking demand caused the government to lean toward conventional power. Epira officially opened up generation to the private industry in 2001. Since then the generation sector has been dominated by thee major players. The country has had difficulty financing renewables due to challenging policy as well as infrastructure constraints. The government allows no more than 40% foreign ownership in projects. For developers, becoming a Qualified Third Party (QTP) or an Independent Power Producer (IPP) is challenging, and bottlenecks in permitting make it difficult to secure financing for projects.

The SolarNova program has been the driving force in solar PV adoption. The first two tenders under the program, awarded in 2015 and 2017, yielded 116MW of capacity. The third tender, awarded to Sembcorp and Kurihara Kogyo in June 2018, will add another 50MW. While not officially disclosed, it has been reported that the winning bid for the third tender was close to zero. This underlines the confidence that developers and investors have of recovering costs through the sale of excess generation. This excess can be sold into the wholesale market or to other commercial and industrial customers. Apple's agreement with Sunseap to power 100% of its Singapore operations with renewable-sourced electricity from the latter is an example of the direct sale model.

Unlike any other country in South Asia, Sri Lanka has 100% electrification. New power plants are required to meet growing demand, and also to balance retirements. The island nation of about 20 million people has a large base of small hydro plants, is expanding wind and solar installations, and piloting newer technologies such as geothermal and wave energy. Multilateral lenders like Asia Development Bank (ADB) and International Finance Corporation are active in the market, lending funds and providing technical assistance. Some of the recent smaller-sized solar projects bid out are aimed at giving the local entrepreneurs an opportunity in this sector.

Solar has so far attracted most of the clean energy investment in Taiwan though investment in wind is poised to grow fast, largely because the government auctioned 5.5GW of offshore capacity in 2018. Taiwan's local banks have lent to solar projects, and are becoming comfortable with offshore wind assets. In June 2019, Orsted secured a NT$25 billion ($806 million) loan facility for its offshore wind projects in Taiwan, one of the biggest clean energy deals globally in 1H 2019. Some 15 Taiwan and international banks are part of the syndicated loan agreement.

Tajikistan has not seen any serious investment in renewable energy. Although the government has called for the construction of small hydro and solar power plants, the country's installed capacity for small hydro remains at less than 120MW and no new solar plants have come online. Still, international development banks and public-private partnerships are making some progress. The Asian Development Bank approved a $10 million grant in 2013 to support green energy solutions in households and Pamir Energy, a public-private partnership company, is investing in small hydro projects in rural parts of the country.

Stimulated by the attractive feed-in premium, also known as the 'adder', introduced in 2007, renewable energy capacity has grown significantly. Within two years of the release of the 2015 Power Development Plan (PDP), Thailand had achieved almost half of its 2036 renewable energy capacity target. Among all technologies, solar accounts for majority of the growth. In its infancy, there were concessional financing programs from the Clean Technology Fund, Asian Development Bank and International Finance Corp. Over the years, Thailand's conglomerates actively participated in the development of renewable energy projects. Local commercial banks have supported the energy transition in Thailand, and have actively financed projects in the country.

There are effectively no clean energy investments in Turkmenistan to date and the investment climate is not very conducive. Turkmenistan's policy of providing highly subsidized energy limits commercial viability of renewable projects. The Asian Development Bank had previously committed to investing heavily in Turkmenistan's power industry by funding potential projects. The status of these projects is unclear.

The growth rate in renewables investments in Uzbekistan is irregular, driven by announcements of projects such as that made by SkyPower, for a 1GW investment in solar power. Outside of the very few headline cases, investment is scant. The government seems to be targeting solar over wind, although this may be more dependent on the investors showing interest in the market. Finance for renewables is backed by international development institutions, such as the ADB, the IFC and the EBRD. Renewables are very much in the early days of development in Uzbekistan. Investment has mostly been directed to hydropower in the past, with the refurbishment of some hydro plants having been funded, although these assets are all state-owned.

Vietnam has emerged as the hotspot for clean energy investment within Southeast Asia, driven by solar developments. Between 2012 and 2017, wind attracted $1.5 billion in investments, but only 189MW of wind was installed at the end of 2017. The introduction of the solar FiT in 2017 led to a solar boom over the last two years. The state utility Vietnam Electricity (EVN) reported 82 projects with a combined capacity of 4.46GW connected to the grid by June 30, 2019, achieving more than five times the country's 2020 target. Activity in onshore and offshore wind development is picking up too after the upward revision of the FiT, with 7.8GW in the pipeline.

In the infancy of the wind industry, development banks such as KfW and Vietnam Development Bank provided financing. There has been an increase in financing of renewable projects from local banks such as Bank for Investment and Development of Vietnam, Vietnam Bank for Agriculture and Rural Development and Vietcombank over the last two years. Despite concerns over certain clauses in the power purchase agreements, financing from regional and foreign banks for renewable energy projects in Vietnam are on the rise.

Small hydro draws mostly domestic investors, while large hydro draws international ones. Investment in solar and wind energy is discussed but to date little funding has actually been committed. The clean energy investment landscape in Albania is not enhanced by the number of speculative investors involved in small hydro projects. A secondary market thrives for licenses, generating paperwork and heavy turnover of development rights, but little actually gets built. 
The government has announced plans to track development rights and withdraw licenses from speculators who don't appear to be on a path toward construction. If followed through on, those steps could potentially see more investment directed toward projects that are completed. The most notable instance of foreign investment in large hydro is the 73MW Banje power plant, owned by Statkraft of Norway. Albania's first solar auction awarded 100MW of capacity to a foreign investor, but progress on contract negotiation has been slow. There is no transparency on future auctions.

The country's first wind farm ' the 50.6MW Mesihovina project ' began producing electricity in March 2018. The facility was built at a cost of $101.4 million. Siemens Gamesa provided the turbines and the project was primarily financed through a loan provided by KfW, a German state-owned development bank. Another wind farm, Podvelezje I, was financed in 2018. A July 2018 tender for the construction of a 65MW solar project was cancelled due to lack of bids. Most renewables investment has come from international concessional lenders, including International Finance Corp., the European Investment Bank and European Bank for Reconstruction and Development. In addition to domestic funds and government grants, organizations such as the United Nations Development Program, GIZ and USAID provide co-financing as well as technical assistance. Some small-hydro projects are financed by local banks.

Financing is well established and widely available for hydro projects, for which the country has domestic expertise. Wind and solar projects use both domestic and international concessional financing from the Georgian Energy Development Fund (GEDF) and USAID. From 2011 to 2018, Georgia attracted $700 million, 85% of which was directed to small hydro projects. Most of the foreign investment has come from the Czech Republic, Germany and Asia. The potential for new wind and solar development is bringing in European players. The wind and solar plants in operation have been majority financed by the GEDF as demonstration projects.

With its lignite resource expected to dwindle substantially over the next decade, North Macedonia faces the option of either importing coal or diversifying into natural gas and renewables. Efforts to expand natural gas transmission lines are underway, and the government plans to incentivize demand for natural gas for power and heating; options include converting the mothballed heavy oil-fired TEC Negotino power plant to natural gas. North Macedonia was the first country in the Western Balkans to erect a sizable wind farm ' a 36.8MW project at Bogdanci owned by ELEM. There are plans to expand Bogdanci's capacity to 50MW. 
The government is offering concessions for investors looking into funding small hydropower plants, however, strong local opposition from environmentalists has pushed back against projects that they believe are sited poorly and  would have negative downstream impacts. Finance for wind and small hydro projects has mainly come from such international concessional donors as the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development, with local developers or the state utility providing smaller equity stakes.

To date, renewables investment has been limited to multilateral finance institutions. The European Bank for Reconstruction and Development has solicited expressions of interest from consultants to manage Moldova's clean energy tender program. EBRD also aims to launch a green energy finance facility (GEFF) in Moldova, which it describes as possessing a national energy sector 'characterized by heavy dependence on imports.' The World Bank is funding a competitive power market project with the objective of enhancing Moldova's access to the European energy market, which has a higher proportion of clean power. Spain's Gas Natural Fenosa is the largest foreign investor in the country's energy system, having bought in 2000 the power distribution company covering southern and central Moldova, which serves more than 800,000 customers. There is no demonstrated expertise in financing of renewables projects by local banks.

Russia's renewables capacity accounts for less than 1% of total capacity, even though auctions have been running since 2013, as many of the awarded projects are yet to be built. However, as foreign companies, including Fortum, Enel and Vestas become increasingly active in Russia's renewables auctions, this could drive more projects to complete. More renewable capacity came into operation in 2017 than the two previous years combined, according to the Ministry of Energy, showing the pace is stepping up. Fortum owns Russia's first wholesale wind farm, commissioned in January 2018, and was the biggest winner in Russia's 2018 auctions, securing both solar and wind capacity. Financing is a barrier to business in Russia due to international sanctions.

Over the last five years, when excluding small hydro, renewables capacity has grown at a CAGR of 44%. The majority of this is due to the financing of large-scale wind farms, sourced from domestic banks, foreign banks and money from impact funds. One of the biggest investors in Serbia's clean energy sector is MK Fintel ' a joint venture between Serbia's MK Group and Italy's Fintel Energia ' and it is expected to build around 60% of the country's 500MW wind capacity target. Beyond traditional energy players, the country's wind sector has also attracted financing from Masdar, a subsidiary of Abu Dhabi's Mubadal Investment Co., where it bought a 60% stake in the 158MW under-construction Cibuk 1 wind farm.

Clean energy investment grew steadily over 2012-2017, with wind leading and accounting for more than $1 billion each year over that period. Solar saw a surge in investment in 2017 as unlicensed projects rushed to commission before transmission costs increased. However, investment in clean energy has stagnated since 2018, amid policy uncertainty and ongoing currency fluctuations and an economic slowdown. Turkey holds auctions for pre-licenses, which are required for renewables projects to reach commissioning. After two auctions held in 2017 only one more, for wind capacity, is planned for April 2020, leaving developers with little scope to bring projects online.

Recent regulatory and legislative reforms have spurred rising clean energy investments in Ukraine, which attracted more than $4 billion in 2018 and 1H 2019 alone. The biggest investments so far have been made by local developers led by Ukraine's largest non-state utility DTEK and the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development, which has gone to lengths to present Ukraine as lower risk than previously perceived. U.S.-based Overseas Private Investment Corporation offers insurance against political risk for some energy investments, and the feed-in tariff is backed by a sovereign guarantee which also boosts investor confidence. Solar and wind projects have attracted similar levels of financing over 2018-19.

A scarcity of capital, price-distorting subsidies and political risk combined to make Argentina an unappealing destination for clean energy investment in the first half of this decade. That began to change in December 2015 with the arrival of President Mauricio Macri. Since then, Macri's government has sought to cut subsidies and liberalize energy markets to spur conventional and renewable project build underwritten with foreign capital. 
FODER, created under Macri's administration, was backed by the World Bank, which provided guarantees of payments for the renewable tenders. The guarantees boosted confidence among foreign debt providers. Only then did Argentina begin to see financing in the sector, accounting for $3.7 billion since 2016 and peaking in 2018 with $1.9 billion, a record for the industry in that country. Despite the recent progress, however, Argentina's latest re-entry into macroeconomic crisis may push investors away and create difficulties for auction-winning projects that have yet to secure financing.

Development of clean energy projects in Bolivia is led by state-owned Empresa Nacional de Electricidad (ENDE), with investment coming from international development banks and the Central Bank of Bolivia. The role of solar generation solidified in 2018, as ENDE commissioned 65MW in Tarija and Potosi, a large increase compared to the 5MW project in Pando installed in 2015. A 50MW PV plant, financed by European development agencies, was also commissioned in Oruro in 2019. Bolivia's first wind farm, Qollpana phase I (3MW) was commissioned in 2014 with a second phase (24MW) brought online in 2016. A pipeline of four wind projects, financed over 2017-18, may further the addition of 132MW of new capacity in the near term.

Brazil attracted almost $56 billion in new asset finance for clean energy plants in 2009-18, by far the largest amount in Latin America over the period. Wind alone accounts for 54% of the total, while solar attracted 8%. The solar share should increase as developers secured almost 2.5GW in contracts in the 2017-19 auctions. Brazilian national development bank BNDES has played a major role in the development of the country's renewable energy market. The bank is the top global lender to clean energy, having disbursed $23.5 billion for renewable energy projects (excluding large hydro) between 2009 and 2018. However, the bank had changed the methodology it uses to calculate interest rates. Those are now slated to increase gradually for new loans until 2023 when they reach par with commercial levels. Between now and then, we expect BNDES's contributions to fade somewhat as private capital takes a more prominent role.

Chile recorded $11 billion of clean energy investment from 2013 to year-end 2018. The 2018 level, however, was almost 60% less than the previous year. The country has many types of financial organizations investing in renewables, including development and commercial banks. The U.S. Overseas Private Investment Corporation (OPIC) has been the main lead arranger in the country. Although distributed PV generation expanded strongly in 2018 (from 12MW in 2017 to 24.3MW in 2018), the lack of cheap financing is an obstacle. In an attempt to boost distributed generation, the government expanded the size limit for installations from 100kW to 300kW in 2018. The number of installations decelerated in 2019, however.

Most investment directed to non-hydro renewable energy in Colombia to date has come from international development banks. From 2010 to 2018, Colombia attracted $1 billion in investment, with 2018 the year that saw a substantial increase on non-hydro investments, with solar attracting $200 million, or 100% of all investment received in the same year.

Costa Rica attracted $2.1 billion in new-build clean energy investment over 2010-2018. Over a third of that capital was directed to small hydro plants ($0.8 billion), followed by geothermal with $0.6 billion and wind with $0.6 billion. Investment peaked in 2014 with almost $0.6 billion provided to the three technologies, but it dropped by half in 2017. In 2018 Costa Rica attracted only $13.5 million to its clean power sector.

The Dominican Republic's clean energy sector attracted $1.4 billion of investment over 2010-2018. Wind energy captured the bulk of it, $746 million, followed by solar with $298 million. Over half of the investment was recorded on the past two years. Most renewable energy projects are financed by project developers and multilateral investment banks. Commercial banks have limited participation in the market.

Investments in clean energy in Ecuador are very small. Since 2011, the total invested amounted to only $500 million, mainly in small hydro assets. Development banks Inter-American Investment Corporation and Corporacin Andina de Fomento (CAF) are the biggest lead arrangers in the country, mainly investing in small hydro.

El Salvador's clean energy sector attracted $1 billion of investment over 2010-2018. Over half of the investment was directed to PV plants, which received $624 million, followed by $261 million for biomass and waste. Largely due to its successful clean energy auctions, over 65% of the total was recorded in 2016-2018.

Guatemala attracted $1.4 billion in new-build clean energy investment over 2010-2018. Over half of the total was directed to biomass and waste ($728 million), followed by small hydro with $343 million and solar with $173 million. Investment peaked in 2014, with $657 million provided. It then dropped continuously over the next four years, with no investment recorded in 2018.

The country does not have specific legislation mandating microgrids, which slows down project developments and keeps risks high. Regardless, microgrids are appearing on the island. One, financed by the Inter-American Development Bank (IDB), the United Nations Environment Program and the United States Agency for International Development (USAID), links the towns of Cteaux , Port--Piment and Roche--Bateaux and is managed by a newly created electrical cooperative. Another in Feyo Bien, is supported by IDB. Both microgrids are powered by hybrid PV-diesel generators. Sigora Solar has also developed a diesel generator powered microgrid in Mole Saint Nicolas, to which it will add solar generation shortly. In 2019, the government of Haiti and the World Bank established a new financing instrument to incentivize private companies to develop clean off-grid energy projects in the country. With $17 million in funding, it aims to provide electricity to 200,000 households in the next 10 years.

Honduras's clean energy sector attracted $2.6 billion over 2010-2018, driven by high investment in solar energy of $1.3 billion between 2014 and 2018. These investments were boosted by a feed-in premium that came into force in August 2013. A renewable energy feed-in premium is applicable to electricity generation from renewable resources. PV projects installed by July 31, 2015 (up to 300MW of capacity) received a base price for their energy equal to the short-term marginal cost plus $0.03/kWh plus 10%.

Jamaica attracted $0.3 billion in new-build clean energy investment over 2010-18. Wind energy was responsible for the highest investment in this period ($180 million), followed by solar with $127 million. Wind investment peaked in 2015 due to renewable energy auctions.

A substantial increase in opportunities brought about by energy reform transformed Mexico into a leading destination for clean energy investment under the previous administration. Plans to strengthen state control under Lopez Obrador, potentially at the expense of the private sector, are forcing a change of course, Mexico continues to see substantial development activity. The second largest power market in Latin America, Mexico's installed renewables capacity represents 11% of its 77GW total. This share is expected to increase as a result of new investment in the country's excellent solar and wind resources, though the future of auction mechanisms put in place by energy reform is in question. Mexico's financing landscape is diverse, with project developers, commercial banks and development banks all playing important roles. Wind projects, in particular, have been successful in attracting investment. The cost of wind and solar has declined rapidly in recent years, a trend that is expected to continue and which will pressure the country's natural gas sector.

Nicaragua attracted $942 million in new-build clean energy investment over 2010-16, but none has been disbursed since 2017. Wind has accounted for the highest share, a third of the total, followed by small hydro with $218 million and geothermal with $215 million.
Panama's clean energy sector attracted $1.6 billion of investment over 2010-2018. It experienced a jump in solar and wind installed capacity from zero in 2013 to over 450MW in 2018.

As nearly the entirety of electricity in Paraguay comes from large hydro, the country has not received significant clean energy investment in recent years. In 2011 Paraguay received $28 million for biofuels investments.

Peru attracted $3.1 billion in clean energy investment from 2010 to 2018. Most of the investments were in small hydro and onshore wind projects, equivalent to 39% and 32%, respectively, of the total. However, from 2016 to 2018, solar attracted most investment, registering $300 million in the period, compared to $200 million in wind. 

Peru saw a peak in investment throughout 2012-2014, mostly led by financing of auction projects. In recent years, clean energy investment in the country has faded, as only $300 million was invested in 2017 and less than $2 million in 2018. The country has received capital from international and national commercial financial institutions, as well as development banks. The biggest lead arrangers are U.S. Overseas Private Investment Corporation (OPIC) and European Investment Bank, registering $235 and $213 million on PV and onshore wind.

Between 2011 and 2018, Uruguay received $4.5 billion in clean energy investment from national and international commercial banks and international development banks. The lead arrangers are Inter-American Development Bank and Kreditanstalt fr Wiederaufbau (KfW). In 2015, the country registered the highest annual investment, $1.2 billion. Over 90% of the total was directed to wind plants. In 2018, investments in renewables hit record low levels for the period, with just $5 million directed to clean energy projects.

Clean energy investment levels in Egypt fluctuate year on year, depending on individual deals. 2018 investment volumes fell 75% from 2017 to $875 million, due to the second round of the feed-in tariff program. This was after 2017 saw a surge that helped the country secure a record $3.4 billion. As is common for renewables deals in Egypt, most of the financing for the feed-in tariff projects came from concessional investors (in this case, the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development, and World Bank's International Finance Corporation). Indeed, the majority of total clean energy investment came from foreign sources. Japan and Germany account for the largest shares, at 21% and 14% respectively, largely because they are home to development banks JICA and KfW. The feed-in tariff scheme required that a certain share of investment come from domestic sources.

Hydro and solar have been the focus of renewables investment in Iraq to date. Despite 2.5GW of installed hydro capacity, just over half is available to generate due to damages and aging infrastructure. In 2019, the Ministry of Energy has issued tenders for seven projects with a total capacity of 755MW. Financing renewables projects in Iraq is difficult, and private investors are forced to rely on local banks that lack experience in financing larger projects. With 50% of electricity lost before billing and only 50% of bills collected, there is a high perception of risk surrounding investments in the country's energy sector.

Wind and solar have been the focus of renewable investment to date, with $1.6 billion of utility-scale solar and $1.1 billion of wind financed as of 1H 2019. The government launched a 30MW battery-storage project and targeted a further 70MW of battery-storage capacity pending the outcome of the first project. Traditionally, international development banks have provided financing for renewable projects, however, an increasing number of domestic banks and private equity funds are active in the market. As such, financing for renewable projects in Jordan is well established, and the process of securing finance is less onerous than elsewhere in the region.

The deployment of renewables started very recently in Kuwait, translating into high growth rates from very small bases. The bulk of renewable generation is solar (both PV and solar thermal), with onshore wind accounting for the rest. No other renewable energy technologies are set to be developed, but some hybrid projects are in planning. The country does not have financial institutions solely dedicated to green investments, but domestic banks have been active in financing renewable energy projects. Increasing capacity is funded through the private-public-partnership (PPP) model. For example, the Az-Zour North Power and Water plant uses the PPP model and initial public offering to secure financing. The aim is to increase the private ownership in more projects.

The current pipeline of renewables projects will ensure strong growth in the sector in Lebanon. Following the signature of PPAs for 180MW of solar in 2017, the PPAs for the first 200MW of wind developed in the country were signed in February 2018 at a price of $113/MWh. A further 800MW of projects could sign PPAs in the coming years as a result of further tender rounds. The Lebanese Centre for Energy Conservation received considerable expressions of interest for its tenders, including both local and major international developers such as ACWA Power, First Solar and Tesla, amongst others. Investment in the first round of auctions has come mostly from domestic sources. The National Renewable Energy Action Plan targets $1.7 billion of investment to develop the renewables sector.

The country's plans to implement clean-energy investment is very real, and Oman lags slightly behind other countries in the region so is motivated to progress quickly. The government has recently become very strategic about diversifying its energy and economic strategy. Not only will the fossil-fuel resource eventually run out, they are also paying an opportunity cost to use these resources, which could be managed more optimally. Specifically, combined power and water-desalination plants that were put in place 15-20 years ago are now a disaster in terms of efficiency. Across the region, massive investments are under way to replace these with efficient gas plants, reverse osmosis water plants and solar power. Oman is very well situated as the country enjoys some of the greatest resource potentials in the world for solar and wind.

While renewables currently represent less than 1% of total installed capacity in the country, this is set to change under the NREP. To date, structural obstacles, such as subsidized energy prices and the concentration of ownership of generation assets among few institutions have stymied investment and development. The gradual opening of the energy sector to private sector participation means more players are becoming involved. For instance, Saudi-based Acwa Power, in a consortium with AlGihaz Holding Company, is developing the 300MW Sakaka PV project. It is completely underwritten by French investment bank Natixis and additionally supported by the Arab National Bank.

Investment in renewables has been considerable ' $400 million went toward funding solar plants in 2017 alone. Spending is set to skyrocket: the U.A.E. has pledged $163 billion in spending on renewables by 2050. Home-grown players such as Masdar have led a number of consortiums heading the country's main projects, such as the Shams Power solar thermal plant, commissioned in 2013 and owned by the Abu Dhabi-based developer (80%) and Total SA (20%). The project was underwritten to the tune of $600 million by a group of 10 foreign and domestic banks, underlining the extent to which sources of finance are diversified. International developers, investors and banks have spent considerable sums on the country's renewable energy initiatives.

Investment in clean energy comes from international development organizations and other countries, especially in the Persian Gulf, and reached $55 million in 2018. The Palestine Investment Fund, or PIF, and the Arab Bank are financing a $20 million solar portfolio to be developed in the West Bank. Massader, a PIF subsidiary, invests in large-scale infrastructure projects, including the $80 million Noor Palestine solar program.

There are no clean energy investments to track yet as the first set of projects are still in the pre-bid stage. These will be solar projects as solar resources are abundant in Qatar. Investment in the projects can come from anywhere but it must not solely be from Qatari banks. Additionally, the developer can, at a maximum, own 40% of the project with the other 60% going to Strategic National Investors. Yet, the developer is responsible for sourcing all the financing.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Prices for clean energy are driven up by the requirement to use locally manufactured equipment. While the domestic solar manufacturing industry has started producing panels at scale, product costs remain far higher than those sold internationally. Retail rates are relatively low by virtue of the country's rich gas resources. When compared across the region, tariffs are cheaper than in neighboring Morocco and Tunisia, but more expensive than those imposed in Egypt and oil-rich Gulf states. Prices have not been raised over past years, but low oil and gas prices have strained the public purse since they began to fall in 2014. The current political uncertainty renders reforms in this area unlikely before 2020.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Angola's residential and commercial electricity prices have not changed since 2013. At $27/MWh in 2018, they are among the lowest across emerging markets. Extensive fossil-fuel subsidies significantly affect the price at which electricity is offered by the state generation company, reducing the potential incentive for consumers to install small-scale PV. Angola does not have an industrial tariff or a wholesale power market. Electricity sector reform, which began in 2014, has sought to increase retail tariffs for electricity. These are now expected to be implemented in 2019. Currently, ENDE cannot charge cost-reflective tariffs and is dependent on government subsidy. Higher rates are expected to increase the financial viability of the utility and reduce subsidies to the sector, potentially attracting independent producers.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Electricity access is low, at just 32% percent of the population (Rural 11%, Urban 56%). In addition, domestic production covers only 12% of domestic consumption, with the remainder sourced from lower-cost imports. In past years, the Government of Benin has contracted expensive thermal power generation to address outages due to the unavailability of power imports arising from temporary supply challenges in Ghana and Nigeria. The regulated retail tariffs are high by regional norms, but are not sufficient to cover the costs of local generation. These correspond to $0.19 U.S. dollar/kWh, which is about 40-50% higher than the average in Sub Saharan Africa. The expensive generation mix and inability to cover costs has led the country's distribution utility SBEE (Socit Bninoise d'Energie Electrique) into financial distress. Moreover, SBEE's combined grid losses are high at 24%, and the income of the utility only covered 80% of its costs in 2017.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16:
For decades, electricity in Botswana has been heavily subsidized, but this is slowly changing with tariffs having increased in recent years. Private consumers have paid low power prices, which has led to the Botswana Power Corporation dispatching power at a loss. In an effort to create more cost-reflective tariffs, BPC has therefore gradually increased the tariffs and steadily reduced the subsidy from 2.4 billion Botswana pula ($220 million) to 1.4 billion Botswana pula with the intention to reduce it further to 800 million Botswana pula in 2018. Electricity tariffs have risen consistently over the last decade at an average of 10% annually. 

Up until three years ago, residential consumers were paying the highest electricity tariffs. This has now changed, with BPC now charging industrial customers the highest tariffs as the largest consumers of electricity. However, this change may need to be reviewed as the largest state mine in the country, BCL Mine Limited, was forced into liquidation and closed in 2016.


Up until the 3 years residential consumers have paid the highest electricity tariffs. BPC now charges their biggest users, Industrial customers, the highest tariffs which may need to be reviewed seeing as the largest state mine in the country, BCL Mine Limited, was forced into liquidation and closed in 2016.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Electricity costs in landlocked Burkina Faso are on the higher end of tariffs in the region, as the country needs to import expensive diesel to run its thermal power plants. This situation was exacerbated in 2018, with diesel prices nearly doubling. The regulator ARSE sets a national fixed electricity tariff, with no distinction between prices for commercial, industrial and residential users. While the tariff has been stable over the last five years, it is not cost reflective, meaning that the national utility Sonabel is reliant upon government subsidies.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Electricity tariffs are set by the monopoly electricity supplier, Regideso. Power prices are extremely high, considering the high proportion of hydro, with average tariffs being among the world's most expensive. The increasing lack of power supply has been driving these high tariffs, along with grid inefficiencies and a lack of investment into new infrastructure. In 2017, amid the lack of power supply, Regideso leased a 30MW gas power plant to supply the capital Bujumbura. The dependence on the thermal power plant has made electricity tariffs increase more since then.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: The Electric Sector Regulation Agency (ARSEL) sets electricity tariffs in Cameroon. These are relatively high for the region, particularly for a hydro-dominated market, owing to high transmission costs (including grid distribution losses of about 30%). The government subsidizes the tariffs by transferring funds to the monopoly utility, Eneo, and it has paid out more than $20 million between 2012 and 2019. Hydropower remains Cameroon's cheapest source of electricity, but recent growth in small-scale and off-grid solar suggests that these alternatives are becoming increasingly competitive in rural areas away from the three separate power grids.
