Grid operators must buy excess production from renewables installations, but no price is specified and they may not buy electricity at above-market rates, which limits the policy's effectiveness.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: The government artificially keeps power prices low and financially supports the heavily indebted state-owned utility Enerca, which is unable to cover its costs. The utility is currently undergoing a reorganization with the support of the World Bank in order to improve its performance. Technology costs in the country are difficult to determine due to the very low pipeline of any capacity additions. The very few projects that have been announced lack in detail and are currently on hold due to ongoing political disturbances, preventing progress from being made.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Chad's government heavily subsidizes power retail tariffs, which have remained unchanged since their last adjustment in 2012. As the government is committed to increasing the population's access to cheap electricity, there is little chance of rates rising in the short-term. The tariffs are nonetheless higher than in most neighboring countries. Electricity costs are difficult to determine due to the lack of detail on capacity additions.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Retail power prices are much lower than in neighboring Cameroon and the Central African Republic, and cheap when compared to the region as a whole. There is no differentiation between commercial, industrial and residential prices, and the only variation is by consumption band. Tariffs have been fixed since 1994 and are kept well below production costs through significant subsidies. Prices are unlikely to be increased in the near future, following the successful relaunch of recently-privatized state utility E2C.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: The DRC has a regulated electricity tariff that has only marginally changed over the last few years. Residential customers are charged one of the lowest tariffs in the world, which does not even cover the operating costs of the utility, SNEL. However, there have been recent increases to residential tariffs due to a devaluation in the Congolese franc, according to reports. There has been little change to the levelized costs of electricity in the DRC due to a lack of new projects being built in the last 36 years and poor maintenance of existing energy infrastructure. Electricity is mostly purchased by consumers for a fixed lump sum as meters are very scarce, leaving much of the billing at the discretion of officials. Furthermore, it is also common for public institutions (schools, health centers and public enterprises) to have large amounts overdue on their electricity bills.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: An abundance of hydropower and domestic gas resources have contributed to low retail prices in Cote d'Ivoire. The government attempted to raise tariffs in 2016, but backed down in the face of protests, going as far as to compensate the affected consumers for the temporary price hike. International lenders, such as the World Bank, have renewed pressure to increase rates to no avail. The disparity between production costs and tariffs means that the sector as a whole runs at a loss. Despite such issues, offtaker risk remains low and IPPs are usually paid on time under their take-or-pay contracts with the utility. CIE's finances are also relatively stable thanks to the stewardship of French management company Eranove. The process of restructuring the utility's debt was completed in early-2019

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Power prices are regulated in Eritrea and there is no differentiation between commercial, residential and industrial tariffs. Tariffs remain unchanged since 2017. Almost all on-grid capacity is powered by diesel, which is costly to import. With beneficial wind and solar resources, Eritrea offers good conditions for clean energy deployment. Around half of the population still lacks access to power, so the potential for mini-grids is therefore high. The country's levelized cost of energy for different technologies is difficult to determine due to the lack of detail on capacity additions.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: The heavy presence of cheap hydro gives Ethiopia among the lowest power prices in Sub-Saharan Africa. Lack of exposure to fuel prices also has ensured minimal variation in prices. However, a currency shortage and the subsequent rapid devaluation of the Ethiopian birr caused the Ethiopia Electric Utility (EEU), who manages the distribution grid, to increase retail prices by 50% to $0.03/kWh in 2018 to improve its profitability. EEU is expected to double retail prices again by 2022 to $0.06/kWh to combat these currency struggles, but Ethiopia will still have among the cheapest power on the continent. Upon commissioning of the 6GW Grand Renaissance Dam, the country plans to export cheap power to neighboring countries.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Ghana has some of the highest power prices in the region, due to an inefficient transmission and distribution system with high losses, PPAs with expensive thermal generation and a failure to effectively collect revenue. As a result, the power prices increased through the mid-2010s, and became one of the main focuses of the 2016 election. In March 2018, the new government cut the electricity tariffs for industrial customers by as much as 30%, and the reductions were also extended further to residential and commercial customers. The new tariffs are not reflective of the cost of generation and transmission, and so are heavily subsidized. Despite the reductions, the tariffs are still one of the highest in Sub-Saharan Africa.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Guinea's power prices are among the region's lowest at an average retail price of $123.95/MWh, even given a significant price rise in 2018. Prices were increased in order to ensure a better cost recovery, with substantial increases to commercial and industrial rates. Prior to this, tariffs had not been adjusted for more than seven years. The state subsidizes the national utility EDG in order for it to stay operational. Insofar as power purchasing is concerned, EDG agreed to pay China Water and Electric around $85/MWh for energy produced by the 240MW Kal'ta dam, which was completed in 2015. Investments in interconnectors aim to facilitate Guinea's interest in becoming a net exporter in the mid-term.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Kenya's electricity tariffs are set by the Electricity Act of 2006. They had tended to increase in recent years and jumped 8-21% from 2017 to 2018. Kenya Power introduced off-peak tariffs for commercial and industrial customers in December 2017, which are applicable during the night time if a customer meets a certain threshold of monthly power consumption. Power prices in Kenya are higher compared to neighboring economies such as Ethiopia, where cheap large-hydro power is available, and Tanzania, where the government keeps tariffs lower than generation costs.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Power prices are extremely high in Lesotho. They were $0.77 per KWh in 2018, on a weighted-average basis. Prices are elevated substantially by the need to procure imports from South Africa, which cost more than 10 times as much as domestically produced electricity. A growing domestic fleet, so one with low marginal cost electricity, should help reduce local power prices.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Liberia's retail electricity prices have declined significantly in recent years as a result of the refurbishment of Mount Coffee Hydropower Plant, which brought a low-cost supply to the heavily constrained power system. Regulated tariffs, which are equal across all customer types, dropped by more than 40% over 2015-17, to $0.35/kWh today, and rates stayed the same in 2018. Factors that could place upward pressure on power prices include substantial investment required in the LEC grid and potential subsidizing of new renewable energy projects.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Madagascar power prices are relatively high compared to the average electricity tariff in Sub-Saharan Africa. Residential prices are comparable to the region's average of $122/MWh, but commercial and industrial tariffs are 1.5 to 2-fold more expensive than the Sub-Saharan African average at $213.74/MWh and $257.33/MWh respectively. All tariff types have increased in the last decade, despite government support for social retail tariffs. The steady increase in diesel prices and correspondingly high costs associated with the country's dependence on fossil-fired generation continue to aggravate state utility Jirama's financial situation.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Electricity tariffs have steadily increased in recent years in order for the central utility to raise revenue and improve the energy deficit. Price increases are unpopular among consumers, especially given the frequent scheduled blackouts in Malawi. Fuel prices are also increasing quite significantly, which is particularly disruptive given Malawi's dependence on diesel generation for emergency power. The country does not have any significant interconnection to neighboring markets, so is unable to import power. Regulators are in discussion to open up interconnections to Zambia, which would improve power supply in the country and potentially bring prices down.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Power prices are subsidized and have remained relatively stable for the past decade, yet are steadily increasing. The average electricity tariff was $0.18/kWh in 2018, which is particularly high compared to neighboring countries. This is likely in part due to costly fossil fuel imports. The state utility EDM runs at a loss, despite being supported by the Malian government. In contrast, the tariffs offered by independent power producers are cost-reflective at around triple the price offered by EDM, causing discontent and limited uptake by customers.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Generous subsidies have kept retail tariffs stable for the past few years. Compared to neighboring countries, Somelec's power tariffs are low at an average retail price of $131.22/MWh. However, the vast majority of citizens pay discounted 'social' rates bankrolled by the state, while rural consumers are faced with steeper bills levied by microgrid operators. There is little regulatory clarity concerning the determination and adjustment of tariffs, which falls under the remit of the regulatory agency ARE.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Power prices in Morocco are subsidized by the state utility, the Office Nationale de l'Electricit et de l'Eau potable (ONEE), which does not pass on the full cost of generation to consumers and therefore operates at a loss. Government support of the energy sector is a strain on public finances but has been rationalized within a developmental context. Servicing the 5% growth rate in electrical demand and the acute evening peak remains a primary concern in securing new generating capacity, much of this slack has been met with expensive diesel generators. The difficulty and expense in meeting evening peak demand has necessitated storage requirements for Moroccan solar tenders and electricity tariffs that are 40% higher during the evening for commercial and industrial clients. The high cost of meeting evening peak justified a PPA for the Noor I solar thermal project of $189/kWh 2013, which includes five hours of storage. Since 2013, a maturing domestic industry, technological advances and hybrid-plant design with PV have driven down costs. In 2018, the PPA for the latest solar thermal (hybrid) project was signed at only $70/MWh. In 2016, the PPA for 850MW of wind projects awarded to the Enel, Siemens, and Nareva consortium set a world record price of $30/MWh on average. PPAs for solar PV auctions to date are unknown, however, most projects have been commissioned in the context of rural electrification and deferment of grid upgrades.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Despite a five-year freeze in the 2010-15 period, retail power prices have risen considerably over the last decade with commercial tariffs climbing more than eightfold, and residential bills more than doubling, as state utility Electricidade de Mo'ambique (EDM) attempts to make up for longstanding revenue shortfalls. As recently as 2017, the regulator increased the tariffs for both the commercial and residential bands by approximately 34%. Industrial prices saw a marginal decrease over the same period, falling from $41.97 to $41.53/MWh. Social tariffs, which apply to low-income users, have remained stable. Like most countries in Sub-Saharan Africa, Mozambique does not have a wholesale power market, but it does belong to the Southern Africa Power Pool, which is gradually increasing liquidity.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16:
Unlike many of its neighbors, retail power prices in Namibia are cost reflective and unsubsidized. Therefore, their prices are among the highest in sub-Saharan Africa, and have increased above 5% annually for the last six years. Retail tariffs vary by season and time of use (peak versus non-peak), and contain high capacity charges for industrial and commercial consumers. These retail-rate structures are prime for battery development, which could reduce a site's peak load and shift consumption from high-priced to low-priced times of the day.
The country is burdened by its inability to meet demand with domestic power. About 60% of electricity needs are met with electricity imports from South Africa, the costs of which are substantially higher than power from local plants.
High electricity prices are driving investments in off-grid solar-plus-battery systems, even in areas where the grid is available. Windhoek, the capital of Namibia, alone has an estimated 20MW of off-grid capacity. 
While the country has done much to incentivize solar generation, which will help provide electricity at midday, the country lacks highly flexible generation sources that would help minimize electricity imports during the most costly peak hours.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Nigerien power prices are subsidized and remain stable over the long-term, yet were adjusted in 2018 to enable better cost recovery. Prior to that, prices had only been adjusted once since 2012, when a social tariff was also introduced. Nevertheless, Niger offers some of the lowest electricity tariffs compared to its neighbors, with the average retail electricity price standing at $126.41/MWh. Equally, retail fuel prices are subsidized and have remain unchanged since 2013.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16:
Electricity prices are set by the Nigerian Electricity Regulatory Commission (NERC) under its multi-year tariff-order model. Distribution companies have said that the tariffs are not cost-reflective, and so investment has stagnated. Tariffs have not been updated since 2015 and so do not incorporate the significant drop in the price of solar that has occurred worldwide.
The 'yet-to-be-built' on-grid PV projects partially 'agreed' a tariff of $0.075-0.115/kWh, which falls within the range of BNEF's levelized cost of energy for Asia. No wholesale power market exists yet in Nigeria. Instead, NBET brokers transactions between generators and distributors. The 'Eligible Customer' regulation allows bulk buyers to buy directly from a generator at a negotiated PPA rate.
In 2018, BNEF carried out a detailed study about on-site solar in Nigeria and found that solar on commercial and industrial premises can cost between $0.1 and 0.2/kWh in Nigeria. PV alone is already cheaper than grid electricity tariffs or electricity from a diesel generator, which typically costs $0.28-0.32/kWh.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Electricity prices in Rwanda are among the highest in East Africa, and commercial and residential tariffs have increased considerably since 2010. The biggest driver of this is the 'take-or-pay' contracts administered by REG. These contracts compensate developers for the contractual offtake from their projects even at times when power cannot be evacuated. On top of that, the PPAs are signed in dollars and are exposed to fuel-price fluctuations. As a result of these high prices and low income levels in the country, retail electricity is highly subsidized by REG and the Government of Rwanda. Small hydro remains the most popular source of generation, due to the strong network of rivers in Rwanda, but the country has also taken advantage of methane from gaseous lakes in the southwest to generate electricity.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Power prices in Senegal have not changed a great deal over past years, but are on a downward trajectory as the government tries to reduce rates. The trend should continue as new renewables projects and domestic gas discoveries drive down production costs, which are higher than elsewhere in the region due to a reliance on costly diesel generation. Early-2019 saw the beginning of a long-awaited harmonization program, through which the private holders of electrification concessions will be compensated so that they can reduce retail rates charged to rural customers, which are higher than those levied by Senelec.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16:
Electricity tariffs can be unstable in Sierra Leone, and stabilization clauses are often written into PPAs as a result. There has been considerable variation over the last few years, according to Climatescope data.
Power prices for commercial, industrial and residential customers are becoming more harmonized after efforts by EDSA to adjust heavy subsidization that was previously distorting prices.
For bulk supply, most of the utility's procurement costs are unknown. A deal signed with the Turkish Karadeniz Powership in 2017 was negotiated at 16.4'/kWh for 30MW of baseload supply over five years.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Retail power prices in Somalia are among the highest in Africa because electricity service providers still rely primarily on inefficient diesel generators with high fuel costs. Transmission infrastructure is fragmented and unreliable, and losses are high at around 40% compared to the sub-Saharan Africa average of 11%. Power grids are usually localized, which increases costs and prevents companies from realizing economies of scale. Finally, metering infrastructure and consumer rates are inadequate enough to incentivize efficient electricity use. Many electricity providers charge based on the number of appliances or light bulbs used, giving consumers little reason to use more efficient devices or to curb their consumption.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: The winning tariffs have dropped significantly in each renewables auction: wind and PV fell 24% and 29% between Rounds 3 and 4, after adjusting the tariffs for factors such as inflation and merchant tail. Overall, the LCOE for onshore wind in South Africa ' at $62-89/MWh ' falls in the middle of our benchmark estimates in 1H 2019, as its relatively-low capex is counteracted by higher financing costs. It's a similar story for PV (without tracking), with an LCOE of $60-66/MWh. As is common in the region, South Africa has no wholesale electricity market and the energy regulator (Nersa) determines final retail prices. Eskom has repeatedly argued for substantial tariff increases to claw back its billions of expenses. Overall, tariffs climbed an average of 13.7% a year between 2004 and 2018.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: The South Sudanese government subsidizes power prices for the few customers with access to the grid in the capital and charges one uniform tariff. There is very little purchasing power in the population, but the main issue is not the lack of demand, but rather a lack of installed capacity. Moreover, the national grid is often not operational. A handful of regional capitals use heavy fuel oil-powered mini-grids, run either by the state utility or by local cooperatives. In contrast to those run by the state-owned utility, the grids run by the local cooperatives charge cost-reflective tariffs, thereby curbing customer numbers somewhat.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Sudanese consumers benefit from generous electricity subsidies, which result in some of the world's lowest retail prices. A reduced 'social tariff' benefits those who consume less than 200kWh/month, which is a higher threshold than found elsewhere in the region. These tariffs fall far short of meeting utility production costs, leaving the companies financially dependent on the government. However, raising tariffs is politically difficult given Sudan's political instability. Following the breakaway of South Sudan in 2011, Sudan lost the majority of its oil assets, leaving it with little choice but to import the fuel needed for its thermal power generation. Sudan's runaway inflation and currency devaluation compounds the challenge, making fossil fuel imports increasingly costly.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Retail electricity prices in Tanzania have remained lower than many other East African countries, averaging close to $0.09/kWh in 2018, and are regulated by the Energy and Water Utilities Authority. Prices are low partially due to the near-600MW of installed hydro capacity, but also due to heavy subsidization from Tanzania's Ministry of Energy, which is intended to attract industrialization in the country. In February 2016, TANESCO, the state-owned utility, lobbied for slightly lower retail prices to help the country reach its 75% electrification target in 2025 without jeopardizing its profitability, but prices have overall remained relatively stable.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Togo's challenge is to expand power generation in a cost?efficient manner. The country relies heavily upon imports from the West Africa Power Pool, which provided almost 75% of consumption in 2018. The price of imported hydropower and gas?fired generation ranges from $80 to $120/MWh. To increase its energy security, Togo signed a 25-year PPA with U.S.-based Contour Global in 2010 for a 100MW Heavy Fuel Oil (HFO) plant, at offtake prices as high as $170/MWh. Such high offtake prices offer an opportunity for large-scale renewables to be built at a considerably lower cost of generation. On 31 October 2018, Siemens, Eranove and TSK signed a memorandum to work together on the framework for the 65MW K'k'li gas-fired electricity power station, which will supply 30% of the country's electricity needs for 25 years.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Due to the high level of subsidies, Tunisia's average residential electricity prices were among the 10 lowest in Africa at $52.50/MWh in 2017. Industrial and commercial prices ' at $76/MWh and $87/MWh, respectively ' are significantly higher than the residential tariff but still more than 50% below the regional average. In 2019, Tunisia signed a tariff of $24.40/MWh for 200MW of PV ' a record low for Africa.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Uganda has relatively high retail prices compared to neighboring countries. This is largely due to the combination of cost overruns and expensive take-or-pay contracts with renewable (mostly large-scale hydro) projects. Umeme, the country's transmission and distribution utility, guarantees shareholders a 20% return on investment, further boosting prices. Residential, industrial and commercial rates have all increased more than 50% in real terms since 2010.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Electricity prices in Zambia are historically stable and low, due to the fact that they are subsidized. Retail tariffs are below the cost of production, so Zesco faces significant financial pressure. The utility's overall debt is estimated at $1 billion and it has reportedly fallen into arrears on payments to IPPs, after the 2015-16 drought led to the signing of emergency PPAs. For instance, Zescos's debt to Electricidade de Mozambique (EDM) for importing power from a Karpowership stands at around $70 million. In 2017, average commercial electricity prices were increased as Zesco began implementing steps toward more cost-reflective tariffs, which was also necessitated by inflation of the Kwacha. The tariff increase was approved by the Energy Regulatory Board, but subsequent upward revisions of retail tariffs planned for 2018 were cancelled following direct intervention by the President, pending the local election cycle. For renewables, high solar irradiation and declining technology costs hold strong potential for the development of PV capacity, but wind energy potential in Zambia is relatively limited. Zambia's hydro generation potential is estimated at more than 6,000MW, more than double what it is today.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: National electricity tariffs are roughly USD$0.0983 per kWh, compared to a regional average of USD $0.14 per kWh, according to ZESA. In reality, Zimbabwe's tariffs are among the highest in the region when accounting for exchange rates.  In April 2019, ZESA applied for a 30% increase in tariffs to fund grid maintenance after the price of inputs such as diesel and coal increased. The national regulator, ZERA, is operating at a loss and ZESA has struggled to collect more than $1 billion owed by defaulters. The government's mandatory rollout of prepaid meters was designed to bring in more stable revenue. According to ZETDC, the program has improved revenue inflows by 35%.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: The electricity prices in Afghanistan are highly volatile because the country relies heavily on electricity imports to meet its needs. Over the last few years, because of appreciation of the U.S. dollar against Afghani, the national utility has hiked prices. Afghanistan, on an annual basis, pays more than $200 million to buy electricity from its neighboring countries. The utility however believes that once the country is able to harness its own resources, the prices will come down again.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Armenia's retail electricity prices are higher than those of neighboring Azerbaijan and Georgia, but not drastically so. Power prices are not subsidized, but are low enough to be acceptable to most of the population. The country is reliant on imported gas for roughly under half of its generation. Energy security is a major driver of the shift to renewable energy. The cost of clean energy in Armenia is falling, and becoming favorable compared to gas. The Masrik-1 auction price of $41.90/MWh was lower than many in the government foresaw, and is expected to be used as a baseline tariff for other, smaller projects.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Power prices have significantly increased in recent years, as the government has attempted to shore up the viability of the power system. Soviet era networks and generation assets require upgrades and will have to be supported by higher power prices. The issues with subsidized power prices and antiquated installations are common to most of Azerbaijan's neighbors, with which it has interconnections. Generation is largely fueled by the country's own natural gas, so cost will decline as power plants are upgraded to more efficient turbines. This may well present renewables with strong competition for a while to come.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Average power prices in Bangladesh are lower than in neighboring India, even though the smaller country generates most of its electricity from more expensive natural gas compared to cheap domestic coal in India. To keep the retail tariffs low, the government provides subsidies at two levels ' by selling fuel to power generation companies below the market rate and providing subsidies to the power distribution companies. Electricity prices have been rising at regular intervals over the past few years but they are still not high enough to meet all the operational and new investment expenses of the power distribution companies.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Cambodia's consumers pay some of the highest retail electricity rates in the region, at $0.15/kWh for most residential consumers. These tariffs have declined by roughly one-third since 2010, as the government has sought to make power more affordable as it connects more villages to the grid. Tariffs are not cost-reflective but are subsidized by the government, which covers losses faced by electricity distributors. Because of the focus on rapid electrification and lowering costs, EDC and the government have favored large power plants with low per-megawatt costs, such as hydro and coal.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: China has some of the cheapest residential electricity in the world because it is subsidized by commercial and industrial (C&I) users. It began, in 2016, to address this cross-subsidization by lowering retail C&I power costs. China's Premier announced the target to reduce retail C&I tariffs by another 10% in 2019, after the same mandate last year, in order to benefit the manufacturing sector and lift the economy against the backdrop of trade tensions with the U.S. Levelized costs of solar and wind power have dropped significantly on the back of efficiency improvements and oversupply '  the solar policy change in 2018 triggered a 30% module price drop. Subsidy-free projects for both technologies have appeared in 16 provinces.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Retail electricity tariffs across the country for fiscal 2019 increased by just 1% on average from 2018, as two-thirds of the 18 major states did not make any changes to tariffs. Commercial and industrial consumers continue to cross-subsidize agricultural and residential users. Auction tariffs in 2018 did not set a new record low as borrowing costs rose, the rupee depreciated and developers factored in the difficulties of land acquisition. India still enjoys the lowest LCOE in the world for solar and third-lowest for wind.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Power prices in Indonesia are one of the lowest in the region: at $76-89/MWh for commercial and industrial users in 2017, and $78/MWh for households. The government subsidizes retail electricity tariffs. A subsidy is given directly to the national utility PLN to cover its electricity supply costs. The government has not changed electricity prices in 2018 and 2019. The levelized cost of solar and wind power is still not competitive with conventional generation technologies like coal and hydro in Indonesia, due to the limited overall deployments in the country and the high cost of finance for these projects.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Electricity prices in Kazakhstan differ from region to region, and by the amount of electricity consumed. The average retail electricity price in the country, including distribution, value-added tax and fees, is $0.04/kWh as a result of government subsidies. In neighboring Russia and China, average prices are at $0.07/kWh and $0.08/kWh. Bringing renewables into the system at an average price of 31.68 tenge ($0.083)/kWh will strain the resources of the Financial Settlement Company, with which all renewable generators sign power purchase agreements, as this is higher than the retail tariffs. The introduction of renewables auctions has lowered the cost previously paid to developers through feed-in tariffs.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Kyrgyz Republic, like many of its neighbors in the former Soviet Union, has low power prices due to government subsidies. While electricity rates have increased slightly in recent years, prices for residential customers remain among the lowest in the world (at just $0.01/kWh) and far below the level needed for full cost recovery. The World Bank estimated the cumulative debt of the energy sector companies to be at 96.7 billion som ($1.4 billion) at the end of 2017. This is roughly 20% of the country's annual GDP. Electricity prices will have to increase significantly in order to pay this debt in a timely manner, according to the bank.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Power prices in Laos are relatively low, due to its abundance of low-cost hydroelectricity. The government sets electricity tariffs and subsidizes industry, residential consumers, agriculture and small and medium enterprises with rates below the cost of service. Banks and hotels, on the other hand, have to pay significantly higher tariffs, which can make onsite solar competitive for a small segment despite the absence of net metering or other incentives. Rates have remained stable through 2017-2018. The government announced, at the beginning of 2019, that it will try to cut electricity prices for households and businesses.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Malaysian residential electricity prices are among the cheapest in the region at $54/MWh, while commercial and industrial tariffs are higher, at $94-108/MWh. Average power prices have remained the same across all segments for the last four years. The government has announced that power prices would remain the same at least until the end of 2019. The levelized cost of electricity (LCOE) for renewable energy technologies is still not competitive with conventional generation assets like coal and gas power. Small hydropower projects offer the least-cost renewable energy generation technology, followed by solar. However, in the recent competitive auction held under Malaysia's third round of large-scale solar auctions, the lowest bid for solar power came in at 177 ringgits ($42)/MWh. This is about 55% lower than the lowest bid received in the auctions conducted in 2016.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Retail electricity tariffs in Mongolia range from 110.67 tugrik ($0.04) per kWh for households to 158.23 tugrik per kWh for commercial and industrial users. This level, having climbed 60% since 2011, is higher than neighboring countries such as Kazakhstan, and just slightly lower than China. Wholesale prices for general thermal generators are at 80.86 tugrik/kWh, while the feed-in tariffs for on-grid renewables are: wind $80-95/MWh, small hydro $45-60/MWh, and solar $150-180/MWh. This level is more attractive than neighboring countries such as Kazakhstan and China. In general, costs can be higher than in other countries due to transportation and limited know-how in the local market.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Power prices were low in Myanmar before 2018, but the new tariff, effective July 2018, raised the tariff for commercial and industrial users significantly (around 60% for commercial), in an attempt to better accommodate the development of renewable energy. The LCOE of solar and wind in Southeast Asia (Thailand as a benchmark) is still two to three times higher than of the U.S. or China. Residential power prices remain the same.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: According to the Nepal Electricity Authority (NEA)'s annual report, its average price of electricity sold is 8.14 rupees per kWh, whereas the average power tariff paid to generators is 7.52 rupees per kWh. There is no mechanism of tariff adjustment, so the price keeps relatively stable. The power price is relatively low compared to neighboring countries such as India, mainly because hydropower dominates Nepalese installed capacity and runs on lower marginal cost. This low-cost power also means that the willingness to expand power generation in Nepal is restricted. In fact, the NEA has reported losses for consecutive years. Asian Development Bank (ADB) conducted a policy dialogue with the NEA as early as 2016, which highlighted the need for tariff revisions on a regular basis.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Artificially low power prices, transmission and distribution losses and unpaid customer bills contribute to more than $10 billion of circular debt. In June 2019, the International Monetary Fund agreed to a 13th bailout for Pakistan worth $6 billion, focused on reducing debt in the power sector. Subsidy cuts on fuel and power tariffs are on the agenda. Consumers have already suffered several tariff increases since 2017, following an unstable electricity tariff policy. The government cuts tariffs to provide relief to consumers, only to raise prices months later to recover debt.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Electricity in the Philippines ranks among the most expensive in Southeast Asia. While costs are declining, it is happening at a slower rate than in neighboring countries. A lot of this is due to the country's location. Philippines is far from the sources of its imported fuels, and power prices reflect that. Economies of scale are difficult to tap because the country is made up of more than 7,000 islands. Adding to this are ratepayer subsidies and spending on off-grid and grid-extension projects, which bump up unsubsidized rates.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Singapore's power prices are linked to the price of oil; the city-state is 95% dependent on imported natural gas for generation, most of which is purchased at oil-linked prices. The average wholesale electricity price (Uniform Singapore Electricity Price or USEP) for 2018 was S$110/MWh ' a slight increase after years of price-depression caused by a large system reserve margin. The reserve margin stood at 80% in 2018 but is expected to fall to 58% in 2019, and go further down to 40% by 2022 following the retirement of 2,600MW of generation capacity. The liberalization of electricity retail in Singapore under the Open Electricity Market (OEM) regime in 2019 may mitigate somewhat the upward pressure on electricity bills from potentially higher wholesale prices emanating from declining reserve margins.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Sri Lanka has among the highest tariffs in the world for residential users (45 rupees/ 28 U.S. cents), which partly explains the rapid uptake of rooftop solar in households. Industrial and commercial segment tariffs are lower. Tariffs have not been revised since 2014.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Taiwan offers some of the world's cheapest retail power prices ' a deliberate government policy to benefit semiconductor and other manufacturing industries. In 2017, the residential tariff was the third lowest and the industrial tariff the sixth lowest according to Taipower, the vertically integrated utility that owns 64% of Taiwan's total power capacity, and the International Energy Agency. The utility raised the average retail tariff by 3% in April 2018 for the first time in four years; industry and large commercial companies will feel the brunt of the increase, while 80% of residents and small businesses are not affected. Adding new and more expensive renewables and gas generation will further stress Taipower's balance sheet as the cost cannot be fully passed on to end-consumers.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Tajikistan, like most former Soviet Union countries, has low power prices due to government subsidies. Its electricity rates are however higher than in the neighboring Kyrgyz Republic, and have been increasing for the past several years. The government has raised rates in an effort to improve the financial health of its main energy company, Barqi Tojik, but not all tariffs have increased. The Tajik Aluminum Co., for example, still has access to a special, subsidized electricity rate, even though it accounts for almost 20% of the country's power consumption.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Thailand's retail tariffs consist of a base tariff that is reviewed every three to five years and an adjustment tariff component that is reviewed every four months. The adjustment tariff reflects changes in fuel costs, electricity purchase cost and the impact of government policies. The costs of various renewable energy schemes are passed through to retail consumers and have contributed to an increase in retail tariffs over the years. Compared to neighboring countries such as Malaysia and Vietnam, retail tariffs in Thailand are higher. A drop in equipment costs globally, the establishment of domestic equipment production bases and a reduction in development and balance-of-plant costs as developers gained experience, have all contributed to a constant decline in the levelized cost of electricity for solar and wind in Thailand.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Subsidies for free, rationed electricity ended in 2018 and the government is attempting to force the installation of meters at every location. There are reports that the government is using police personnel to check for installations. Most citizens don't have the money to pay for meters or for electricity and may be jailed for not installing meters. The government is aiming to increase revenues, although it is unclear if the new policies have increased anything other than unrest.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Power prices have increased in recent years, although they are still quite heavily subsidized. Central Asia countries all have similar prices, and connections between them have been restored after they lapsed following the collapse of the Soviet Union, allowing for some imports and exports. Uzbekistan's old generation assets are in need of an upgrade in order to be able to meet peak power demand ' which outstrips supply in the peak winter periods, leading to power outages. The ability to raise power prices while such a situation continues may be limited, as outages are already leading to local protests. Generation is largely fueled by locally-produced natural gas ' so improvement in the costs of power will be made through improved efficiencies in power plants.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16:
Retail tariffs in Vietnam are heavily regulated and subsidized, and considered to be among the lowest in the Southeast Asian region. Retail tariffs below cost recovery levels challenged EVN's financial position. The tariffs remained almost flat from 2005 to 2010 and then began increasing until 2015, when they reached about $0.07/kWh. They were again flat in 2016 and 2017. In March 2019, average electricity retail tariffs increased by 8.36%. 

Coal is currently the cheapest source of generation in Vietnam, at $56-105/MWh. Vietnam's wind and solar industries are still in the early stages of development, with a limited domestic supply chain. However, interest from local and international developers is strong and the levelized cost of electricity for both solar and wind is expected to decrease as equipment costs fall globally and the industry matures.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Albania does not have a power exchange, but plans to implement one have been undertaken. Consumers are split into two classes: residential customers and small- to medium-sized commercial enterprises are eligible to receive a regulated electricity tariff, while large consumers negotiate their own rates. The tariffs are re-stated annually, while OSHEE, the supplier of electricity for regulated tariff customers, is under pressure from the World Bank's loan covenants to reduce its debt burden, potentially by increasing prices.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Prices are still partially regulated in Bosnia and Herzegovina ' particularly in the region of Republika Srpska. There is not yet complete economic dispatch in the wholesale market in the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina, meaning prices can be distorted. Residential tariffs are set below the cost-recovery point, which disincentivizes the private sector from investing new power plants. This state of affairs has contributed to the country being four times as energy intensive as the EU average. The highly subsidized residential sector amounts to more than half of final energy consumption. Tariffs have, however, been increasing in recent years.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16:
Georgia's electricity prices are fairly low due to legacy hydro assets. Customers with very low demand qualify for a below-market rate originally developed for disadvantaged consumers, but the subsidized tariff does not require means-testing and has been widely applied. 
However, some retail electricity prices have been rising in response to worsening winter supply constraints. The rate increases are focused on commercial and industrial customers. From 2015 to 2018, commercial electricity prices increased 30%, from $57.79MWh to $75.54MWh. In the same period, industrial prices doubled from $42.20MWh in 2015 to $84.62MWh in 2018. In contrast, residential rates declined 10%, from $57.38MWh in 2015 to $51.10MWh in 2018. While the cost of wind and solar is falling, it is not competitive with existing hydropower plants.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: North Macedonia has some of the lowest electricity prices in Europe, with residential bills amounting to less than half that of the European average. Tariffs are gradually increasing due to the progressing electrification of household heating. The country typically has been a net importer of electricity, relying on its neighbors for nearly a third of its electricity annually. A national power exchange and market coupling with Bulgaria are expected to bring more transparency to wholesale power prices.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: The fossil-fueled Kuchurgan power plant, controlled by Russia's Inter-Rao and located in the breakaway region of Transnistria, has maintained its near-monopoly supply status in Moldova, selling at a lower price than power imported from Ukraine's DTEK. Wholesale power prices in early 2019 averaged around 966 Moldovan leu (49 euros) per MWh, down from a peak of around 1,320 leu in 2015. This volatility is largely the result of annual and bi-annual negotiations with private suppliers. Industrial and commercial retail electricity rates in 2018 averaged 1.56 leu (0.08 euros) per kWh, while residential customers paid an average of 2 leu per kWh.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Russia benefits from some of the lowest electricity prices for residential, commercial and industrial customers compared to its neighbors, though prices vary significantly by region. This is a result of the low cost of energy resources, as natural gas makes up the majority of power generation and Russia has an abundance of cheap natural gas. That said, electricity prices are increasing at an annual rate of roughly 5%. Rates are also likely to continue to rise on the back of planned modernization works on Russia's ageing power fleet.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Commercial, retail and industrial power-price reforms were introduced in 2015. Previously, tariffs were set below the cost-recovery point for the state utility, EPS. The reforms also helped Serbia align with the EU's accession requirements. For end-users, it meant sharp increases in tariffs in 2016 and 2017, although in 2018 prices for consumers of all sizes only increased by 1-2%. Serbia's feed-in tariffs are over twice the average wholesale price in 2017, and between one-to-two times the commercial and industrial rates.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Power prices in Turkey have risen over the last five years, but are still kept low through intervention in the market. Wholesale power prices do not allow power producers to recoup their costs, which are rising along with fuel prices and heightened currency fluctuation. Gas plants especially struggle as the  gas supply has been strained, and resources are diverted toward heat and away from power. BNEF's levelized cost estimate for coal power in Turkey is still the lowest across technologies, due to its high capacity factor, but it does not have the same downward trajectory that wind and PV LCOEs have followed in Turkey over the last five years. Financing costs remain high, however, across all technologies, keeping LCOEs from falling as rapidly as in other regions.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Power prices in Ukraine were regulated until the introduction of a wholesale market in 2019. New market rules have not brought full liberalization, however, as some state-owned power is price-capped to keep residential electricity tariffs low. The wholesale market is still heavily concentrated and dominated by fossil fuel plants owned by DTEK. To avoid excessive volatility, the wholesale market is operated with price caps. Both thermal and nuclear plants are in need of investment for renewal and life extension. It is unclear how this will be funded and how retail prices will change if and when price caps are lifted.  Ukraine's situation is further complicated by a shortfall in coal supplies from the east of the country, which has been destabilized by conflict with Russia. Coal imports have partially compensated for this, while some plants are retrofitting to run on gas instead.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Since Macri took power, electricity prices have spiked, as customer subsidies have been cut. Since 2015, industrial prices grew by 1,054%, while residential and commercial increased by 1,041% and 911% by end-2018, respectively. CAMMESA, the governmental market regulator, regulates tariffs and is also the offtaker for the RenovAr auctions. Auction bids dedicated to large-scale projects have consistently dropped in each round, averaging $59.6/MWh in the first, $54/MWh in the second, and $42.4/MWh in the last round.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Bolivia's electricity prices are set by the government and, as a natural gas producer, dependent on heavily subsidized gas-powered generation. However, only 67% of the 9.9TWh generated in 2018 came from gas plants, compared to 72% from the previous year. The share of hydro-powered generation has increased from 23% to 26% and the share of solar generation has increased from 0.1% to 1.3%. Electricity prices continue to rise, although rates remain low compared to most countries in Latin America. In 2018, the average retail electricity price was $0.12/kWh, up 4.5% from 2017.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Retail electricity prices (in local currency terms) jumped an average of 81% between 2010 and 2018 for the three customer classes of commercial, industrial and residential. This was mainly due to inflation and decreased hydropower generation. In 2018, Brazil's retail tariffs were among the six highest in Latin America, at $195/MWh for commercial, $168/MWh for industrial and $196/MWh for residential. Commercial and industrial (C&I) customers with power demand greater than 500kW are eligible to purchase electricity from Brazil's deregulated wholesale market. Consumers with demand between 500kW and 3MW choosing this option must purchase wholesale power generated from incentivized renewable sources, including wind, small hydro, biomass and solar.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: In Chile, spot prices are determined by the node of delivery, which takes into account the marginal operating costs of nodal plants as well as nodal demand. Wholesale prices have shown high volatility in recent years during the day. In 2018, wholesale prices slipped to zero at times during midday, while shooting back to $60/MWh at night. The same pattern was observed in previous years, but the situation has improved since the interconnection of the country's main power subsystems, SIC (Sistema Interconectado Central) and SING   (Sistema Interconectado del Norte Grande). The tariff is based on peak load pricing, where consumers pay a price according to the demand. Average national commercial, industrial and residential tariffs rose slightly in 2018 to $224/MWh, $158/MWh and $197/MWh, respectively.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16:
Colombia is highly dependent on hydroelectric sources, with 70% of generation supplied from hydro on average annually since 2010. Prices are subject to upward pressure from extreme weather, as seen in 2015-16 when a pronounced El Nino effect was observed. Despite that spike, from 2013 to 2016 the country saw an average 30% reduction in retail power prices, across all customer classes. The El Nino draught resulted in an increase of 30% in commercial electricity prices from 2016-2017, from $100.21 to $132.13/MWh; 6% in industrial rates, from $97.03 to $103.56/MWh; and 19% in residential prices, from $123.18 to $147.63/MWh. 
In 2018, commercial electricity was the only tariff that decreased compared to 2017,  from $132.13 to $115.49/MWh. Industrial electricity prices rose from $103.56 to $105.49/MWh, while residential prices increased from $147.63 to $153.97/MWh.
Given Colombia's reliance on large hydro and historically minor progress in developing non-hydro renewable sources, its wholesale power price has been volatile. From 2017 to 2018, wholesale prices spiked 77%, from $36.53 to $64.92/MWh.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Costa Rican electricity prices rose in 2016 due to heavy use of diesel-fired generation to satisfy a 6.6% increase in electricity demand. Prices fell in 2017 but started rising again in 2018. The average commercial price was the most volatile, averaging $203.09/MWh in 2016, $179.8/MWh in 2017 and $186.9/MWh in 2018. Residential and industrial prices increased about 3% from 2017 to 2018.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: The Dominican Republic's residential power prices averaged $133.80/MWh in 2018 compared to $152.49/MWh in 2015.  Commercial prices fell over this period from $217/MWh in 2015 to $176.60/MWh in 2018. Average industrial prices decreased from $210.69/MWh in 2015 to $145.80/MWh in 2018. In contrast, wholesale prices jumped from $96/MWh in 2015 to $141/MWh in 2018, representing an increase of 46% over the period. The culprit was retail rate subsidies, which are estimated to have cost $479 million in 2018 alone. With the commissioning of the Punta Catalina thermal power plant in 2019, the government foresees a reduction in electricity prices and subsidies.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Commercial and residential power prices have decreased $0.20/MWh from 2017 to 2018, the tariffs were $103.90/MWh (commercial) and $101.50/MWh (residential). The most expressive reduction was for the industrial tariffs, from $94.90/MWh in 2017 to $80.10 in 2018, more than 15% lower. Ecuador has among of the lowest retail electricity rates in Latin America.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: From 2015 to 2016, commercial, residential, industrial and wholesale electricity prices in El Salvador decreased on average by 20%. However, dry conditions in 2016 that reduced hydroelectric reservoir levels led to increased generation from fossil fuels, causing electricity prices to rise in 2017 and 2018. Commercial prices increased 8% from $199/MWh in 2016 to $215/MWh in 2018. Residential and wholesale prices increased by 20% and 23%, respectively, over the same period, while industrial prices rose by 17%.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Guatemala's average residential electricity price increased 4% between 2016 and 2018, from $227 to $237/MWh. Commercial prices increased 9% from $145/MWh in 2016 to $158/MWh in 2018, while industrial rates rose from $140/MWh in 2016 to $154/MWh in 2018. Guatemalan retail power prices are among the highest in Latin America.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Electricity prices in Haiti have remained flat since 2009. The residential tariff was the lowest, presenting an average of $112.03/MWh. The commercial and industrial electricity prices in 2018 were of $194.56/MWh and $198.25/MWh, respectively.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Electricity prices in Honduras have risen from 2017 to 2019, affecting residential rates the most. Its average price jumped from $138.48/MWh in 2017 to $154.94/MWh in 2019. This was due to the end of the subsidy for consumers of up to 300kWh, which benefited 1.6 million ratepayers. Commercial prices increased from $163.27/MWh in 2017 to $169.23/MWh in 2018, while industrial prices were the least affected, rising 1% from $131.03/MWh in 2017 to $132.63/MWh in 2018.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Jamaica has the most expensive electricity in Latin America. In 2018, commercial electricity prices increased 28%, from $213.79/MWh in 2016 to $273.20/MWh. Industrial electricity prices rose 30% in 2018 compared to 2016, reaching $218.73/MWh. The residential price increased 27%, from $243.17/MWh in 2016 to $309.49/MWh in 2018.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16:
Residential power prices rose in 2018, but historically Mexican consumers have enjoyed among the lowest subsidized rates in the region. Mexico's reserve margin, which is about 6% and has been falling in recent years, and rising load growth, which was 2.9% year-on-year in 2018, are expected to offset planned capacity additions and so keep prices high. The Mexican market is also characterized by relatively high wholesale prices overall, with both day-ahead and real-time prices rising steadily. 
Power in Mexico remains heavily weighted towards fossil fuels, with natural gas, oil and coal together accounting for over 70% of total installed capacity in 2018. Rising prices in the wholesale market attest to the role played by costly thermal generation, with a growing reliance on expensive fuel oil and imported liquefied natural gas (LNG) from the U.S. Off-takers with a load center of at least 1MW are classified as 'qualified users' and are allowed to purchase electricity directly from qualified suppliers. There are now six such qualified suppliers active in the wholesale market, including CFE Calificados, the subsidiary of state power utility Comisin Federal de Electricidad (CFE). CFE continues to be the supplier of basic retail services to residential customers and small and medium-sized commercial customers under regulated tariffs. Regulator CRE sets the final retail and last-resort supply tariffs based on the cost of energy and ancillary services required.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Electricity prices in Nicaragua rose slightly from 2016 to 2018, when industrial tariffs rose from $192 to $194/MWh. Commercial electricity prices are the second highest in Latin America and the Caribbean at $253/MWh, only after Jamaica's. Residential tariffs are significantly lower at $194/MWh, but still appear among the top seven most expensive tariffs in the region. Nicaragua's high retail prices are largely due to its dependence on imported fossil fuels for generation. Renewables development represents a path to greater energy independence for the country.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Most of Panama's electricity generation comes from fossil fuel and hydro (large and small). From 2016-2018, commercial power prices grew from $174/MWh to $185/MWh, industrial prices increased from $168 to $181/MWh, and residential prices moved from $153 to $162/MWh. The wholesale price increased from $59.19/MWh in 2016 to $76.70/MWh in 2018.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: In 2018, Paraguay's average residential electricity prices increased 11%, moving from $64.40/MWh in 2016 to $71.59/MWh in 2018. Industrial prices jumped 31% over the period, and commercial prices rose 7.6%. Despite the increases, Paraguay's electricity prices are the lowest in Latin America due to the excess of hydroelectricity.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: From 2016 to 2018, power prices in Peru rose an average of 10%.  Industrial electricity was the most inflationary, increasing 12%, from $79.71/MWh in 2016 to $89.68/MWh in 2018. Commercial and residential rates were respectively $106.40/MWh and $137.57/MWh in 2016, rising to $117.95/MWh and $150.14/MWh in 2018.  Even after recent increases, Peru's electricity prices rank among the cheapest in Latin America.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: As Uruguay is heavily dependent on hydropower, auctions have been a key mechanism to diversify the power matrix. From 2009 to 2016, the country contracted over 300MW of wind through auctions. As a result, wind generation jumped 32 times, from 144GWh in 2013 to 4,732GWh in 2018. However, due to the increase of intermittent generation combined with level demand, the country is starting to have curtailment issues.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Electricity tariffs in Egypt may still be low by global standards but they have risen significantly in recent years, as the government has sought to cut subsidy costs. Industrial prices have increased the most ' by a compound annual growth rate of 30% for 2012-18 ' while residential and commercial tariffs have climbed 15-28% over the same period. The efforts to reduce fuel and electricity subsidies are a condition of the country's three-year, $12-billion loan program from the International Monetary Fund. The government has said that electricity subsidies will be phased out by the end of June 2022 (three years later than planned). However, it has a tough task to balance these economic reforms with the need to ensure social stability, with over a quarter of the population living below the poverty line.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: The government subsidizes electricity and fuel prices, giving Iraqis some of the cheapest prices in the world. The supply of electricity is unreliable and available for less than 15 hours a day. This has forced consumers to turn to private, predominantly diesel, generators for supply. Cheap electricity has led to very high consumption, with each household consuming twice as much on average as in neighbouring Jordan. As a result, electricity subsidies cost the Iraqi government 3.4% of GDP each year while fuel subsidies cost it 3.6%. The government has introduced a progressive tariff increase to reduce the subsidy and encourage efficient consumption of electricity.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Prices for consumers in Jordan are subsidized. Commercial consumers have traditionally paid the highest electricity prices, subsidizing residential consumers. This led to a rise in behind-the-meter projects, with 415MW of small-scale solar installed as of 2019. Wheeling projects have been discouraged slightly through lower prices set for commercial consumers. These changes have not stemmed financial losses at state-owned National Electric Power Co., which is already heavily indebted, and electricity prices across sectors are expected to continue to rise.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Consumption of energy is heavily subsidized in Kuwait. Electricity prices are among the lowest in the Middle East. These subsidies distort the allocation of resources by encouraging excessive consumption, accelerating the depletion of natural resources and undermining the growth potential of renewables. This results in the highest per capita energy consumption in the world. The government increased electricity prices for the residential (expatriates only) and commercial sectors in Kuwait in 2017. However, electricity prices are much lower than the cost of generation, and the subsidy level is still very high even after the price increase. There's more to be done to encourage rational use of electricity and investment in the renewable sector.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: The government subsidizes electricity prices in the form of cheap diesel and heavy fuel oil for the state utility, lectricit du Liban (EDL), which sells electricity to the grid significantly below its cost of generation. The World Bank estimates that this massive strain on public finances is responsible for 40% of all government debt since 1992, two years before retail tariffs were frozen. However, any movement toward more cost-reflective power prices remains politically untenable. EDL's inability to meet electrical demand has spawned a large fleet of private diesel generators. These supply the grid during the daily blackouts, which may last three hours in Beirut and up to 12 hours in rural areas. Despite their illegality, these generators contribute an estimated 23% of all electricity. The PPA for the first round of wind auctions was at $113/MWh. The LCOE of solar PV in Lebanon will likely be competitive in the context of the country's diesel-dominated power sector. By 2018, small-scale PV solutions already totaled around 60MW, with more in development as solar cost continue to drop.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Similar to other countries in the region, Oman's electricity prices are highly subsidized for residents. Prices paid by consumers were static from the early 1990s until 2017 and only covered about 54% of production costs. In 2017, the country introduced a cost-reflective tariff that removed subsidies for customers whose yearly use exceeds 150MWh (effectively commercial customers), charging them set prices based on typical demand profiles for the season and time of day. The intent was to incentivize conservation efforts by customers and had the effect of raising prices paid in total. In order to increase cash flow, the government decided to incentivize residential customers to install rooftop solar PV panels rather than decreasing subsidies. This will effectively cut their usage costs by around 40% while also decreasing the amount of subsidy paid. The power market is not competitive and prices paid for fuel and generated electricity are all set by various government agencies, acting in an orchestrated manner. Comparison of levelized costs of energy is therefore somewhat irrelevant.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: The country's energy prices have long been subsidized well below regional and international levels. They are, however, on the rise ' with the most recent increase implemented at the beginning of 2018. While commercial and industrial tariffs did not increase by much, residential tariffs more than tripled. The target is for energy prices to reach international levels by 2020. In the first round of NREP auctions, the winning bid for the aforementioned 300MW solar tender by local player Acwa Power came in at $2.36/MWh. Acwa was selected over an EDF bid of $1.78/MWh. While awarded projects do not usually include the costs relating to land acquisition or connecting the projects to the grid, the Saudi government will take over these costs in the first round of auctions. It is unclear whether such an arrangement will also stay in place for future tenders.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: U.A.E. solar tenders have attracted headlines for record low tariffs: June 2016 saw the Dubai Electricity and Water Authority (DEWA) announce the $29/MWh price agreed on with the Masdar-led grouping chosen to complete the 800MW third phase of the Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum Solar Park. The project's fourth stage, adding 700MW of solar thermal capacity, was awarded to a consortium of Chinese and Saudi investors with a 35-year PPA price of $0.073/kWh ' by far the lowest for the technology. The Emirates Water and Electricity Co. (EWEC) awarded the Noor Abu Dhabi 1.17GW to a joint venture of Marubeni and JinkoSolar at a low tariff of $24/MWh. Retail electricity tariffs are the Gulf's highest and are independently set by the four utilities.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Electricity in the Palestinian Territories is expensive compared to its neighbors. Most power is imported from Israel, and Palestinian consumers pay the same retail prices as set by the Israel Electric Co., despite the higher standard of living in Israel compared to Palestine. Power prices are determined by the regulator, and although they are high, Palestinian distribution companies (which are also the retailers) are unable to fully recoup their costs. Consumers are able to install rooftop solar panels, and high power prices incentivize their uptake.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column16: Qatar's electricity prices are on par or lower than those of their neighbors. Much of this is due to heavy subsidies from the government and in some cases, free access to electricity. Prices might increase in the future as the government looks to set up a wholesale electricity market and remove certain subsidies it deems unsustainable. The levelized cost of electricity remains low. The country runs on power generated from natural gas, a fuel that is abundant in the region.

column4: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs
column5: BNEF Take: Power prices and LCOEs

column16: Algeria opened up generation to competition in 2002, but the sector has remained dominated by Sonelgaz. The state-owned utility's dominance is ensured by its access to the country's abundant gas resources, whose cheap procurement has prevented the emergence of competitive independent power producers (IPP). The Sonelgaz group is the sole authorized retailer of power on the country's three grids. However, consumers are free to procure their own electricity through self-generation or power purchase agreements (PPA). Increasingly cheap solar technology, the high cost of diesel generation and unreliable grid power have created a favorable environment for small-scale renewables.

Much of Angola's infrastructure was destroyed during its 27-year civil war, which ended in 2002, and had to be rebuilt and refurbished. A significant investment program has increased generation capacity from 700MW in 2002 to around 5.3GW in 2018. The country saw capacity grow 22% in 2018 as a result of the commissioning of the 750MW Soyo gas plant and additional phases of the Lauca hydroelectric dam. When fully commissioned, the flagship $4.3 billion Lauca will become the largest hydropower plant in Southern Africa, alongside Mozambique's CahoraBassa. Restructuring of the sector began in 2014 and has sought to strengthen the role of an independent regulator, IRSEA (Instituto Regulador do Sector Electrico). It has also sought to unbundle the power market, creating PRODEL-EP on the generation side, together with RNT and ENDE as the transmission- and distribution-system operators. Generation and distribution/retail are technically open to private participation, but private players have not entered either market yet. The power network is still fragmented across three regional grids (North, Central, and South) and some isolated systems, though the primary North-Central-South backbone connection is under way as of mid-2019.

Benin relies on thermal generation, with a heavy dependence on neighboring countries. In March 2019, the 120MW Maria Gleta II Heavy Fuel Oil and Gas plant began operating, and the country still has virtually no renewable energy projects to date aside from a 500-kilowatt hydro project. The planned PV projects should help Benin to reduce its energy dependence by building up local energy capacity. Benin is also trying to diversify supply through the construction of a Floating Storage Regasification Unit in the port of Cotonou to supply the 300MW dual fuel Maria Gl'ta power plants starting from 2020. Finally, Benin is also planning additional electricity transmission interconnections within the regional market. So far, the grid has mostly served the south of the country, whereas the northern part of Benin is relatively isolated and has limited access to cost-efficient sources of energy.

Botswana's power sector is dominated by coal, accounting for 79% of the current installed capacity. By contrast, solar PV accounts for just 0.1%, although this is expected to change with the development of a 100MW solar project that was re-issued in May 2019. Botswana has gradually weaned itself off dependency on imports from the SAAP, and it now imports only 23% of the distributed power nationally. There is only one operational 1.3MW solar plant in the country and renewables do not benefit from purchase obligation as BPC buys all the power available regardless of sector.

Currently, the Botswana Power Corporation is the sole provider of generation, transmission, distribution and retail services. However BPC is looking to transform itself into a transmission and distribution utility, and move away from being a fully-integrated utility. Independent power producers (IPP) have been allowed to enter the market since 2007 but have only began to expand into the generation market in the last two year with the signing of two PPAs' for the Morupule B Coal plant and a 1MW solar plant in 2017.

Power generation in Burkina Faso is dominated by thermal plants that run on expensive imported fuel. Sonabel has tried to keep up with rising demand by ramping up generation and by importing electricity, with imports rising from 145GWh in 2009 to 837GWh in 2018. The power sector is partly liberalized and divided in two segments, of which the first covers urban areas where Sonabel has a monopoly over all power market segments. Although generation is open to private actors, no IPPs are active. The second segment covers rural areas, where local cooperatives (COOPELs) are responsible, overseen by the rural electrification agency ABER. In this segment, the private sector may operate generation and off-grid distribution projects. The offtaker can be commercial, as in the case of the Essakane PV plant.

The renewable energy installed capacity is dominated by small hydro power plants (55%), followed by natural gas (34%) solar PV (6%) and biomass (5%). The capital Bujumbura accounts for 95% of electricity consumed. Besides its national generation, Burundi also imports electricity from neighboring countries, Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) and Rwanda, through a cross-border hydropower complex. The power sector continues to be dominated by Regideso, which has a monopoly for electricity transmission, distribution and supply. Transmission, distribution and generation infrastructure is old and needs further modernization and investment.

Large hydro dominates the capacity mix, followed by fossil fuels. Cameroon was one of the first countries in Africa to open its electricity sector to private-sector participation, and in 2001, AES became majority shareholder of the utility (then called Sonel).
