A new reform phase began in 2011 with the unbundling of generation, transmission and distribution. Sonel was acquired by Actis in 2014, and rebranded as Eneo. A 2015 decree split the transmission and system operation components to create the state-owned Sonatrel, which decides on dispatch and is a single buyer for grid-connected generation. Eneo dominates generation, but two IPPs operate the two main thermal plants. The legal framework for electricity needs significant review, which has now begun following the October 2018 elections.

Most electricity generation comes from dated small hydro systems, the oldest of which has been operating since the mid-1950s. These systems are poorly maintained and break down often. The national grid only extends to the capital Bangui. There are supplementary diesel-powered generation units, but these are small and only account for a fraction of total power generation. There is an interconnection with the Democratic Republic of Congo, but this is inactive due to degradation. State-owned utility Enerca dominates the generation, distribution and retail of electricity, despite all three segments being liberalized for competition. So far, however, no independent power producers have emerged, likely due to the dire security situation in the country. There are plans to introduce further laws to facilitate competition, but none have yet been made public.

Chad's current generation fleet is exclusively powered by fossil fuels. Procurement, transmission and distribution are the state utility's prerogative, but independent producers can sell their own output, with Socit Nationale d'Electricit du Tchad (SNE) purchasing electricity from a 20MW thermal plant owned and operated by VPower, as well as NRC's 20MW thermal plant. Vergnet's aforementioned wind plant does not seem to be generating power so far. A further IPP, Aggreko, entered the market in mid-2019 with a 24MW heavy fuel oil plant. SNE is the sole procurer of all power generation, so corporations are unable to purchase the own energy via power purchase agreements. A law setting out more detailed regulations for IPPs, which clarifies the procedures and penalties, remains stuck in the National Assembly.

Thermal power constitutes just over half of installed capacity in Congo, primarily provided by a 300MW gas plant in Pointe Noire owned by Italian developer Eni and the Congolese state. Large hydro also accounts for a sizeable slice of generation through the Imboulou (120MW) and Moukoukoulou (74MW) dams. No non-hydro renewables capacity has been installed to date, with new projects in the pipeline exclusively comprising large hydro projects or the expansion of the Pointe Noire gas plant. The four segments of the power sector are dominated by private utility E2C (Energie Electrique du Congo), which was a public enterprise running by the name of Societe Nationale d'Electricite until June 2018. Power generation was opened up to private power producers in 2003, but regulations concerning private generation still remain unclear, with the only semi-independent power producer to date being Eni's gas plant. The plant's power purchase agreement must be renegotiated following the change in E2C's legal status.

Hydropower supplies the vast majority of the DRC's electricity needs and the Congo River has significant potential for further dam development. As yet, there are no utility-scale wind and solar projects, although there is some evidence this could change: Copperbelt Energy has announced plans for two PV plants to feed electricity to copper and cobalt mines in the country. Volt renewable energy has also announced a 500MW solar development project with the SNEL, the national utility provider. Power generation still largely rests in the hands of state-controlled utility SNEL, which owns and operates 94% of installed capacity in the DRC. Independent power producers own just 6% of total generating capacity, at 135MW, which is mostly used for mining activities.

Cote d'Ivoire was one of the first African countries to liberalize power generation ' opening up the sector to independent power producers in 1994. Three companies that own and operate gas plants account for more than half of installed capacity, with state-owned hydro-electric dams making up most of the rest. Compagnie Ivoirienne d'Electricit (CIE), one of Africa's few utilities not owned by the state, retains a monopoly over electricity purchase, transmission and retail. However, things may change following the renewal of CIE's contract with the state in 2020. The government's focus is on thermal assets for the time being ' a coal plant is being built, the gas fleet is being upgraded and an LNG terminal is under construction. On the renewables side, some 190MW of PV will be commissioned by 2020 and a 46MW biogas project is due online in 2022.

To date, the vast majority of installed capacity in Eritrea runs on imported fossil fuels. State-utility EEC dominates all segments of the power market and there is little transparency on the regulatory framework governing the energy sector in the country. A handful of independent power producers are active, with little transparency on their arrangements with EEC. Eritrea has no interconnection with its neighbors, although this could change in coming years, due to its improving relations with Ethiopia.

Ethiopia Electric Power (EEP) currently owns all generation and transmission in the country and Ethiopia Electric Utility (EEU) is responsible for distribution. The roll-out of a public-private partnerships law will allow independent power producers to negotiate PPAs directly with EEP. Along with plans to tender out renewable generation, such as the Scaling Solar Initiative, these policies will go a long way in diversifying Ethiopia's power mix. Nearly 90% of capacity in Ethiopia currently comes from hydro, and the country has suffered from load shedding due to drought. A diversified power mix will also be essential in ensuring reliability for the country's growing commercial and industrial sector ' 13 industrial parks are under development in Ethiopia, expected to grow power demand by 1.5-2GW.

The generation sector has several independent power producers operating plants together with state-owned companies such as Volta River Authority (VRA). State-owned Ghana Grid Co. (Gridco) is the sole company that owns and operates the transmission system. Distribution is carried out by the Electricity Company of Ghana (ECG), the Northern Electricity Distribution Co. (Nedco) and Enclave Power Co. ECG had to be rescued through concession by Meralco, the Philippine electricity company. The concession is aimed to turn around the poor finances of ECG and increase investment in the Ghanaian grid. Some 62.5% of generation was sourced from oil and gas in 2018, and 37.2% was from hydro. Renewable energy is largely confined to two utility-scale PV plants, with little prospect of new projects in the near future. On-site solar for commercial, industrial and public premises has been gradually penetrating since 2017.

Around two-thirds of generating capacity is derived from small and large hydropower, with the completion of the aforementioned Kal'ta project in 2015 effectively quadrupling the country's installed large hydro capacity. Hydropower capacity is set to scale up with a series of dams in the pipeline, including the 450MW Souapiti project. The remainder of Guinea's electricity fleet is oil and diesel-fired. There are plans to develop offshore gas fields, but reserves remain unproven. Efforts to liberalize the power market are driven by the prospect of trading competitively within the West African Power Pool and the first two of four planned interconnection lines should be completed by 2021. To date, generation is the only segment of the power market open to private players, with state utility EDG generating 90% of all electricity.

The liberalization of the generation market has seen more than 10 independent power producers cut into KenGen's market share. The government has also mandated Ketraco to compete with Kenya Power on transmission. In March 2019, the president signed the Energy Bill 2017, which liberalized the electricity retail market on paper. But, the market has been so far monopolized by Kenya Power in practice and it would take another year or more to set up detailed regulations. Large hydro and geothermal are the two main sources of Kenya's generation mix. The share of non-large hydro renewables generation reached 52.3% in 2018, with some contribution from Lake Turkana wind and Garissa solar plants that started operation late in the year.

In 2018, Lesotho imported 30% of its power from neighboring South Africa. While its domestic fleet is composed entirely of hydro, South Africa's grid is composed of 90% coal power. Between its domestic production and imports, Lesotho's average carbon intensity is about 0.218 CO2 kg/KWh. Expansion of its domestic fleet with renewable energy will diminish import volumes and lower the carbon footprint of the power sector. The country has a strong financial incentive to do so, as imported electricity costs 10 times as much as domestically produced power.

LEC is a state-owned monopoly responsible for generation, transmission, distribution, retail and system operation in Liberia. The utility owns and operates a small fleet of mostly hydroelectric generators, including the 88MW Mount Coffee Hydropower Plant, which was returned to service in December 2016 after being offline for 26 years through civil turmoil and the ebola outbreak. LEC also procures power from independent producers ' mostly embedded diesel generators. The LEC grid is concentrated around Monrovia and the remainder of the country is not electrified, with microgrid regulation in the process of being set up. Liberia receives 8MW of power from neighboring Cote d'Ivoire and will receive an additional 27MW once the West Africa Power Pool is complete.

More than three-quarters of Madagascar's installed capacity is powered by fossil fuels, with the remainder accounted for by small hydro and solar, at 2% of installed capacity. Renewable energy additions have stagnated in the past few years, compared with the growth rate of new thermal capacity. For more than a decade, the generation sector has been opened up to independent power producers and there is a clear intention to attract more private and international investment to the industry. Independent companies can also sell power through direct sales or within rural electrification concessions, although experience in this segment remains limited. The typical PPA guarantees a volume and number of run hours to the generator for up to 20 years.

All of Malawi's electricity generation comes from hydropower plants situated on the Shire River. In recent years, low water levels and debris clogs in the river have significantly reduced electricity output and caused severe load shedding. Malawi has no significant interconnection to neighboring countries, making the energy deficit worse. Plans are in place to connect Malawi to the Southern Africa Power Pool by 2021, which should finally make power imports possible. In 2016, the generation market opened up to IPPs and since then, PPAs have been signed for some 200 MW of new renewable generation. However, nothing has been built yet. With no IPP assets yet operational, Malawi's central generation utility EGENCO owns all generation, while its counterpart ESCOM owns transmission and distribution assets. ESCOM is the market's single offtaker.

Just under half of Mali's power generation runs on fossil fuels and the remainder is supplied by hydropower. All segments of the power market have been liberalized since 2000, yet EDM dominates generation, transmission, distribution and retail. In rural areas, authorized mini-grid operators can sell power. Most of this capacity is fossil-heavy, but there is an increasing number of hybrid projects. While tendering processes are yet to be standardized, the first clean energy projects have been awarded successfully. In 2015, the government issued two PV tenders for the development of a 25MW project in Koutiala and a 50MW in Sikasso. In August 2019, the rural electrification agency announced a tender for two solar PV plants totaling 1.3MW, in addition to a 1.5MW energy storage system.

Thermal plants account for the majority of Mauritania's installed capacity at 71%. Since 2013, however, clean energy capacity has steadily increased, with a handful of solar PV and wind plants in the pipeline. The power sector is not yet liberalized, with all segments of the power sector remaining under Somelec control. In rural areas, however, operators with a concession may participate in power generation, distribution and retail. Solar PV-diesel hybrid projects are increasing in popularity, with a number of 2-6MW projects having been brought online, most recently at Kiffa and N'ma. Expanding renewables capacity and the discovery of offshore gas have made the government eager to begin selling energy to its neighbors.

Coal is the largest sector in Morocco's power mix, accounting for 39% of capacity and more than 62% of generation as of 2018. The coal sector has added more than 2.4GW of capacity since 2011 with 1.3GW added in 2018. In the context of total capacity growth of 35%, renewables capacity has remained constant at around 34% for the last five years. Wind and solar capacity has more than tripled from 5% to 18% since 2011, and additions of a further 2GW of renewable capacity in the coming years will push this to the target of 42% by 2020. Recent years have been poor for hydroelectric generation, and total renewables generation has been flat at around 16% but grew to 20% in 2018. This has hidden an underlying growth in solar and wind generation from only 3% in 2010 to 14% in 2018. The Moroccan state utility, ONEE, still holds a monopoly over the transmission network and is involved in all sales of electricity in Morocco. ONEE also accounts for around a third of total generation, and more than half of the distribution and retail sectors of the power market.

Mozambique's power market is structured around Electricidade de Mo'ambique (EDM), a state-owned and vertically integrated utility responsible for the transmission, distribution and sale of electricity. All power consumers in Mozambique must buy electricity from EDM, which oversees 20% of the country's generating capacity, but purchases power produced by IPPs and the 2.1GW Cahora Bassa Hydro (HCB). The latter is majority owned by the Mozambican state (92.5%). Some 90% of the plant's generation is exported, mostly to South Africa. Cahora Bassa's vast size means that hydroelectric generation dominates Mozambique's power sector, representing 70% of the capacity mix in 2018. A new draft electricity law is expected to overhaul the sector, streamlining the legal framework and clarifying licensing for generation, transmission and distribution. A new regulator, Arene, was stood up in 2017 but is not yet fully operational and will require support to become a strong and independent regulatory body.

The Ruacana hydro plant dominates Namibia's power fleet, accounting for 58% of installed capacity. Namibia has some of the strongest solar resources in the world, thanks to its proximity to the equator and its arid climate.  Single-axis tracking solar PV projects have achieved an annual capacity factor of over 30.2%. High capacity factors and advances in solar technology have contributed to a swift decline in the levelized cost of solar. BloombergNEF's levelized cost estimates suggest they have halved for solar in sub-Saharan Africa between 2015 and 2019 (from $107/MWh to $53/MWh).
Low costs and high output have contributed to Solar PV's rapid growth in Namibia, which has seen a doubling of solar capacity each year between 2014 and 2018. Solar PV currently represents 13% of installed capacity.
At the moment, Nampower is the only offtaker with which IPPs can sign PPAs. However, the Electricity Control Board, the regulator, wants to switch from a single buyer model to a modified single buyer model, where IPPs can sell directly to local distributors and large consumers, and potentially also export power.

Niger's power demand is predominantly met through energy imports from Nigeria and its market is dominated by state utility Nigelec. The Electricity Act of 2016 opened up power generation to the private sector, with IPPs also being able to enter transmission and distribution if granted a concession. The only independent producer to date is Sonichar, which supplies the northern zone of Niger through a 32MW coal-fired power plant. Several solar projects are either in the process of construction or remain in the pipeline, and investment in non-renewable generation is set to continue. The 130MW hydroelectric Kandadji dam faces repeated delays and construction is ongoing on the 600MW Sakaldamna coal plant.

Nigeria has no non-hydro renewable energy installed on-grid. Of the 13.5GW total capacity, 84.7% is accounted for by natural gas, 14.5% large hydro, 0.7% off-grid small hydro and 0.1% off-grid distributed PV. Only 7.5GW of the installed capacity is actually available, of which Nigeria generates an annual average of around 3.5 to 4.5GW of electricity.
Generation is fully privatized, transmission is government-owned, and distribution is private but with only 11 regional players.
Nigeria aims to create an enabling environment for increasing grid capacity. As of April 2018, distributors must provide metered billing as opposed to the estimated billing system previously in place, in accordance with new regulation.

Rwanda's power mix is based heavily on hydro, at just under 50% as of December 2018, but other technologies, such as solar, natural gas and diesel, are also represented. Since 2010, the country saw installed capacity grow 170%, reaching 222MW in 2018. State-owned Energy Development Corp. has been the most prominent developer, but there are a multitude of private players involved in Rwanda's generation sector. The country has an oversupply of on-grid generation, as well as a backlog of contracted projects. As a result, new developers will not be able to secure permitting until the roughly 200MW of generation projects with existing contracts are commissioned. The country is instead focusing near-term investment into transmission and distribution, both of which are fully controlled by REG.

Only power generation has been liberalized in Senegal, with transmission and distribution remaining vertically-integrated. Independent power producers, such as APR and Aggreko, operate a larger fleet than that of state-owned utility Senelec. The 1.1GW power mix is dominated by oil and diesel, with large hydro, oil, natural gas and coal accounting for the remainder. Additional power is imported from two dams in Mali. A renewables transition is underway, with143MW of solar installed since 2016 and a 158MW wind farm to be commissioned by 2020. However, government support for future additions is likely to be tempered by the discovery of major gas reserves off Senegal's coast, with extraction set to begin in 2022. A pivot back toward thermal energy is also under-way, as the government plans to convert oil plants to dual-fuel and to build several new combined-cycle gas turbines.

Sierra Leone's National Electricity Act separated the Electricity Board into two state-owned entities: the Electricity Generation and Transmission Corp. (EGTC) and Electricity Distribution and Supply Authority (EDSA) in 2011. The country's power system is extremely dependent on seasonal hydro generation operated by EGTC and procured by EDSA through PPAs approved by regulators. EDSA can also procure power through PPAs with independent power producers, but the weak economic and political environment is not conducive to building new power projects. 
The arrival of the Karpowership, a floating power plant, in Freetown Harbor in late 2017 has relieved some stress on system and power prices, but issues remain. There has been no progress on planned solar projects as yet.

The population of Somalia relies on traditional biomass for its basic energy needs due to an unreliable power supply. Electricity suppliers that do operate mostly run on diesel generators, although PV systems are starting to penetrate the market, mainly in Somaliland. The initial investment required for a diesel generator is still lower in some cases than a PV system, so adding PV to an existing diesel system is proving popular among small IPPs. Many electricity service providers operating in Somaliland have specific plans to add renewables to their existing diesel infrastructure.

Eskom, the state-owned utility, dominates the power sector. Independent generators have started to capture generation market share, mostly renewables, and municipalities are responsible for retail of electricity in some areas. (The customer still has no choice of supplier). The country regularly exports electricity to its neighbors through the Southern African Power Pool. South Africa saw some short-term load shedding (scheduled power cuts) in June 2018 and again in early 2019 ' but both were a far cry from the height of regular load shedding in 2014-15. Coal dominates South Africa's electricity mix, accounting for 73% of capacity in 2018. This share is likely to be maintained once the Medupi and Kusile coal plants (at 4.8GW each) come online together with the government's IPP program.

Fossil fuels dominate on-grid energy generation, with power plants consisting of a mix of oil or diesel-fueled facilities, with the exception of one small hydro facility in the capital, Juba. The majority of the population, 99%, is off-grid and relies on diesel generators for power. In terms of renewable energy, 15MW of distributed off-grid solar PV is progressively coming online, developed by Depo Energy. Furthermore, Scatec Solar will develop a 0.7MW hybrid PV project with 1.6MWh of storage in the near future, in addition to the previously-announced 2.25MW of hybrid solar plants. To support power market development, there are plans to create new transmission lines to Ethiopia, Sudan and Uganda.

The structure of Sudan's power sector has evolved in recent years. Following the unbundling of the sector at the turn of the millennium, 2016 saw the creation of the Sudanese Electricity Holding Co. This has an effective monopoly on procurement, with the holding company overseeing two generation utilities ' the Sudanese Thermal Power Generating company and its hydro-focused counterpart ' as well as two companies whose respective remits cover distribution and transmission. These companies remain state-owned, despite the 2001 Electricity Law to open up private participation in the energy sector. There are no real independent power producers to date, although there is one company which owns and operates thermal plants in a handful of regional capitals, yet the fuel is supplied through the Sudanese Electricity Holding Co. free of charge. In terms of technology, the country is still predominantly dependent on oil- and hydro-based power generation, with hydropower accounting for more than half of installed capacity.

On-grid, Tanzania has a diverse, albeit dirty, power generation portfolio, consisting of thermal generation like natural gas (632MW) and diesel (231MW), but also large hydro (568MW), small hydro (19MW) and biomass (11MW). Capacity has increased at a snail's pace, with only 15MW of new on-grid capacity commissioned since 2016. There are a number of independent power producers selling power to TANESCO under power purchase agreements, but TANESCO still owns over 50% of the country's generation. The country's Ministry of Energy has plans to establish a competitive wholesale and retail electricity market in 2025, but this remains little more than ambition at this stage.

Togo's generation is mainly thermal. The country relies on a 100MW Contour Global fossil fuel power plant and also imports significant gas generation from Ghana and Nigeria. The country aims to reach electricity independence by 2030. There has been no large-scale renewable project in Togo to date, although the national electrification and energy independence plan relies heavily on renewable energy build. Under the new renewable energy sector law, renewables benefit from priority dispatch and purchase obligation from the offtaker. Although the power sector is officially open to all players, the CEB (Communaut Electrique du Bnin) still owns most generation capacity in the country, as well as transmission assets. The CEET (Compagnie Energie Electrique du Togo) is responsible for retail.

Over 94% of Tunisia's 5.5GW of installed capacity and more than 95% of the power produced in 2018 came from gas-fired plants. As of end-2018, only 240MW of wind plants, 55MW of PV, and 62MW of small hydro were commissioned. However, the power mix is due to become more diversified over the next few years as auctions are due to increase the clean energy capacity. The state-owned utility Tunisia Company of Electricity and Gas (STEG) controls over 80% of power generation and has a monopoly over transmission and distribution of electricity and natural gas. IPPs are allowed in the market under the concession and authorization programs and can rely on a 20-year standardized PPA with STEG. According to law 2015-12 that regulates renewable energy generation, STEG is mandated to buy all power produced by clean energy plants.

Uganda began unbundling its power market at the turn of the century, splitting up the utility's generation, distribution and transmission arms. To date, more than ten different independent power producers (IPPs) have commissioned projects on the grid. They compete alongside the state developer, Uganda Electricity Generation Company Limited (UEGCL). The country's transmission remains under state monopoly, with the Uganda Electricity Transmission Company Limited (UETCL) being the sole operator of the system. Distribution is liberalized, with Uganda Electricity Distribution Company Limited (UEDCL) licensing eight different electricity distribution companies, pending approval from the Electricity Regulatory Authority (ERA). The Electricity Regulatory Authority oversees all three segments of the power sector.

Zambia's power market is dominated by large hydro assets and Zesco, a vertically-integrated utility owned by the Zambian government. Zesco generates, transmits, distributes and supplies the majority of the country's electricity. However, the sector is increasingly diversifying away from large hydro and Zesco's monopoly over generation, with IPPs capturing the majority of market share in other generation technologies. The share of large hydro in installed capacity fell from 95% in 2000, to 92% in 2010, and 78% by 2018, as IPPs commissioned new PV and fossil fuel plants. There is a pipeline for new hydro projects including the 2,400MW Batoka Gorge Dam power project, and several existing large hydro facilities are also being upgraded by Zesco. A large and untapped potential remains for small-scale hydropower, especially for rural electrification, which may change pending the success of the second GETFiT round. Zambia is largely a power-exporting nation, except for in years of low rainfall and low hydro generation when it becomes a net importer.

State-owned ZESA is the holding company for both the national generation utility (ZPC) and the T&D utility (ZETDC). Hydro accounts for about half of Zimbabwe's overall power generation, supplied by the Kariba plant on the Zambezi river. Water levels on the river have been low over the past few years, which has contributed greatly to the country's severe load shedding. The other largest source of generation is coal, which has also been unreliable due to fuel shortage and cost fluctuations. The market for power generation has been liberalized and is open to IPPs. ZERA, the regulatory agency, has issued 30 IPP agreements in the past five years and most are for renewable energy (solar). However, only eight of these are currently operational. Participation by the private sector is still low due to capital constraints. ZESA faces major challenges including validating infrastructure, insufficient foreign currency, power theft, and non-payment of bills. As a result, it is said to be on the brink of collapse.

Afghanistan relies heavily on imports. About 80% of the total generation capacity is imported, with the majority of demand being met by hydroelectricity. It is estimated that the country has the potential to generate 318GW of electricity from renewable sources with 23GW from hydro, 67GW from wind, 222GW from solar and 2GW from geothermal. So far, only parts of hydroelectric projects have been implemented. Da Afghaninstan Breshna Sherkat (DABS) is a government-owned utility that controls the power market, with little participation from the private sector. Policies are in place to increase the role of the private sector and create a favorable atmosphere for corporate power purchase agreements.

Armenia's installed capacity comprises just over half natural gas and one-third hydro, with the remainder being predominantly nuclear. Besides a few utility-scale solar PV and wind plants, some small-scale hydropower plants have been announced, with a near complete lack of geothermal projects in the pipeline. Renewables are being installed mostly to displace gas and provide more power for the summer peak. The power market is being liberalized in order to align with EU rules. The generation market is fully liberalized, with a range of owners and smaller players, while transmission is controlled by state-owned High Voltage Electric Networks (HVEN). For the moment, privately-owned Electric Networks of Armenia (ENA) is the sole buyer and supplier of power for retail and industrial consumers.

Gas accounts for the largest share of generation in Azerbaijan, with hydropower a distant second, and renewables having only a small impact. The country is self-sufficient in energy, although the interconnectors with neighboring countries allow for some imports and exports. Renewables projects do not benefit from priority despatch, although the state-owned power company does have some obligations in the purchase of power. The power market is not unbundled but is controlled by the central government. Efforts are under way to reform this, with DNV-GL acting as a consultant to the government, and with support from development institutions. There is no market for PPAs (power purchase agreements) as yet.

Bangladesh produces 70% of its electricity from gas power plants. However, as the country's gas supplies dwindle, it plans to meet its rising electricity demand through imports from India, Nepal and Bhutan. Bangladesh is also investing in new coal and nuclear power projects with technical help from India and Russia. Private participation is allowed only in the power generation sector while transmission and distribution are owned by the government. Bangladesh Power Development Board acts as a single wholesale-buyer of all electricity. Currently, there are no incentives for off-site captive generation and third-party sale of electricity is restricted. Renewables, including large hydro, produce only 2% of electricity. This share may hold steady as rooftop solar projects increase in the coming years.

Cambodia's power market is dominated by EDC, a utility that controls most of the grid and retails power to all grid-connected consumers. Nearly all of the generators are owned by independent power producers, which are able to sell to EDC only via a special license. In remote areas of the country, electricity is supplied by hundreds of private operators that generate, deliver and sell power. These operators however lose their licenses to generate power as soon as the national grid arrives. Over 90% of grid-supplied power in Cambodia is generated by large hydro and coal-fired plants. Most of these units have been built since 2012, with the overall stock quadrupling as Cambodia sought to wean itself off imports as demand boomed.

Coal still dominates China's power system, accounting for 53% of capacity and 64% of generation in 2018. The two numbers are already almost 10 percentage points down from just a year ago, demonstrating the speed of change. Wind and solar together now account for 19% of capacity and almost 8% of generation. Generation from renewables continues to grow, not only due to growth in capacity, but also reduction in curtailment. China's grid companies have deployed multiple approaches to incorporate more renewables, including generation rights trading, expanded inter-regional power transfer, thermal generator flexibility retrofits and spinning reserves reduction. The result is historically low national average curtailment rates of 4.7% for wind and 2.4% for solar in 1H 2019.

India's total installed power generation capacity was 356GW in April 2019 ' the third largest in the world ' with renewables (excluding large hydro) accounting for 77GW. Since 2017, the capacity additions from renewables have exceeded those of coal power generation. 
Electricity generation in India is a diversified mix of federally owned plants, state-owned plants and those owned by private companies. The transmission system comprises five interconnected regional grids, which are controlled by national and regional load dispatch centers. State-owned distribution companies have monopolies at the retail level with only a few cities, such as Delhi and Mumbai, having private operators. Industrial and large commercial users can chose to procure electricity through open access mechanisms but residential retail is not liberalized.

The power market in Indonesia is semi-unbundled: private players can only participate in generation, and accounted for 35% of the installed capacity in 2018. System operation, transmission and distribution is controlled by PLN, which is the sole offtaker. Private developers are not allowed to sign direct power purchase agreements with consumers. Corporate users may only procure renewable power through on-site PV systems, which can be purchased upfront or leased. Indonesia's power mix is dominated by fossil fuels, which accounted for 85% of the installed capacity in 2018. The share of coal has increased from 36% to 50% of the installed capacity during 2010-18 to meet the rapid rise in electricity demand. Renewables' share has declined due to lack of support from the government.

Power generated in Kazakhstan comes predominantly from Soviet-era plants that are old and inefficient and burn high ash coal of which the country has a 300-year supply.  Fossil fuels generate 87% of the electricity generated. Though there is a mandate to green part of the power generation infrastructure with up to 10% renewables by 2030, it will be difficult to do so due to the comparatively inexpensive price of this fuel and technology. Although there is favorable policy in place to expand renewables, the economics of doing so and the entrenchment of fossil fuel resources in terms of employment and infrastructure will prove to be challenging obstacles. Kazakhstan's abundant coal resource and well-developed transmission infrastructure have positioned the country as a net energy exporter in recent years.

Kyrgyz Republic does not have a competitive wholesale market. While the country's vertically integrated state-owned utility, Kyrgyzenergo, was formally unbundled in 2001, state-controlled entities continue to dominate in each segment. Electric Power Plants JSC, for example, controls nearly 98% of power generation, the National Electric Energy Transmitting Co. has a monopoly in power transmission and four companies (that is, Vostokelectro, Jalalabatelectro, Oshelectro and Severelectro) handle nearly all power distribution. Kyrgyz Republic's installed power capacity has remained flat in recent years, at around 3.8GW, but the country needs more capacity. Renewables play only a nominal role in the country's power sector.

The domestic power market in Laos has a single-buyer structure, with lectricit du Laos (EDL) the sole buyer and retailer as well as the grid operator. Power generation was partially liberalized in 2010, when EDL spun off its large hydro assets under EDL-Gen, in which it owns a stake of about 75%. Independent power producers are also active in the market. They have been responsible for roughly 90% of the capacity additions since 2015. Capacity additions picked up rapidly from 2013 onwards, due to external demands: Thailand's EGAT financed, contracted and now dispatches several new large hydro projects and a 2GW coal plant. External demands will keep on driving new capacity addition as Laos is planning to double its transmission capacity with neighbors Thailand, Vietnam, Malaysia, Cambodia and Myanmar over the next few years.

Coal and gas dominate power generation in Malaysia, and accounted for 75% of the installed capacity and 86% of electricity generation in 2018. This share has largely remained stagnant despite the government's efforts to promote renewable energy. A number of projects awarded under the two large-scale auctions completed in 2016 and 2017 are expected to be commissioned in the next two years. The government is also in the process of awarding an additional 500MW of new projects in the third round of auctions. These projects will help increase the share of solar in installed generation capacity, and generation, in the next three to four years. The electricity sector is partially unbundled, with private participation allowed in electricity generation. Independent power producers account for more than 75% of all power generation assets in Malaysia. The three state owned utilities ' TNB, Serawak Energy and Sabah Electricity ' are the only entities allowed to participate in electricity transmission and distribution. Developers are currently not allowed to enter into power purchase agreements with retail customers. However, the new industry reforms announced in the country in September 2019 propose to allow this for rooftop solar power projects.

Fossil fuels accounted for 93% of generation in 2018, although this may change as the highly-polluting Soviet-funded coal plants age, and as the share of renewables rises. Mongolia has four grids, with grid-connected generation capacity expanding. This should reduce Mongolia's significant reliance on electricity imports from Russia in the western grid and to a lesser extent from China in its south. Curtailment of renewables is not yet a significant issue in Mongolia. In addition, Mongolia has approximately 1MW of off-grid solar and 0.9MW of solar-wind hybrids, which typically apply to Mongolian 'towns' and 'living tents' (soums and gers) distributed in remote villages. The power market is mostly state-owned and the grid is regulated, without near-term plans for liberalization. The state is the biggest player in generation and distribution, and the National Dispatching Center is the only offtaker.

Natural gas and large-scale hydro are two dominant sources of energy for Myanmar, accounting for over 90% of the country's installed capacity. Renewable energy is getting traction, with the country's first utility-scale solar plant of 40MW coming online in May 2019, and another 460MW of solar and wind projects announced or under construction. Although the country's power market is still dominated by a few state owned players, it is starting to open up power generation to foreign players. Sembcorp Power, a Singaporean utility, became the first foreign independent power producer in Myanmar this year, while a few Chinese and European players are negotiating with the government to develop solar, wind and microgrid projects in the country.

Hydro is the main (99%) of power generating source in Nepal. No fossil fuel is used for powering the Himalayan country, except for diesel consumed by back-up generators widely adopted in commercial and industrial facilities, and at home. Nepal experiences serious shortages of power: many people remain with restricted access to electricity, while those with access have regular or irregular blackouts. The situation will likely change as the country builds more hydro, and introduces wind and solar as new sources. Its power generation and transmission is bundled and dominated by a single state-owned entity ' Nepal Electricity Authority (NEA). Some independent power producers exist, and the country plans to encourage such producers to increase supply. Nepal imports power regularly from India to meet power demand, especially during the dry season.

Closing the power supply gap is a policy priority: in the past two years, the government has brought over 6.5GW of coal and gas capacity online under the China-Pakistan Economic Corridor, and there is more to come, trumping renewables new build. Growing public debt means that generators often are not paid due subsidies, and power distribution companies cannot claim their heavy transmission and distribution losses from the consumer. Captive power plants are common among industrial users. The behind-the-meter solar market is significant, importing over $300 million in PV modules from China per year, with some installed in country, and some re-exported to Afghanistan.

Historically, geothermal, oil/diesel and hydropower were the Philippines' largest sources of generation. In 2018, coal was the largest power source, at 52GWh (52%), while the share of renewables rose slightly to 23% of generation. After Epira liberalized the power market in 2001, Aboitiz Power, San Miguel Global Power and Trans Asia acquired the majority of assets and currently own about 62% of the total capacity. Epira also institutionalized the Wholesale Electricity Spot Market (WESM) for Luzon and Visayas regions, and will soon be open to Mindanao. The government supports the signing of power supply agreements between large-demand consumers and developers, and has mandated utilities to facilitate customers wanting renewable power through a Green Energy Option program.

Tuas Power, Senoko, YTL, Keppel Merlimau, Sembcorp, PacificLight and Tuaspring account for 90% of the generation capacity in Singapore. Bids are submitted to the wholesale market operated by the Energy Market Company ' a subsidiary of Singapore Exchange. Prior to the inception of the OEM, only consumers whose monthly consumption exceeded 2MWh ('contestable' consumers) were allowed to purchase electricity from licensed private retailers. Those who didn't meet this consumption threshold ('non-contestable' consumers) had to purchase electricity at the regulated tariff from state-owned SP Group. Under the OEM regime, which rolled-out island wide in May 2019, all consumers, regardless of their monthly consumption, are allowed to purchase electricity from a licensed retailer. The retail market is highly competitive, with 28 licensed firms.

The Sri Lankan market is a long way away from liberalization. Ceylon Electricity Board, the dominant utility, is yet to be unbundled, and seems at odds with the regulator PUCSL. Besides their differences on the ideal long-term generation mix for the country, the regulator is unhappy with the delays in new plant construction by the utility. Resorting to oil-fired emergency power is not only expensive, but also extremely polluting. The PUCSL has not announced any retail tariff revisions since 2014. CEB has not been able to make a convincing case for tariff revision, transparently laying out its power procurement and power sales.

Coal accounted for nearly half of Taiwan's power generation in 2018. This position is likely to change with the government's energy transition set to increase the share of gas power to 50% and renewables to 20% of total generation by 2025 while phasing out nuclear power, which accounted for 10% of generation in 2018. To spur accelerated growth, policies have been introduced to give renewable energy priority dispatch and permission to be sold directly to end-users on the unregulated market, with Facebook signing the island's first corporate renewable power purchase agreement in January 2019. Fossil fuel generators can only sell power to Taipower. Liberalization for thermal generators is due to take effect in 5-8 years.

Barqi Tojik, a vertically integrated state-owned utility, dominates Tajikistan's power sector. Despite its strong market position, the utility is in poor financial health due to low subsidized tariffs, losses on transmission and distribution services and mediocre collection rates. The government has granted Pamir Energy the authority to generate power, provide transmission and distribution infrastructure and sell to retail consumers in one remote region, but Barqi Tojik acts as the utility for over 95% of the country's population. Industrial players consume most of Tajikistan's power.

Thailand's power market is partially liberalized, with the generation sector opened up to the participation from private players. State-owned utility EGAT is the sole offtaker of all generated electricity. The introduction of Small Power Producers (SPPs) and Very Small Power Producers (VSPPs) promoted the decentralization of power generation utilizing renewable energy. In 2018, renewables, including large hydro, accounted for 18% of total domestic electricity generation. Natural gas is still the backbone of Thailand's power system, accounting for 60% of 2018's electricity generation. The latest power development plan of Thailand shows a further step back from coal and an increased role for gas in the power mix.

Natural gas is the main fuel for power generation in Turkmenistan. Power is controlled by the state, highly subsidized and also rationed. Blackouts and instability are common. Significant system upgrades are needed but the country does not have the resources for that.

Gas accounts for most generation, followed by large hydro. This is not about to change. In renewables, some wind and solar are in planning or discussion, but the targets are very limited. The country has reconnected with some of its neighbors after abandoning a regional network in 2009. This reconnection will allow for imports and exports or power and help to develop a regional market. Plans to export power to Afghanistan have provoked local protests in regions that face blackouts during the high-demand period of winter. Renewables do not get priority dispatch, and the frameworks for managing a larger amount of renewables in the power system are not in place. The state-controlled utility is the sole purchaser of renewable generation, with an implied state guarantee. The market is not unbundled, but is state controlled and vertically integrated. Plans to reform the system are advancing slowly with assistance from development institutions. There is no market for corporate PPAs.

Vietnam's power system is predominantly fossil fuel based with coal, gas and oil supplying 60% of generated electricity in 2018. Hydro's potential has been largely harnessed in Vietnam and accounts for 38% of supply. Renewable energy (excluding hydro) has a limited role in the current generation mix, with less than 1% of total supply.

Vietnam's power market is partially liberalized, with the generation sector open for private participation. EVN and its subsidiaries monopolize transmission, distribution and retailing of power. Vietnam operates on a single buyer model with EVN as the sole off-taker of all generated electricity. A power sector reform roadmap is in place. In 2012, the competitive generation market was established and unbundled EVN's power generation function. In the second phase of liberalization, Vietnam introduced the competitive wholesale market in 2019. A competitive retail market is targeted after 2021. A mechanism for direct purchase of power by corporates is also under development.

Albania's power market is undergoing reform, which the government promised to the European Union in exchange for financial support under the Third Energy Package, legislation intended to open up gas and electric markets in the EU. Electricity generation is unbundled; transmission and distribution are not. State-owned KESH participates in generation along with independent power producers. State-owned OST, the transmission system operator, was granted membership into ENTSO-E, the European network of transmission operators pending verification of its unbundled status. As of 2018, this status has not been confirmed. The electricity distributor, OSHEE, is also not fully unbundled into an independent entity. 

Albania's domestic generation is nearly 100% hydro-powered, and until 2017 the country was dependent on its neighbors for electricity imports because domestic sources were insufficient. Higher hydropower production in 2018 saw the country briefly become a net exporter of electricity.

BiH's power fleet is roughly split between just over 2.1GW of capacity from five lignite power plants and an equal amount of hydro. The 50.6MW Mesihovina wind farm started operating in March 2018. Renewable energy capacity is minimal, but includes wind, solar, biomass and small hydro. Several further wind farms are planned, including two of 48MW each, in addition to six lignite power plants. While the electricity sector is open to private participation, the overwhelming share of generation and distribution is overseen by three vertically integrated public utilities whose remit is geographically distributed. Some international companies have said they have been forced to partner with a state utility after investing in BiH. NOSBiH operates and balances the grid. The wholesale market does not yet operate transparently and dispatch is not determined on purely economic terms.

Most of Georgia's power is supplied by small and large hydro plants. In 2018, Georgia had a total installed capacity of 4,179MW from 32 power plants. Hydro plants accounted for 77% of the total (2,971MW of large hydro and 261MW of small hydro), followed by natural gas (926MW) and wind (21MW). Electricity generation in 2018 was 12,149GWh, of which hydro represented 81% of the total. 
Georgia has significant grid interconnections with Armenia, Turkey and Russia, which it uses to balance its supply. The country has ambitions to become an energy exporter. However, hydro capacity additions are slowing due to public opposition to new large-scale developments. Wind is popular, and output could increase significantly if the government approves the project pipeline. 
Georgia's power market is unbundled and open for privatization in all segments. There are 21 qualified generators in total. The main generators are the state, which owns the 1,300MW Enguri Hydro Plant, and the Czech private company Energo-Pro Georgia. In 2018, Enguri was responsible for 33.4% of generation. The vast majority of power is transacted through contracts, but a wholesale spot market has been growing slowly. In 2018, 10,800GWh was sold through direct contracts while 2,644GWh was transacted on the spot market. There is little market for corporate PPAs, though rising commercial and industrial power prices could increase demand.

The North Macedonian power sector has been unbundled and partially privatized. State-owned ELEM's monopoly on generation ended in 2008 for big industrial consumers. Since 2014, 230 companies with annual revenues of at least 10 million euros ($11.38 million) are allowed to choose their supplier. ELEM maintains control of the country's two major coal power stations, with a combined capacity of 800MW, as well as most smaller generation assets. 
Independent power producers are active in small hydro projects. Distribution is fully unbundled, although EVN, an Austrian utility, is the largest player and has enjoyed a monopoly on electricity distribution for over a decade. State-owned Mepso operates the electricity transmission system and has yet to be fully unbundled. The country is looking to set up an independent power exchange by the end of 2019, as well as couple with the Bulgarian market.

Moldova's transition to clean power auctions represents its first step into wholesale markets. Until those projects come on line, the country will continue to obtain roughly three-quarters of its domestic power from the Kuchurgan power plant. Power from Kuchurgan or imported from Ukraine constitutes more than 90% of Moldova's supply. Electricity supplied by Ukraine's DTEK is sourced from thermal plants that burn coal and could include some power from wind and solar sources. Renewables generated in Moldova itself contribute a negligible amount to the country's power supply. Distribution has been privatized in the south and part of the central region. An attempt to sell off the network in the north failed, and it remains in state hands. The rest of the power market is state-controlled and prices are regulated. There are plans to reform the system, which has six licensed power producers that operate in part under regulated tariffs.

At the end of 2018, Russia had an installed capacity of 242GW. Though generation, system operation, transmission and distribution are managed by separate entities, much of them are state owned.  Fossil fuels account for more than 60% of Russia's power generation. Due to Russia's wealth of oil and gas resources, renewables are unlikely to meaningfully displace fossil fuels in the near future, in particular, natural gas generation. However, renewables are being used to improve domestic power supply to remote regions that are not connected to the grid. These regions traditionally relied on power generation from oil. So, while natural gas is likely to remain the dominant generation technology, generation from oil has fallen by more than two thirds since 2000.

In 2018, some 66% of Serbia's generation came from coal, while most of the remaining 34% came from a combination of large and small hydro facilities. Serbia has struggled to meet the unbundling requirement under the EU's so-called third energy package. The state-owned TSO, Elektromre'a Srbija (EMS), has gained its license to operate and transmit electricity on the transmission system. To satisfy concerns over independent operation'since the government also runs the state utility, Elektroprivreda Srbije (EPS) ' EPS and EMS are operated by different ministries. But generation, retail and distribution fall under the control of the state-owned utility EPS meaning the EU Secretariat still deems Serbia non-compliant. Serbia's import and export balances are sensitive to the country's hydrology for hydro generation, the condition of its aging fossil fuel plants, and demand dynamics from one of its seven interconnected, country neighbors.

Turkey has undertaken ambitious power-market reforms to privatize and liberalize the sector, and to exploit domestic energy resources. This has primarily meant an emphasis on lignite and hydro, as well as renewables. The government has dialed back its nuclear ambitions, but still plans one 4.8GW Russian-backed plant. Commissioning is unlikely before 2026. The historic dominance of coal generation is likely to continue in the short term, though gas has struggled as the economy slows down. In the 2018 generation mix, coal accounted for 37% and gas 30%. Renewables additions, mainly wind and solar but also geothermal and biomass, are all growing, but face an uncertain future due to a lack of clarity on the feed-in tariff.

Nuclear plants supplied more than half the electricity generated in Ukraine in 2018 ' a proportion that has increased in recent years. Non-hydro renewables account for just over 3% of generation ' a proportion that is likely to increase with the growing renewables pipeline. The upcoming power auctions could slow that growth rate, however, depending on the quota of capacity on offer. The new power market structure will require further price liberalization to incentivize independent power producers to enter the market. Generation is only partially privatized, and DTEK is by far the largest single player.

Argentina's power matrix remains largely reliant on thermal and large hydro assets. Currently, 51% of installed capacity is gas power plants, with hydro representing 28%. The country has a considerable amount of oil & diesel assets at 11% of the mix. Argentina added 1.6GW of thermal capacity in the last year alone. Renewables share increased from 2.5% in 2017 to 4% by 2018 thanks to the commissioning of projects awarded in RenovAr.
The total capacity of wind and solar assets, less than 300MW in 2017, reached nearly 1GW by 2018. For the first time, wind generation achieved the same level as small hydro. Despite the dramatic increase in wind generation, Argentina fell far short of its 8% renewables goal by year-end 2018. By then, only 2.5% of its generation came from small hydro, wind, solar and biomass.

Bolivia's power market is dominated by natural gas, which accounts for 50% of generation. Government-subsidized pricing limits the competitiveness of renewables. However, Bolivia is seeking to expand its hydroelectric capability to 74% of capacity by 2025 (up from 30% in 2018) and allow the country to export electricity. Despite the subsidized competition from fossil fuel, renewable generation, such as from the Uyuni and Ouro solar plants, now accounts for 4% of total capacity. ENDE is responsible for most generation, transmission and distribution.

Brazil has the largest power market in Latin America, with total installed capacity of 162GW in 2018. The country's size, plentiful resources and conducive policies have made Brazil the region's main renewable energy market and one of the top 10 in the world. Its matrix remains highly reliant on hydropower, which accounted for roughly 65% of the country's generation in 2018. The heavy reliance on one source came at a high cost in 2014: a prolonged drought put Brazil's water supply and energy matrix into stress, exposing the market to costly generation from fossil-fueled plants. The hydro crisis emphasized the country's need for generation diversification. Auctions and net metering will continue to be crucial policies to develop Brazil's power sector. In terms of structure, the power market is fully unbundled and fairly evenly split between state-owned and private-sector players.

Chile has a National Electric System (Sistema Elctrico Nacional, or SEN) as well as two smaller isolated systems in the south of the country, the Sistema Elctrico de Aysn (SEA) and Sistema Elctrico de Magallanes (SEM). SEN was created with the connection of the country's two primary power systems, the Sistema Interconectado del Norte Grande (SING) and the Sistema Interconectado Central (SIC), at the end of 2017. The process of interconnection is ongoing and the country commissioned a second line connecting the two systems in June 2019. The SIC and SING sub-systems together account for 99% of Chile's total installed capacity, with 18.4GW and 6.2GW installed, respectively. 
In 2018, Chile had 2.3GW of solar and 1.5GW of wind capacity, representing 16% of total installed capacity, and renewable power represented 21% of all energy generated. Wind generation in Chile surged from 1.4TWh in 2014 to 3.5TWh in 2017, while solar output spiked from 0.5TWh to 5.1TWh. Together, wind and solar represented 11% of the country's total power generation in 2018, up from virtually nothing five years ago.

Of Colombia's total installed capacity of 17.3GW at year-end 2018, large hydro represented 62% and provided 74% of the 68.9TWh generated that year, followed by natural gas at 10% of generation. Other renewables accounted for 8% of generation, with most coming from small hydro. Capacity additions since 2010 have been dominated by hydro, oil and diesel. Among renewables, Colombia had only 933MW of small hydro, one 18MW wind plant and one 10MW solar plant commissioned in 2017. 
Colombia's power market has numerous private and state-owned players across segments but remains concentrated. Government-operated Empresas Publicas Medelln (EPM), together with privately owned Emgesa and Isagen, accounted for 63% of generation in 2018.

The power market in Costa Rica is regulated and dominated by the vertically integrated Instituto Costarricense de Electricidad (ICE), which is the major generator in Costa Rica and the sole power purchaser in the country. However, the Costa Rican market allows private participation in the form of cooperatives and independent power producers. These entities can be involved with generation and distribution in some parts of the country.
In 2018, the country had an installed capacity of 3,601MW, with hydropower representing 66% (2,387MW) of the total. Oil and wind, respectively had 16% (572MW) and 10% (378MW) of the capacity.
Total generation in 2018 was 11,356GWh, mainly from hydropower with 73% (8,343GWh), followed by wind with 16% (1,799GWh).

The Dominican Republic had 3.6GW of installed capacity in 2018. Oil and diesel are the main sources of electricity, accounting for 1.6GW, or approximately 50% of total capacity. Small hydro, wind, solar and biomass together account for 13% of the total. Although generation is open to private players, it remains dominated by state-owned entities. The distribution segment is divided into three public companies: Edeeste, Edenorte and Edesur. All state-owned companies are managed by the Corporacin Dominicana de Empresas Elctricas Estatales (CDEEE).

In Ecuador, the Ministry of Electricity and Renewable Energy (MEER) oversees renewable energy policy and planning. In 2015, the Act Establishing the Public Electric Power Service (LOSPEE) was published, overseeing the power sector in Ecuador. Under this law, the National Electricity Board (CONELEC) becomes the Agency for Regulation and Control of Electricity (ARCONEL). While generation is open to private players in Ecuador, transmission is under the responsibility of state-owned utility Corporacin Elctrica del Ecuador (CELEC EP Transelectric). Distribution is divided between 11 majority-public companies, in which MEER is the majority shareholder. 
In 2018, Ecuador had a total of 8.7GW of installed capacity, with hydro representing 50% and thermal power accounting for 39% of its mix. In 2016, the country doubled its hydro capacity, which totaled 4.4GW in 2018. Clean energy, encompassing small hydro, biomass, wind and solar plants, represents 11% of total capacity.

El Salvador had 1.9GW of installed capacity in 2018. Oil and diesel constitute the single largest source, with 38% of the total, followed by large hydro with 28%. Among renewables, biomass and geothermal dominate, with 15% (294MW) and 11% (204MW), respectively. PV capacity has increased four-fold since 2015, reaching 60MW in 2018. 
El Salvador's power market has been unbundled, and generation is open to private operators. The country is part of the Central American Electrical Interconnected System and is connected to Guatemala and Honduras by 286km of transmission lines.
Between January and September 2019, El Salvador added 84MW more PV capacity to its grid. This increment is due to the commissioning of two PV projects. In March 2019, Real Infrastructure Capital Partners concluded a portfolio of three PV plants with a combined capacity of 44MW in the city of Acajutla: Los Remedios, La Trinidad and M'rquez. 
In July 2019, AES El Salvador and the Guatemalan Corporacin Multi Inversiones (CMI) installed 40MW of the 100MW Bosforo PV portfolio. Those plants are located in the cities of Santa Ana, San Sebastin Salitrillo, Sonsonate and Jiquilisco. With these new additions, El Salvador's solar capacity jumped 58% in less than one year.

The power market in Guatemala is unbundled. The country has 50 companies (private and state-owned) acting in generation, distribution, and transmission. Guatemala is connected via the Central American Electrical Integration System (SIEPAC) to Honduras and El Salvador. Northern Guatemala is also connected to Mexico's transmission system. 
Guatemala has a total of 3,969MW of installed generating capacity. Wind capacity increased 40%, from 76MW in 2017 to 107MW in 2018. Biomass and hydropower (small and large) account for 60% of installed renewables capacity. 
In 2018, 64% (7,730GWh) of the electricity generation in Guatemala came from renewable sources ' including large hydro. Despite that, electricity generated by coal increased 27%, from 3,060GWh in 2017 to 3,903GWh in 2018, while large hydro decreased 14%.

Haiti has around 284MW of installed generating capacity, with the bulk (80%) derived from fossil fuels. The remaining 20% comes from the P'ligre hydro plant, which is undergoing restoration, and other small hydro plants. EDH owns 44% of generation capacity in Haiti and is responsible for transmission on the 1,500 km of distribution lines on the island. Today, given infrastructure limitations, EDH is able to power Haiti's capital Port-au-Prince and a few cities nearby, but only intermittently. Meanwhile, the use of diesel generators, kerosene lamps and other forms of off-grid technologies is commonplace. EDH has received grants from the World Bank, the Inter-American Development Bank (IDB) and other international organizations to help the company improve its infrastructure.

Honduras has a total installed capacity of 2.6GW. In 2018, 28%, of total electricity produced came from oil and diesel plants. Large hydro represented 21% of generation, while renewables (biomass, small hydro, solar and wind) accounted for a combined 44% of power production. Solar capacity has increased by 31% since 2015, rising to over 500MW in 2018. Honduras is part of the Central American Electrical Interconnected System (SIEPAC) and is connected to El Salvador, Guatemala, Costa Rica, Panama and Nicaragua by transmission lines. Honduras is a net importer in the regional market.

In 2018, Jamaica's total electricity production fell from 4.7GWh to 4.3GWh, an indication of the age and condition of its generation fleet. Over 65% of it came from fossil fuel plants. Renewable energy (small hydro, solar and wind) accounted for roughly 8%. 
Clean energy capacity started increasing in 2016, when auction-winning projects came online. Among the winners, wind plants with combined capacity of 60MW and one 20MW PV plant were commissioned in 2016. After 2016, just 2MW were added to solar capacity in 2018, reflecting on Jamaica's total installed capacity of 862MW. Private utility Jamaica Public Service (JPS) is in charge of 60% of generation and 100% of transmission and distribution services on the island.

Mexico's generation matrix is dominated by thermal sources, which represented approximately 81% of total generation in 2018, primarily natural gas and diesel. Hydro accounted for approximately 10% of generation, followed by nuclear and wind at 3% each. At year-end 2018, Mexico had 4.5GW of wind capacity commissioned, by far the largest renewable technology excluding large hydro. Solar commissioned capacity grew significantly in 2018 to 1.3GW from 344MW in 2017. Mexico is expected to undergo a solar boom through 2020, with over 6GW of utility-scale PV added to the grid in addition to 3GW of wind. 
A fundamental change introduced by Mexico's energy reform is the separation of state-owned vertically integrated utility CFE, which holds the majority of generation assets and retains monopoly over transmission and distribution. Grid operation moved from within CFE to newly created, independent grid operator CENACE, which is to guarantee open and non-discriminatory access to transmission. Deregulation of generation in 2016 created Mexico's wholesale market, which has operated on a day-ahead basis since January 2016, with a real-time spot market beginning in January 2017.

Renewables account for the biggest share of power generation, reaching 58% of the 4.6TWh produced in 2018 ' up from 47% in 2016. Fossil fuel plants are still responsible for a substantial share, but decreased from 52% in 2016 to 41% in 2018. Nicaragua's power sector is unbundled and distinct actors (both state- and privately owned) participate in the generation and distribution sectors. At least 18 companies with active generation contracts hold a large share of installed capacity. Nicaragua is part of the Central American Electrical Interconnected System (SIEPAC) and is connected to El Salvador, Guatemala, Panama, Costa Rica and Honduras by transmission lines.

Panama had 3.8 GW of installed capacity in 2018. Oil and large hydro are Panama's main sources of electricity, with hydro responsible for 36%, or 1.4GW. Renewable sources accounted for 882 MW in 2018, with an increase of solar and wind from 2014 to 2018 of 68MW to 454MW.  Panama's power market was unbundled in 1997, with generation and distribution opened to private operators. Panama is part of the Central American Electrical Interconnected System and is connected to Costa Rica via 150 km of transmission lines.

Paraguay's electricity market is overseen by the Department of Mines and Energy, which is under the Ministry of Public Works and Communications (Ministerio de Obras Pblicas y Comunicaciones) and controlled by state-owned vertically integrated utility Administracin Nacional de Electricidad (ANDE). ANDE allows the participation of independent power producers (IPPs), however, as of 2018, there were no IPPs registered in the country.

In 2018, Peru generated 62% of its total 50TWh from renewable sources including large hydro. That source accounted for 51% in 2018, up from 40% in 2016, despite no significant capacity additions. Regarding non-renewable sources, coal and oil saw shrinkage in generation. Coal was responsible for generating only 43GWh in 2018 compared to 674GWh in 2017; oil declined 71% in the same period. 

Peru's installed hydro (small and large), solar, wind and biomass accounts for 43% of the country's 13,052MW of generating capacity. In 2018, 585MW of small hydro was commissioned compared to 472MW in 2017. Solar capacity jumped almost threefold from 2017 (96MW) to 2018 (285MW), and wind increased 54%, 243MW in 2017 to 375MW in 2018.

Uruguay's electricity market is overseen by the Ministry of Industry, Energy and Mines. The vertically integrated utility company UTE (Administracin Nacional de Usinas y Transmisiones Elctricas) controls part of the generation market and 100% of transmission and distribution. UTE allows the participation of independent power producers through auctions, usually for 20-year power purchase agreements (PPA).

Egypt's generating capacity mix remains decidedly fossil-fuel-focused, with more than a 90% share. This is principally because the government has sought to build out capacity quickly after the electricity shortages a few years ago. As part of this strategy, Siemens completed in 2H 2018 its 'Egypt megaproject' to build three combined-cycle gas turbine plants totaling 14.4GW. As a result, gas-fired generating capacity expanded by 200% over 2010-17 and is expected to continue as the government seeks to exploit its recently discovered domestic reserves. With regard to structure, at present, the state dominates the power market, with the Egyptian Electricity Holding Co. (EEHC) and its subsidiaries owning more than 90% of each segment. The 2015 electricity law envisaged a gradual market liberalization but progress has been limited so far.

The energy ministry acts as policy maker, power producer, service provider, operator and regulator in Iraq. Gas turbines account for over half of the generation capacity, with steam comprising almost a third. Hydro has traditionally played a role but damage from recent wars has limited generation capacity. Electricity and gas imports from Iran help meet demand, especially during the summer peak. U.S. sanctions of Iran also impact the gas imports from Iran, but Iraq has managed to get waivers from the U.S. The extension of these waivers remains a key uncertainty for Iraq's power sector. The ministry aims to have independent power producers build 9GW of power capacity by 2025 in an attempt to meet domestic demand and reduce reliance on imports. By unbundling the market and introducing the private sector into the distribution and generation segments, the ministry hopes to improve its financial position.

The share of renewables in generation increased rapidly from less than 1% in 2010 to just over 9% in 2018, bringing the target of 10% by 2020 well within reach. Capacity additions will slow down in the coming years as the government has suspended auctions until state-owned Nepco completes a new energy-sector development plan. Distinct bodies exist in the sector for production, transmission and distribution. There are separate companies for generation and distribution, while transmission is the responsibility of Nepco. There is no wholesale generation market, and Nepco purchases all generated electricity. Nepco has a template wind and solar PPA that currently exposes them to energy compensation. Jordanian power prices are not market-driven as generators cannot sell directly to the distributors and the government subsidizes tariffs.

Fossil fuels account for the largest part of Kuwait's power generation. The country has increased the share taken by gas-fired power plants in the past years, and will continue to do so in the future. Renewable energy accounts for less than 1% of its total capacity. A number of projects are under construction or in the pipeline to meet the 2030 renewable target of 15%. The Kuwait Authority for Partnership Projects oversees the development of PPAs according to law 116 of 2014. However, there is little experience in this area. The first phase of the Az-Zour North IWPP was the first IPP in Kuwait, but the model is yet to be refined so it can provide a benchmark for future developments.

EDL has a monopoly on transmission and distribution as well as retail of electricity. Any reforms to EDL or the power market are unlikely in the current political stalemate. Diesel and heavy-fuel generation dominate Lebanon's power mix in the form of ageing plants, leased power ships, or illegal private generators. The country imports some electricity from the Syrian interconnector. The law authorizing IPPs is still pending implementation; however, an exceptional decree granting the executive temporary powers to license new projects, which was introduced in 2014 and extended for three years in April 2019, has made the current pipeline of projects possible.

While Oman produces significantly more crude oil than natural gas, the Sultanate exports crude to the global market and uses gas to generate electricity for its own needs. A new strategic plan for energy and economics in the country will change the mix rapidly over the next 10 years. With 30% of generation slated to come from renewables, the country plans to increase its gas exports and generate additional revenue. Only 0.3% of Oman's renewable energy plan has been implemented so far at a planned slow pace. Oman is being very thorough and methodical with its pilot projects. The next phase of implementation should move more quickly as they are motivated to catch up to other countries in the region.
While there are distinct companies operating independently within the power sector, they are mostly state run. A small amount of generation and some distribution is handled by private companies in rural regions. Oman has recently passed laws to expand privatization of these sectors.
Oman is a part of the Gulf Cooperation Council's (GCC) grid interconnection system, which allows for electricity transfers between the six connected countries (Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, Qatar, Bahrain, the United Arab Emirates and Oman). A 0.22 MW (220 kV) interconnection between the Oman (MIS) and UAE (Abu Dhabi) power systems has been commercially operational since 2012. While not used consistently, the link has provided emergency reserves on a number of occasions, preventing power failures in the MIS.

Oil accounts for the largest slice of generation capacity and this is a characteristic of the sector that Saudi Arabia is intent on changing. It will do so by developing additional non-associated and unconventional gas fields, and by adding more natural gas-fired capacity. Another big thrust for Saudi Arabia is solar and wind technology, the development of which is just beginning. The power market is currently dominated by state-owned companies, though plans exist to privatize key institutions in the sector by 2020. Currently the Saudi Electric Co., through its wholly owned subsidiary National Grid, has a monopoly on electricity power transmission, operation, control, maintenance and rent of transmission network lines. Through the auctions under the NREP program, more independent power producers will be entering the scene.

Installed renewables capacity ' mostly solar ' has grown swiftly over the past six years, rising from 14MW in 2012 to 594MW in 2018. Yet generation is still dominated by hydrocarbons: oil and natural gas account for well over 99% of the current output. A growing project pipeline is set to increase the share of renewables ' the Ministry of Energy has set its sights on issuing tenders at a rate of 1GW a year until 2050. The 1.17GW PV plant in Abu Dhabi started commercial operations in 2017. Utilities have a monopoly on procurement, transmission and distribution. Generation is, however, open to private participation: over 90% of Abu Dhabi's generation is provided by IPPs.

Installed generating capacity in Palestine is concentrated in one large-scale diesel-fired plant in the Gaza Strip, and some small-scale solar projects. The Gaza Power Plant has not been operational for long periods due to fuel shortages, although fuel supplied by Qatar began powering the plant from October 2018. The country still relies heavily on electricity imports, mostly from Israel and also from Egypt and Jordan. There are plans to add more domestic generation capacity, including a 450MW CCGT plant. Renewables uptake is also meant to reduce reliance on imports.

Natural gas has a monopoly on power generation in the country. Renewables will make a dent in this. There are no imports of gas. Renewables are meant to primarily save gas from being burned for power, as exporting the gas as LNG has more value. Clean energy is also used to diversify the sources of power. Generation capacity continues to increase as load grows at 6.5% per year. Renewables will get priority dispatch to meet the gas saving mandate. Only generation is liberalized, and there are no further plans to reform. The biggest players in the generation market are Ras Laffan and Qatar Electricity & Water Company (QEWC). The utility is the sole offtaker of electricity.

An administratively burdensome bureaucracy and high taxes do little to attract investment. Sonelgaz is the offtaker for utility-scale projects. However, the utility's financials have been strained over recent years as it suffers from low commodity prices, widespread fraud and structural inefficiencies. In addition to the company having debts running up to nearly 61 billion dinars ($507 million), many of Sonelgaz's customers are behind on payments. The group launched legal proceedings against over 50 companies it claims owe it money in August 2019. Despite the possibility of arrears on payments, the risk of the offtaker defaulting is held in check by Sonelgaz being backed by the government and domestic banks.

Angola's economy contracted in 2018 for the third straight year, as a slower-than-expected economic recovery unfolds for the major oil producer.
