Declining crude production, falling oil exports and high inflation create a challenging outlook for a return to economic growth. Investments in generating capacity in the form of new large hydro facilities have improved reliability of power supply in the capital region in recent years, though soaring demand and population growth means progress on electrification will be challenging. Angola's electrification rate was just 34% in 2018, with much lower rates of access in rural areas. In spite of the country's explicit focus on development of abundant hydro resources, Angola has ambitious, if unsupported, near-term plans to develop renewable energy. It plans to connect over 500MW to the grid by 2022, and 800MW by 2025. The mapping of resources has been carried out to some extent across all technologies and several solar hybridization projects are under way, but no concrete steps have yet been taken to advance a planned solar auction program or to develop the country's first wind projects.

The MCA II program sets Benin on a good track to develop its energy sector. The aim of the program is to reinforce the power market and hopefully see spillover effects into other sectors, spurring economic activity. The country has important off-grid electrification potential, with only 11% of the rural population currently able to access electricity. The OCEF, subsidiary of the MCA II, has set up a fund for off-grid electrification. A first call for proposals closed in May 2018, while a second round ran from December 2018 to March 2019. BNEF's tool tracking export destinations of solar PV cells and modules from China recorded $17.6 million worth of PV exports between 2015 and 2Q 2019. However, the Port of Cotonou is one of the largest in West Africa and we cannot exclude that these goods were re-exported to other sub-Saharan countries.

Botswana boasts an impressive electrification rate of 61%. Botswana's power demand has plateaued in recently years, sitting at 610MW for the last three years. Demand has peaked due to a slowdown in mining as a result of the commodities' price slump, whereby the largest state mine in the country filed for liquidation in 2016 and halted all operations. BPC has an aging power plant fleet with the oldest plant commissioned in the late 1980's. The plant is currently being refurbished and is expected to be operational in 2018.

Power demand has been rising rapidly in Burkina Faso, with peak demand increasing on average by 9% a year since 2015. Electrification has barely kept up with this growing demand. The national electrification rate is 21%, yet only 3% of the rural population has access to electricity. Burkina Faso has great solar and hydro resources, but limited wind potential. The low rural electrification rate and high solar resources offer a large opportunity for off-grid project development. Mini-grids can be owned and operated by private actors, but require an authorization or license if exceeding 250kW or 1MW respectively.

Burundi is one of the poorest countries in the world and relies on foreign aid. The country has been facing civil wars for decades and since 2015, it is facing severe political tensions. Burundi is ranked 168 among 190 countries in the World's Bank Doing Business index for 2019. Bureaucracy, poor infrastructure, trade challenges, high taxes and low access to credit are among the main challenges for businesses. On the positive side, Burundi joined the East African Community in 2007 and started the implementation of the common external tariff in 2009. Burundi also made major reforms to improve the procedure for creating a new business. The relationship with the East African Community could be a good opportunity for Burundi to proceed with the country's participation in regional infrastructure projects, such as interconnection and shared hydro power plants with neighboring countries.

Cameroon has seen average economic growth of 3.9% a year over the last decade and growth has picked up recently owing to rising revenue from oil, rubber and coffee production. The country has a relatively weak electrification rate of 54%, with less than 30% in rural areas. The government aims to reach 3GW of power capacity by 2020, mainly through new hydropower plants, and off-grid solar in rural areas. The Rural Electrification Master Plan, in its second phase, aims to electrify 10,000 locations by 2035, securing 50,000 connections annually over 20 years. The government is also preparing a new framework to regulate private off-grid renewables projects, although the policy's legal status is still unclear.

Electricity demand in the Central African Republic has been relatively flat over the past decade. Very little progress has been made in terms of national, urban and rural electrification rates. As distribution grids and electrification rates improve, demand is expected to rise. While there are programs to modernize the energy infrastructure, funded primarily by international development banks, these are not sufficient to enable wider electrification of the population. There is therefore a high potential for mini-grids.

Despite having one of the world's lowest electrification rates, and an official commitment toward providing electricity to 15% of the rural population by 2023, no coordinated electrification plan has been launched to date. Microgrid projects are few and far between, but offer great potential in improving electrification rates, especially given the large distances in the country. There are persistent concerns about the lack of investment in transmission and distribution, with grid congestion a particular issue for projects in and around the capital N'djamena.

The Republic of Congo has been teetering on the brink of insolvency since 2016 in the context of an economic crisis sparked by plummeting oil prices. The country's business environment has been detrimentally impacted and has also contributed to reducing the market's attractiveness. Moreover, finance to date has been directed toward large hydro projects rather than other renewables. The National Agency for Rural Electrification and the Fund for the Development of the Power Sector lack the financial means necessary to abate low electrification rates. Investment in the country's decrepit dams is lacking, with no concerted modernization plan in place to date.

Mining activity will drive near-term growth in power demand in the DRC, in part due to the increase in global demand for specialty metals such as copper and cobalt, which the country has in abundant supply. Copperbelt Energy's plans to build two grid-connected solar PV projects for the mining sector are evidence of this. The government plans to triple the current national electrification rate to 32% by 2030 and this is likely to mean favorable policies will be introduced for mini-grids or off-grid solar. Most DRC power plants are hydroelectric stations that do not require near-term upgrades.

Cote d'Ivoire aims to attain full electrification by 2025. The country has one of the region's most developed transmission grid coverage, but still has a long way to go with a national electrification rate of 65%. Although less than one-tenth of urban residents lack access to power, an increasing disparity persists between rural regions and population centers. Demand is growing fast with peak load increasing as much as 65% since 2010. The question of the role to be played by mini-grids in meeting the population's power needs is expected to be resolved at the time of CIE's contract renewal in 2020. Such a development is unlikely, as policymakers remain wary of off-grid electrification.

The prerequisites for doing business in Eritrea are likely to improve following the political rapprochement with Ethiopia. The combination of low electrification rates, good solar and wind potential and the expense of fuel imports offers opportunities for mini-grid developers in particular. However, the poorly maintained or, in parts, non-existent transmission and distribution infrastructure impacts the viability of larger projects. The lack of transparent, clear regulatory framework and incentives further thwart clean energy project development.

Most private sector opportunity in Ethiopia's clean energy space exists within the on-grid sector. The Ministry of Water, Irrigation and Energy has plans for 100% energy access by 2025, with 65% of this target being met through on-grid electrification. This target steps up to 96% in 2030, meaning domestic players have prioritized on-grid developments. Ethiopia has ambitions to be a middle-income economy in 2025 however, and power demand is growing fast across the country (estimated at 30% annually), meaning mini grids and off grid products will still factor into meeting this demand. The country has a separate goal of distributing 3.6 million solar lanterns and 400,000 solar home systems by 2025, but this potential has largely gone untapped.

Power demand in Ghana has been growing, with peak demand reaching 2,525MW in 2018, up by 17% from 2017. The heaviest power consumers are the 51 companies registered as bulk customers (as of August 29, 2019). These entities have a peak demand of at least 500 KVA for a consecutive period of three months or a minimum annual energy consumption of 1GWh. Many of these are concentrated in the Tema Export Processing Zones, which is authorized by the government to promote industrial activities. The extractive industry is also a heavy power consumer, accounting for about 10% of the total power demand in Ghana. The national electrification rate reached 84% in 2018, which is one of the highest in Sub-Saharan Africa.

Power demand has been steadily increasing in Guinea, with an average growth rate of 12% over the past three years. Electrification will continue to push up demand, with more than 60% of the population remaining unconnected despite a 16%-point increase in national electricity access rates since 2010. Little progress has been made to date, however, in raising the rural population's access to power, with less than a tenth hooked up to the grid. So there is significant potential for off-grid project development given the county's ample hydro and solar resources. Existing thermal plants have been modernized, and a program funded by the European Investment Bank is doing the same for the country's large hydro assets.

Kenya's peak power demand has seen moderate growth of 6.3% CAGR from 2010/11 to 2017/18, reaching 1,802MW. It was driven by growing demand from residential customers that could benefit from a subsidized grid connection cost, and from commercial as well as industrial customers. Kenya Power introduced a night-time discounted tariff for commercial and industrial customers in December 2017. But, it has not stimulated consumers to increase power demand as intended, likely because of strict criteria for the use of night-time tariffs. Kenya has the largest off-grid solar market in Sub-Saharan Africa, and is poised to grow further under its National Electrification Strategy launched in December 2018, which aims to attain universal access by 2022.

Data indicates that Lesotho's electrification rate has advanced from 17% in 2015 to almost 30% by 2018. Lestho's energy-access goals stipulate continued growth toward 50% by 2020, and 80% by 2030. This would provide a substantial opportunity for investment in the power sector.

The refurbishment of the Mount Coffee Hydropower Plant was a game-changer for the Liberian energy system. Power quality and reliability has since improved, and retail rates have dropped. However, demand for electricity far exceeds supply and significant grid issues persist. Customers complain of long wait times for new connections, and power producers have struggled to enter into agreement to supply LEC. Outside of Monrovia, microgrid development has commenced despite the lack of a dedicated policy framework and regulatory oversight. Import duty exemptions on clean energy equipment brought into the country by aid organizations have been exploited by developers cycling products through eligible agencies. There is significant potential for new solar and hydro projects but regulatory conditions need to improve.

With electrification rates encompassing only one quarter of total inhabitants and less than one tenth of the rural population, Madagascar offers significant off-grid clean energy development opportunities, particularly given the country's ample solar resources. Power demand has increased consistently in the past decade, at an average growth rate of 3% in the last three years. The World Bank is currently in the process of refurbishing the country's transmission and distribution infrastructure, in addition to restructuring state utility Jirama.

Malawi is one of the world's least electrified countries, with an overall electrification rate of around 11%. In rural areas, this reduces to just 1%. The country's rural electrification fund has an aim of extending the existing grid, but has not yet significantly increased electrification rates, according to reported results. There is significant unmet power demand in Malawi, where only 3% of total energy demand is served by electricity. Severe load shedding has been a persistent issue across the country, causing consumer unrest and economic disruption. Resource potential for solar is high. The central utility has no plans to build solar assets of its own, but it has awarded solar PPAs to a number of developers. Malawi's generation plants are in need of modernization and upgrades, but there is no comprehensive program due to a lack of funding.

Power demand increased annually by more than 8% on average between 2009 and 2018 in Mali. Given that under 40% of the population has access to electricity ' with rates as low as 19% in rural areas ' opportunities for mini-grid developers in particular are high. Solar/diesel hybrid plants are also growing in popularity due to the country's high potential in solar irradiation and its rural electrification fund. The rural electrification agency is responsible for authorizing such operators, making the process of setting up a mini-grid more efficient than in neighboring countries.

Power demand has been increasing slowly but surely since 2010. Officials foresee that coming years could see a tripling of demand with the completion of three large transmission projects connecting large urban centers. With ample solar and wind resources in addition to single-digit rural electrification rates, the potential for clean energy development particularly in the off-grid sector is high. Investment in renewables is set to continue despite imported hydropower and the attraction of offshore gas.

Morocco's electricity demand has grown at an average rate of 5.1% since 2010, slightly outpacing average economic growth of 3.5%. Of particular importance to the energy sector, peak electrical demand has also grown at a similar rate to total demand. Morocco has had great success in the electrification of rural areas, with the ONEE connecting more than 99% of the Moroccan rural population to the grid by 2014. The law that provides the framework for renewables projects, law 13-09, only permits the sale of electricity over the medium- and high-voltage networks. In 2015, the publication of act 58-15 opened up the possibility of access to the low-voltage networks, seen as key to the growth of the small-scale PV sector. However, as of 2018, this act is not yet implemented and therefore any sale of electricity back to the grid by small enterprises or private individuals is not yet possible. This obstacle is intended to be removed in the short to medium term. Estimates of total wind-resource potential for Morocco are as high as 25GW.

Mozambique's power fleet is in need of investment as the country seeks to expand generation capacity to meet growing load and ambitious electrification targets. The Ministry of Energy has published a long-term development plan, the Integrated Electricity Infrastructure Master Plan, which encompasses the southern system and central and northern systems for 2018-2028 and the integrated system through 2029-2043. The Plan envisions new power generation projects totaling 530 MW solar and 150 MW wind, in addition to 4,300 MW of hydro, 1,350 MW of coal and 8,500 MW of gas. Mozambique's electrification rate remains very low at just 29%, and progress in extending access to the wider population has been slow. Power demand continues to grow quickly, with peak consumption nearly doubling since 2010. For on-grid projects, developers can negotiate prices that enable the project to be profitable, but PPAs are negotiated on a case-by-case basis and there is currently no standardized duration for either on- or off-grid projects.

Namibia experienced an economic recession between 2016 and 1Q 2019. As of the second quarter of 2019, the economy showed some signs of growth. Fitch ratings agency expects 1.1% real GDP growth in 2019. 
In spite of the weak economic backdrop, power demand in Namibia has increased year-over-year at an average rate of 4% since 2006. The main factor propping up demand growth is a rapidly increasing electrification rate, which now sits at 54%. Rural electricity access still lags significantly, and is over 20% below the national average. 
The country has an ambitious rural electrification target, aiming for 50% electricity access by 2020. Large investments in off-grid systems and mini-grids will be necessary to meet that goal. Providing access to the rural population has historically been a challenge in Namibia, as it is the least densely populated country in Africa and the rural population is extremely dispersed. 
In some areas, grid extensions are not financially feasible. So far, minigrids have been developed top-down by the government, but they are keen to discuss public-private partnership arrangements with investors.

Demand has steadily increased in the past decade, with future demand likely driven by ongoing electrification. Alongside similar initiatives, the World Bank's NESAP is expected to make considerable progress in the off-grid space, given that only 1% of the Nigerien rural population currently has access to power. The historically slow rate of progress in electrification and Niger's ample solar resources offer ample opportunity for off-grid project development.

Nigeria has a very strong solar resource, followed by up to 3.5GW of small hydro. There is little wind resource. In 2016 alone, Nigerians spent a massive $16 billion to power privately-owned diesel/gasoline generators. More than 60% of companies in Nigeria have access to, or rely heavily on, diesel generators, compared to less than 20% in South Africa. The potential for mini-grids in Nigeria is therefore substantial. 
The on-grid peak demand reported by the government was 20GW in 2018, but actual demand, accounting for off-grid consumption, is likely to be well over 50GW. 
In 2016, Nigeria announced the Power Sector Recovery Program (PSRP), a series of policy actions, operational, governance and financial interventions to be implemented by the Federal Government of Nigeria between 2017 and 2021, in order to reset the Nigerian Electricity Supply Industry for future growth. The World Bank Group expressed its willingness to assist the PSRP with a $2.6 billion loan.

Rwanda prides itself on being one of the best markets to do business in among Sub-Saharan African countries and has an appetite for domestic and foreign investment to serve its fast-growing economy. The Rwanda Development Board has been created to support private sector players entering the country, complementing the strong presence of commercial and donor-backed lenders on the ground. Most of the growth in the energy space has been off-grid, as Rwanda has reached critical mass in its on-grid sector with an oversupply of generation. On the negative side, in 2018 Rwanda implemented new solar-equipment import standards overnight, which raised uncertainty for foreign investors and harmed the business model for some off-grid companies. Moreover, the country is reviewing its National Electrification Plan to define on-grid areas and off-grid divided between solar home systems and mini-grid systems.

Senegal's electrification scheme has fallen short of expectations, since being initially hailed as revolutionary upon its launch in 2008. The private concessionary framework assigned ten rural districts to operators, setting out yearly electrification targets in the process. But operators have fallen behind on their goals while charging prohibitive fees to customers. Electrification has progressed steadily despite such system issues. However, with national electrification at 68%, the 2025 universal access target seems ambitious. More generally, Senegal is a dynamic market ' demand is growing fast and the economy is buoyed by a young, skilled workforce.

Sierra Leone is becoming more attractive for renewables development, as the government cracks down on corruption and the state intends to push ahead with electricity sector reform.
The pico-solar industry is growing, with international companies BBOXX and Easy Solar offering PAYG models and mobile money payments becoming more common. Exemption from import and sales taxes for solar and energy efficiency products also benefits the industry, although red tape often makes it difficult to receive the exemptions.
The lack of domestic manufacturing and financial instability of offtaker EDSA makes project development more challenging, but energy development in other West African countries bodes well for Sierra Leone's future. 
There is significant potential to expand both hydro and solar generation to broaden electricity access.

The absence of reliable electricity supply is in general a major concern for Somalia and a significant barrier to doing business. Even consumers that do have a grid connection are dissatisfied with the quality of the power they receive. Were generation capacity and transmission and distribution infrastructure to improve, power demand could grow significantly. The grid in Somalia is already very decentralized, so off-grid and mini-grid development offers the potential for electrification even in the most remote areas. Somalia's rich solar resources make PV mini-grid systems an attractive option, and its long coastline also offers good resource potential for wind.

The main opportunity for off- or mini-grid projects in South Africa is in rural areas where electrification was at 66% in 2018, compared with 93% in urban areas. The Integrated National Electrification Plan includes initiatives to boost electricity access in rural areas ' aiming to fund an estimated 723,000 grid and 49,650 non-grid connections to households by 2019/20. Electricity consumption in South Africa has stagnated in recent years, declining on average 0.5% per year since 2006. The reduction has been mostly felt by heavy power users due to factors such as economic slowdown, volatility in commodity markets and rising electricity costs. This trend has been reflected in peak demand, which fell for a second consecutive year in 2018.

Power demand in the country is growing and expected to increase 7 to 8% per year, according to government officials. This is due to the combination of population growth, very low electrification rates and little installed capacity to date. Taking into account the abundant solar resources, the case for off-grid solar development is correspondingly strong. On-grid growth is, however, limited by a lack of transmission and distribution infrastructure. In addition to the fragile economic and security situation in South Sudan, this will continue to make it hard to attract utility-scale clean energy developers.

Optimism abounded following the removal of the majority of U.S. sanctions in October 2017, but Sudan's economic situation has not improved much since. Inflation has surged, widening the chasm between production costs and rock-bottom power prices, and economic hardship will persist in the wake of a sharp ongoing currency devaluation. The reliance on costly imported fuel underlines the attractiveness of renewables, to which Sudan's geography is well suited, with its high solar irradiation and strong winds. Future energy demand will be met by ongoing electrification initiatives, with the population growth currently outpacing connectivity rates.

Doing business in Tanzania's clean energy sector presents risk. The country's power demand has failed to grow with the country's population, and the regulator published data showing that power demand actually fell between 2017 and 2018. Additionally, there are questions surrounding the validity of economic growth figures the country has published, which is expected to fuel more investor uncertainty. The country has significant potential for solar and hydro, but neither technology has been fully realized. Through 2018, off-grid solar accounts for just 1.7% of lighting supply in rural Tanzania and 1% in urban areas. A number of multinational off-grid solar players like Zola Electric and Mobisol have operations in the country, but a dominant player has not emerged.

Togo has a low electrification rate of just 11% in rural areas. The country has developed a roadmap for electrification to reach 100% of the population by 2030. The program combines the distribution of 550,000 solar kits, notably with partners such as BBOXX, developing 315 micro-grids, and extending the distribution grid to remote areas. The level of demand for electricity largely exceeds supply, and increased at a compound annual growth rate of 6.1% between 2013 and 2017. The construction of the first utility-scale PV project (5MW by Eiffage and Neoen) has been proposed several times since 2015, but has been held back by the government wanting to benefit from the steep cost reductions of PV, and the required engineering, procurement and construction (EPC) price renegotiations.

The country is slowly recovering from an economic crisis. Growth in GDP reached 2.5% in 2018, up from 2% in 2017, and only 1.1% in 2016. The economy is forecasted to continue its growth trajectory in 2019. Tunisia's peak power demand is recovering, after a 6% drop from 2015 to 2016, and recorded a spike of 18% year-on-year to 4,025MW in 2017. This represented the greatest increase since at least 2011. It is one of few countries in Africa with nearly 100% electrification rates.

A supply glut and lagging transmission and distribution infrastructure are dampening activity in Uganda's power generation sector. The most promising on-grid investment opportunities today involve building wires to transmit power to where it is needed most. The rural electrification and distributed energy sector is also booming. Uganda has a thriving off-grid solar industry, with many companies using pay-as-you-go and mobile money applications to power explosive growth. Offtakers are generally secure in receiving payments for contracted power. The transmission system operator, Uganda Electricity Transmission Company Limited (UETCL) is the sole offtaker for all grid-connected power in the country. Grid-connected projects to date have signed 'deemed energy' (take-or-pay) contracts, and UETCL's commitments are understood to be backstopped by the Ministry of Finance.

Electricity demand has risen on robust GDP growth, due to the expansion of copper mining and agriculture. Peak demand grew from 1.5GW in 2010 to a record 2.2GW in 2018. Despite the drop in copper prices in 2016, Zambia's mining sector has seen copper production almost double following the commissioning of the country's first coal-fired power plant, Maamba, in July 2016. However, Zambia's hydro-dominated power sector has failed to meet growing demand during times of drought: the deficit of power output relative to demand reached around 1,000MW in 2015 and 526MW in 2016, and resulted in load shedding. This had a devastating effect on the Zambian economy, bringing annual GDP growth downwards from a mean 7%, between 2002 and 2014, to 2.92% in 2015, which was the lowest since 1998. In 2019, drought conditions have again caused power shortages, with a peak deficit reported at 273MW. However, the country has made significant steps to improving load management with scheduled 4-hour periods of outages per day and exemptions for critical consumers. The national electrification rate is 31% (67% in urban and 4% in rural areas). The government's plan of 66% national access (90% urban and 51% rural) will likely require mini-grids or off-grid solar, as low population density and affordability can limit the case for major grid extensions to all areas.

On average, the country produces 969MW daily against a peak demand of 2,100MW, resulting in severe load shedding of up to 18 hours per day. Businesses in the country are struggling to maintain operations without stable electricity supply.  Due to unreliable generation in the country's own fleet, Zimbabwe imports around $50 million of electricity each week primarily from South Africa, Mozambique and Zambia. This is not sustainable long-term. All of the country's five main generation plants have surpassed their 25 year general lifespan and are in need of modernization. However, funding for this is limited. In March 2019, Zimbabwe started exporting electricity to regional neighbors including Namibia even while it itself still faced severe load shedding.

Power demand for Afghanistan is largely met by imports. The demand is only expected to rise in the future but imports are not a reliable source to meet the electricity needs, mainly because of the political instability of the exporters. Some policies have been set in place to harness the country's potential to exploit its own hydroelectric, solar and wind resources. There has been progress in the increasing the electrification rates within the country: rural electrification now stands at 85.9% and urban electrification at 98%.

Armenia's peak demand has been falling, from a high of 1.5GWp in 2013. The country's economy has been relatively stable throughout the period, but there has been an increase in energy efficiency efforts and regulation. In a country where the main industry is construction, these regulations could have a marked effect on power demand. Armenia is 100% electrified, with little need for off-grid capacity. Resources for solar and wind are good, though transmission constraints and policy flip-flops have prevented much investment in wind. There are plans to modernize the hydropower fleet in order to extend the life of the plants.

As in many former soviet republics, power demand decreased significantly after the collapse of the Soviet Union due to a drop in industrial production. Power demand has been rising in recent years as the economy has grown, although the relationship will ultimately decouple with economic growth expected to outstrip growth in power demand.  Economic growth is largely dependent on oil and gas exports, and increased efficiency in energy use will further disconnect the two. The country is reforming legislation to strengthen the current power system and market. The electrification rate is 100%, so off-grid and mini-grid potential would appear to be limited. The potential for minigrid development to increase energy security and stability of the system is not yet under consideration.

Bangladesh is an electricity deficit country where several large customers experience regular load shedding. The country will consume more electricity as the population increases and GDP rises. Several industries that had been receiving subsidized gas to generate their own power may start buying electricity from the grid as domestic gas supplies decrease and the country's reliance on expensive imported gas increases. Most of the rural population in Bangladesh has access to electricity through the use of solar home systems. Further increases in the country's power requirements will be met through a combination of new power generation projects and electricity imports from India.

TThe government's aggressive electrification program has raised the share of households with access to electricity from 22% in 2010 to a reported 72% in 2018, boosting demand for power six-fold. The quality of electricity supply remains an issue in remote areas, but opportunities for off-grid companies are thin: the government is not transparent about grid extension plans, and off-grid systems are unable to feed into the grid once it arrives, effectively stranding these assets. Many companies formerly specializing in solar home systems have shifted focus to work on commercial and industrial sites, where there is more opportunity.

China's power demand grew 8.5% year-on-year in 2018, to 6,845 TWh. Growth in 1H 2019 narrowed noticeably to 5%, largely due to trade tensions. Despite that, the energy transition and electrification of transport, heating, industrial processes, etc. are long-term policy goals that will continue to bolster demand. Investing in renewable energy will be subject to new challenges in navigating the relatively opaque auctions that often do not disclose timeline, volume caps, or grid capacity, which is the key limiting factor.

From 2010 to 2018, India's peak demand had a compound annual growth rate of 4.1% to reach 164GW in 2018. In this period of eight years, the peak demand deficit dropped from 9.8% to 0.6% on the back of capacity addition ' mainly coal-fired plants. The Central Electricity Authority expects peak demand to jump to 226GW by March 2022, driven by population growth, the government's focus on ensuring 24x7 power for all, economic growth and the electrification of sectors such as transport. The power sector needs to undergo a rapid transformation to achieve the goal of 40% electricity generation from non-fossil fuels by 2030.

Power demand in Indonesia is not increasing as expected by the country's policy planners. Economic growth rates were high during 2010-12, and electricity demand increased at an annual rate of 8-9%. Demand growth has slowed since 2014 to only 4-5% per year due to lower-than-expected GDP growth. This has forced the government to cut its power capacity expansion plans. The government reported 98% of all households as electrified in 2018, up from about 64% in 2010. In the medium term, there is a huge potential to develop clean energy microgrids in Indonesia as the country has more than 5GW of oil and diesel power generators providing electricity in the remote regions. Replacing diesel power with a combination of solar and battery storage could decrease generation costs as well as emissions. Indonesia receives relatively good sunshine throughout the year, and therefore offers significant opportunities for large- and small-scale solar power projects in the long-term. The country does not currently have any official power plant fleet modernization programs.

Electricity generation reached 103 billion KWh in 2017, having more than doubled since 2000. Demand increased at an annual average rate of 4.4% through 2012, slowed over 2013-16 due to an economic downturn, then rebounded in 2017 to over 6%. Electricity is predominantly generated in the north by inefficient Soviet-era coal plants, while demand is greatest in the south, surrounding Almaty ' the country's largest city. The grid connecting the two regions does not extend westward to the oil producing regions adjacent the Caspian Sea. There is a potential for robust wind and solar development. However, formidable investment, and government reversals of regulation and reform, remain challenges.

The country's electrification rate is near 100%, but the Kyrgyz Republic suffers from power supply reliability issues due to its dependence on large hydropower plants, most of which are operating beyond their intended lifespan. While peak power demand has remained flat in recent years, the country needs to install additional power capacity and invest in existing plants in order to address reliability concerns and enable economic growth. Kyrgyz Republic has seen GDP growth of around 4% for the past five years. It is likely this would be higher if power outages were less frequent.

Power demand has surged as Laos has extended its electric grid to the countryside, with peak load doubling between 2010-2018 and overall generation (much of which is exported) almost quadrupling over the same time frame. Laos aims to reach 98% household electrification by 2020. It is well on its way, according to official statistics, with 94% electrification in 2018, compared to only 15% in 1995. Concerns remain, however, on the quality of the power supply to rural areas, and many speculate that the true electrification rate remains around 70-80%. Off-grid systems are an option for the remaining households, but the remoteness of these homes means that income-generating opportunities ' and therefore, the ability to pay for solar home systems ' remain limited. Most solar home systems to date have effectively been financed through grants.

Average power demand in Malaysia has increased at a compound annual growth rate of 4% since 2010. The country achieved 100% electrification in 2015. The International Monetary Fund expects Malaysia's economy to grow at 4.7-4.8% annually for the next few years. This, along with greater efforts to improve electricity supply in rural areas, offers room for electricity demand growth in the coming years. The country has a potential for 42GW of rooftop solar power capacity, and 16.5GW of solar on water bodies is possible. Malaysia is also the third-largest PV cell producer in the world. The average age of power generation assets in the country is still low, therefore Malaysia does not have a power plant modernization program.

Power demand has slowly increased in recent years but remains low ' a trend expected to continue in the coming decade. This is because GDP growth in Mongolia peaked at 17% in 2011, and has slowed down significantly since. It was as low as 1.2% in 2016. A rebound was observed in 2017 (5.9%) and 2018 (6.9%), meaning more potential opportunities for business in the country. In addition, the national electrification rate for its population of about 3 million is 88% (only 60% in rural areas), so power demand has room to grow. The country has vast land resources and good weather conditions to develop wind and solar, while mini- and off-grid systems operate well in remote areas. Mongolia also needs to modernize its coal-power fleet as it was built at least 30 years ago

Myanmar will need to increase its power capacity fourfold by 2030 from the 2017 level to meet its demand and the target of 100% electrification. In addition to developing utility scale gas plants and renewable power, the government has ambitious plan to build microgrid and offgrid projects across the country, with funding from multilateral development agencies.

Nepal's power generation grew more than 20% in 2017 and close to 10% in 2018, but demand continues to exceed supply of power. In fact, the shortage of power has become one of the most important barriers to better economic growth. The electrification rate is 85%, and 100% is targeted by 2030. With only 2% of the total estimated 42GW of hydro resource tapped, the expected demand of 17,400GWh by 2027 may not be met.

A spate of new power plants commissioned in the last few years means that the gap between demand and supply has narrowed, reducing the frequency and severity of blackouts. Planners are getting ready for an era of surplus electricity on the government-owned networks, with K-Electric following in the next few years. This puts brakes on the expansion of renewables, even though they present the most cost-competitive option to generate power. Despite this surplus, transmission and distribution losses of between 20-30% mean that the market will remain highly inefficient and indebted.

Over the past two decades, the Philippines went through significant energy reforms, and opened up its power industry to the private sector. However, the relationship between developers and regulators has been strained, with the former complaining about red tape and bureaucracy. While the government has created policies that allow more private participation, the failure to meet installation targets suggests a lack of follow-through. Unpermitted rooftop solar is widespread. One of the largest solar vendors widely advertises a solar-diesel-storage microgrid that is often deployed without the required permits. While policy implementation lags, both population and economic growth are expected to increase demand greatly and open up more opportunities for power development.

Singapore is a developed economy with strong legal and institutional frameworks in place to support business transactions and financing arrangements. The country has world-class infrastructure and office space, and a highly educated English speaking workforce. The government is also keen to attract foreign investment and developers into the market and is likely to attract more foreign players for subsequent tender rounds for SolarNova and floating PV projects.

Rooftop solar is a bright spark in renewable energy in Sri Lanka. The availability of a net metering scheme coupled with high tariffs means that more and more rooftops are aiming for solar installations. ADB provided loans worth $50 million to 100 thousand entrepreneurs to build rooftop solar projects in 2018. Import of equipment for renewable energy is exempt from the national building tax (NBT) and as well as the ports and airport levy (PAL).

Taiwan's power demand is only expected to grow modestly at 1.6% in the next two decades, according to Taiwan Research Institute. Yet the government's intention to take all the 5.1GW nuclear power capacity offline by 2025 creates opportunities for renewable energy. The island has been receptive to foreign players, granting three-quarters of the 3.8GW offshore wind capacity announced in April 2018 to overseas developers. The government is also working with global supply chain companies to establish a local offshore wind manufacturing hub. Overseas banks have also participated in project financing.

Despite its near 100% electrification rate, Tajikistan suffers from power reliability issues due to its dependence on large hydropower plants, most of which are operating beyond their intended operating life. Still, these large hydro plants also provide the country with an oversupply of power in summer months, so Tajikistan is an active participant in the CASA 1000 project, a new transmission line that aims to better connect the country with the Kyrgyz Republic, Pakistan and Afghanistan. Tajikistan has experienced high GDP growth for the past six years, and peak power demand has increased moderately.

Thailand has achieved 100% electrification. In the 2018 PDP, total electricity demand is forecast to increase at an average growth rate of 3.2% over the period 2018-36. Year-on-year percentage growth is expected to decrease. Average growth is estimated to be 3.9% over the period 2019-22, and drop to 3% for 2023-37. This is partly due to an expected increase in energy efficiency. To boost the development of the renewable energy industry, Thailand's Board of Investment has exempted such projects from import tariffs. The investment climate in Thailand is stable. There are no known defaults by the single offtaker, EGAT. The grid in Thailand is also relatively robust, with a few instances of supply interruptions and no known curtailment. There are no barriers to entry in the form of foreign ownership restrictions or local content requirements.

The country and its economy are effectively closed to the outside world. Independent offtake, contracts, and investments are extremely difficult, if not impossible, to secure. Any potential for the situation to improve is linked to global gas pricing and fundamentals.

Power demand growth has been largely flat since 2012, according to the Ministry of Economy. However, blackouts in some parts of the country during peak demand periods indicate that demand is not always met. The country's economic development has been boosted by oil and gas production for export. Other sectors have been languishing, and agriculture, another mainstay of the economy, has been battling issues including water scarcity. Much is made of the potential for renewables development in Uzbekistan, due to its good wind and solar resources. The country has embarked on the construction of its first nuclear power plant, with Russia's Rosatom, aiming to help stabilize the power system which, as in many former Soviet republics, is in dire need of investment.

Power demand grew at an average rate of 11% annually between 2014 and 2018 on the back of a growing manufacturing industry. This rapid growth resulted in a tripling of electricity generation from coal in the same period. Vietnam plans to more than triple coal capacity again, from 17GW in 2017 to 55GW by 2030. The country has an electrification rate of 99.2% with the urban population fully electrified. Most of the solar and wind potential areas lie in the low power demand regions in the country.

Albania is seeking investment in its power sector, but its market is viewed as not yet mature enough to overcome perceived risk. Complete unbundling of the transmission and distribution sectors, along with the establishment of a power exchange, would go a long way toward addressing that perception. Control of most institutions remains with state-owned entities, and free market operations are slow to take off. Despite feed-in tariff contracts awarded to numerous developers to build small hydro facilities, most licenses are traded away. Large international investors seeking a lasting presence in the country are rare; Statkraft's presence is an exception. The most recently concluded auction for solar power was awarded to a consortium of international developers. However, with no reported local partner or presence, their long term success in the country is hard to determine.

The World Bank estimates that BiH is in need of an additional $6 billion for the modernization of its power sector and construction of new generation facilities. Over half of the country's thermal capacity was commissioned in the 1960s and 1970s ' the list of thermal power plants to be closed encompasses 30% of the country's thermal total. Demand has grown strongly since the turn of the millennium, and power generation increased by 50% between 2001 and 2013. As exports more than quadrupled between 2001 and 2010, distribution losses halved in the 2007-10 period. BiH is currently a net electricity exporter, although this could change if no significant generation facilities are brought into service over the next decade.

Power demand in Georgia has been rising for the past eight years but is leveling off. The majority of the growth comes from rural areas in the north of the country, where service is complicated by the presence of Russia-occupied territories. There are plans to upgrade the grid and add new high-voltage lines in order to accommodate new renewable energy. Aging hydropower plants are being refurbished to extend their lifetimes. The country is completely electrified, and there is little interest in off-grid developments.

North Macedonia aspires to join the European Union and is working to streamline all operations with EU standards. While there is no one-stop shop overseeing all aspects of project development, recent years have seen progress being made in streamlining application processes. Having been defined by legislation, the timetable for handling applications is clear ' the average time for getting decision on applications is between one and two months.

As was the case elsewhere in the former Soviet Union, Moldova's power demand dropped as a result of the industrial decline when the U.S.S.R. collapsed in 1991. Demand has recovered slowly, as the country remains predominantly agricultural and its economic system contends with the breakaway region of Transnistria, which receives economic support from Russia. The overall economy grew by 4% from 2017-2018, with services and construction outpacing agriculture. The post-Soviet Moldovan energy system requires investment as the grid is outdated and unconnected with Western Europe's. Plans to synchronize the Moldovan grid with the European system have been drawn up, in tandem with a similar plan in Ukraine, but the effort required is enormous, requiring both financial and political resources that heretofore have not been evident.

Russia's climate and expansive land means it has significant resource potential for wind and solar, but meaningful development has thus far been held back by a number of barriers including volatile exchange rates, high local content requirements and international sanctions. Russia has a good grid and road network to support industry, and it has a 100% electrification rate. Electricity demand in Russia has remained fairly flat and is expected to continue to do so, as a result of sluggish economic growth.  Though electricity generation has increased by roughly 25% since 2000, it has only recently reached pre-1990 levels, prior to the collapse of the Soviet Union and the economic shock that ensued

Serbia has a consumption target of 36.6% renewable energy in the electricity sector by 2020. As of 2018, it reached roughly 33% ' hydro commanded a 33% share of installed capacity (plus some small generation from wind and demonstration solar projects). But with 500MW of wind capacity due online by 2020, it is expected to close the gap. To meet the EU's accession requirements, specifically, adhering to the 'Large Combustion Plants Directive', at least eight coal power plants need to be shut down by 2024. The generation gap is to be replaced by two new coal power plants, a combined heat and power plant, and at least 500MW of wind capacity. Since 2010, peak power demand has been flat.

In 2018, Turkey bucked its longer-term trend of adding capacity across all technologies based on the assumption of long-term economic growth and increasing power demand. In 2018 demand slowed, and the first half of 2019 has seen an even more dramatic drop in electricity consumption. The government's prioritization of lignite and emphasis on domestic resources means it is focusing on adding capacity based on energy independence and security of supply rather than just the economics of different technologies. To take advantage of domestic resources, Turkey plans to refit existing coal assets to run off lower-quality domestic lignite rather than imported hard coal ' this should help keep costs down and reduce reliance on imported fuel.

Power demand in Ukraine fell after the 2014 Russian annexation of Ukrainian Crimea, and ongoing militarization of eastern Ukraine has led to major economic volatility and a longer term slowdown. Demand has revived somewhat since 2016, as parts of the country have stabilized and returned to growth. The current generation fleet has been adequate to serve the national market, but Soviet-era nuclear assets must either be upgraded or replaced. The government's drive to improve the energy efficiency of housing and public buildings is expected to limit increases in demand while renewables are developed. The aim is to lower Ukraine's dependence on Russian gas for its power and heating needs. The south of Ukraine has good solar resources, which has drawn investors to regions such as Odessa. Wind resources also are good in several areas. The distribution and transmission system will require major investment to integrate growing renewables capacity.

Argentina's clean energy investment has been affected by the recent macroeconomic and political crises. At risk is the financing of projects from RenovAr 2, which awarded contracts to 1.8GW of wind and solar assets. Additionally, the Ministry of Energy decreased considerably the amount of capacity tendered in 2018. RenovAr MiniRen 3 focused on small-scale projects and awarded only 259MW of clean energy projects due to transmission limitations. The country planned to launch a public-private partnership in order to expand its power grid but has delayed the plans due to a severe devaluation of the Argentine peso. On the positive side, thanks to Resolution 281/2017, which obligates large consumers to meet renewables targets, the country has seen a significant increase in corporate PPAs to procure clean power.

Bolivia's energy reform prioritizes the electrification of rural areas, aiming for universal access by 2025. By consequence, demand for electricity is rapidly growing, rising 5% annually on average since 2010. Much rural electrification takes the form of off-grid projects, mainly relying on thermoelectric generators and solar photovoltaics. Business opportunities for renewables are on the rise after the first projects were commissioned in the past year. The largest planned projects are hydroelectric dams, as the country views them as the fastest way to achieve clean energy targets and increase exports to neighbors.

Latin America's largest economy is restrained by tepid growth as it limps back from a deep recession in 2015-16. Brazil's GDP expanded just 1.1% in 2018, and growth has remained near 1% for the past two and a half years. Sluggish growth is expected to persist through the end of 2019, with annual GDP growth forecast cut from 2.4% in March to 0.8% in September. Unemployment remains high, productivity lags and public debt has risen. Inflation has grown slower than anticipated and is expected to end 2019 at 3.6% vs. a target of 4.25%.

Chile is the world's largest copper exporter, and the energy-intensive nature of that industry creates substantial power demand. The copper industry alone accounted for nearly half of Chile's exports. In a given year, the mining industry consumes an average of 30% of the total power generated in the country. Mining operations are located in the northern part of the country and mostly served by the SING system. The majority of coal assets are also located in this region, in addition to the greatest potential for solar generation in the country. However, the lack of interconnection between SIC and SING has historically driven the majority of solar developments to the SIC system, where over 90% of the population lives and most of the retail demand is located. This reality might change, however, as the government increasingly focuses on integration of the two sub-systems.

The business environment for renewable energy in Colombia is mixed. While the country has seen average electricity demand growth of 2.5% annually since 2010 and has a well-established regulatory framework governing its electricity sector, policies introduced before and during 2018 have done little to accelerate development of non-hydro renewables. The government introduced tax incentives for investments in renewables in Law 1715, effective in 2014. It provides for accelerated depreciation of up to 20% per year for renewable energy investments, income tax deduction of 50% of investment value for up to 50% of taxable income for up to five years, VAT exemption for renewable energy equipment and services and import duty exemption for renewable energy equipment not produced locally. However, it took almost two years from enactment for the law to come into force, so benefits to the market have been limited so far. The off-grid space, or zonas no interconectadas (ZNI), is characterized by a large amount of players, but faces implementation challenges in rural areas.

Costa Rica's government shows strong commitment to energy and climate-related incentives. However, high hydro penetration and slow demand growth limits new entrants in the market. Around 73% of the country's power generation is supplied by hydro, reducing the need for other clean energy sources for the country to meet its goals. Generation grew 20% between 2010 and 2018, while peak demand rose by 6% from 2015 to 2018.

In 2018, the Dominican Republic's electrification rate was 96%. Peak power demand jumped 26%, from 1,810MW in 2010 to 2,280MW in 2018, while generation grew 21% over the same period. 
On January 7, 2019, the Dominican Republic's National Energy Commission (CNE) published a resolution on clean energy auctions. According to this document, national and international companies are allowed to participate, but additional details are not available. On May 27, 2019, CNE authorized 12 provisional concessions for electricity generation, of which two are wind projects and eight are photovoltaic projects corresponding to 874MW in total. The government announced on May 2019 that will invest $900 million in clean energy projects.

On October 13, 2015, the Government of Ecuador submitted its unconditional Intended Nationally Determined Contribution (INDC) to the United Nations, committing to cut greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions in the energy sector by 20.4%-25% below the business as usual (BAU) scenario by 2025. Ecuador also committed to a further reduction of GHG emissions in the energy sector to a level between 37.5% and 45.8% below the BAU scenario by 2025. This additional reduction is conditioned upon availability of resources and international support.

El Salvador's renewables boom is set to continue with more project completions in the next two years. Still, the country remains highly dependent on fossil fuels and hydro, exposing its market to price spikes during droughts and periods of high oil prices. Investment in renewables projects is seen as a path to minimize these impacts.

Guatemala's national energy plan established a target that 64% of its energy should come from renewable sources by 2032. According to the National Electricity Commission (CNEE), as of December 2018, 35% of the country's energy comes from renewables, suggesting that additional investment must be made in coming years. Guatemala's level of electrification was 92% in 2018.

Haiti has limited energy-related policies. The 2017-2018 Finance Act abolished all import duty taxes on PV generation equipment, wind generation equipment, and solar powered off-grid home appliances such as refrigerators, lamps and chargers. Only one-quarter of the population has access to on-grid electricity. The national grid shortfalls have created opportunities for distributed clean energy generation solutions and the implementation of microgrids. With the help of a grant from USAID, EarthSpark was responsible for developing Haiti's first microgrid, which started operation in the south of the country in 2015, providing solar power to around 450 households in the city of Les Anglais. The system relies on batteries to ensure reliability and smart meters for system stability and to facilitate pre-pay capability for its customers.

The business environment for renewable energy in Honduras is high risk. Empresa Nacional de Energia Elctrica (ENEE) has failed to pay the feed-in premium promised to solar plants commissioned by July 31, 2015. According to the ENEE, energy demand is growing and is expected to increase around 4% per year through 2030. Total solar and wind capacity grew by 36% between 2015 and 2018. The national electrification rate in 2018 stood at 81%.

According to the Ministry of Science, Energy and Technology, the national electrification rate in 2018 was 97%. Jamaica's peak demand decreased 2% from 2017 to 2018 to 655MW. Apart of that, Jamaica has not seen many important changes since the renewables auctions in 2015.

After improving under the previous administration, business opportunities for renewable energy in Mexico have begun to encounter increased uncertainties, with the election of President Lopez Obrador in 2018 clouding the outlook for what has recently been Latin America's hottest renewable energy market. The cancellation of Mexico's auctions upended the renewables industry, but fundamentals remain strong. 
Mexico's national generation expanded by over 4% per year over the past five years. The country's three auctions held over 2016-17 spurred investor interest in the country's excellent wind and solar resources, and Mexico has led Latin America in new clean energy investment since 2017. Large projects that secured contracts in the country's first auction, held in March 2016, began to come online in 2018. 
In June 2018, Mexico announced the end of the 15% customs duty on solar PV module imports, introduced in 2015, removing a significant barrier to renewables development. Mexico is a potential market for distributed generation, with residential PV installation accelerating rapidly in recent years. Retail electricity consumers in Mexico who have renewable energy or cogeneration facilities can connect to the national grid, deliver surplus generation to it, and obtain billing credit for excess electricity provided.

Nicaragua's peak power demand jumped 28% over 2010-18, rising 6% on average over the first two years of the period. Growth then decelerated mainly due to an economy slowdown, reaching just 1% per year in 2015-18. Still, the government's National Expansion Plan 2017-2030 expects demand to grow 4.5% per year in that period.

The business environment for renewable energy is positive in Panama. Although hydro still represents a larger source, solar and wind energy began increasing in 2014. Regulations mandate a 5% premium on the price paid for electricity generated from renewable sources, which includes biomass, geothermal, small hydro (up to 3MW), solar and wind.
Paraguay's electrification rate in 2018 was 99%. The country's peak demand jumped 70% over the past nine years, from 1,892MW in 2010 to 3,226MW in 2018.

Ministerio de Energ'a y Minas (MINEM) is responsible for evaluating the need for auctions, and Organismo Supervisor de la Inversin en Energ'a y Miner'a (OSINERGMIN), the power sector regulator, conducts the tenders. A renewable auction expected to be held in 2018 was canceled in April 2017, and no new tender has been announced. MINEM's explanation for the cancellation is that not all projects selected in the previous auction are being developed.

In 10 years, Peru saw its electrification rate spike from 74% to 96%, the biggest increase in Latin America. The progress is due to a rural electrification program, which included an off-grid auction aiming to contract PV systems for isolated regions in the country.

Uruguay's clean energy sector boomed between 2011 and 2015, as result of the energy target and incentive policies for renewable energy. However, the spike in power generation from intermittent sources has saturated the market. As a result, investment has declined and the country is unlikely to hold new clean energy auctions in the short term.

Economic growth helped Egypt increase power demand by a compound annual growth rate of 3% over 2012-18. However, 2017 saw a more modest rise of less than 1%, as economic activity slowed down, in particular in industry, and inflation more than doubled. Economic reforms in 2018 saw modest stabilization and peak power demand grew 5% from 2017. In the longer term, Egypt is expected to see a significant increase in power demand over the next few decades fueled by economic growth. The government is intending to meet the expansion in electricity demand through a mix of fuels, with plans for further coal power tenders and an agreement with Russia's Rosatom to build four 1.2GW nuclear reactors.

International industrials such as General Electric, Siemens and ABB are working with the Iraqi government to repair and upgrade power plants in an attempt to sustain current plant production and rehabilitate capacity damaged during years of conflict. The government also aims to strengthen the grid and reconnect areas in the north and west with the rest of the country. Despite these attempts, Iraq's demand exceeds peak load by almost 50% in hot periods, when air-conditioning units consume the most power. With demand growing in excess of 7% each year, further capacity will be necessary to avoid continued shortages.

The government continues to foresee a considerable increase in power demand despite a slowdown over 2016-2018 linked to slower economic growth. The government expects high population growth combined with an expanding commercial and industrial sector to boost power demand to over 5.8GW by 2025, from 3.3GW in 2017. The majority of Jordanians live in the north of the country surrounding the capital Amman, and 99.9% of the population have access to power. Further renewables growth will be challenged by the financial commitments Nepco has with fossil fuel generators. Whilst growing renewable generation is reducing fossil fuel power plant run hours, Nepco is still bound to pay fossil fuel generators in full through take-or-pay PPAs.

According to the Ministry of Electricity and Water, electricity consumption is growing at approximately 8% a year, meaning capacity needs to double every decade to meet demand. This is the result of several factors, namely wasteful resource consumption on the back of heavily subsidized energy prices, population growth, and a nascent petrochemical industry. By 2018, renewables accounted for a negligible 1% of capacity, but Kuwait's abundant solar and wind resources offer the potential for a quick ramp up. Data from Irena has measured Kuwait's solar global horizontal irradiance at 1,900 KWh/m2/year, while the potential for wind stands at as much as 1,605 hours/year. Although no explicit fleet modernization program has been announced, Kuwait is building capacity in response to the forecasted growth in electricity demand.

Lebanon's power demand is difficult to estimate as much of it is unmet or provided by the fleet of black-market diesel generators. In recent years, an estimated 490MW of additional demand has come from the 1.5 million Syrian refugees present in the country. Forecast demand growth is modest. However, significant investment is required before current demand can be met. Lebanon enjoys high electrification rates and has few off-grid developments, although this sector represents opportunities to reduce dependence on the chronically unreliable grid. In terms of natural resources, Lebanon has abundant solar potential and previous studies have suggested wind potential between 1.5GW to 6GW of capacity.

Oman is struggling with rising public debt. It has historically relied on oil revenue and is also not as rich as its neighbors. It has been significantly affected by the fall in oil prices and the country's credit rating has been downgraded in recent years. The centralized management by the government is relatively efficient at maneuvering these issues, while limited financial resources continue to fuel the investment scene. Financing for IPP projects is still available but more challenging to obtain than it was 3-4 years ago.

Electricity demand has grown at a very rapid clip in Saudi Arabia over the past few decades, but has plateaued since 2015. Capacity totaled just over 90GW in 2018 and has risen on average by 6% annually since 2010. This high demand, driven by an expanding economy, a growing population and the need for greater volumes of desalinated water, has driven the country's interest in diversifying power generation sources and transitioning away from the use of oil. This has prompted efforts to promote the construction of new solar-powered plants as well as gas and nuclear generation.

Peak demand has gone up significantly over the last few years, with an increase of nearly 5,000MW over the last half-decade. This trend is set to continue with the U.A.E.'s persistent economic and population growth. With high irradiation rates, the country has considerable solar potential. Frequent power cuts in the poorer emirates are a thing of the past, and the population is geographically concentrated and connected to the grid ' 85% of Emiratis live in the emirates of Dubai, Abu Dhabi and Sharjah. The power authorities also have very high credit ratings. Existing thermal plants are well-maintained and the country's business environment is generally favorable, with a high degree of clarity regarding the rules and procedures underpinning energy projects.

Power demand is growing in Palestine and this trend will likely continue, although economic growth is limited, especially in the Gaza Strip. The population is expanding more quickly than in Israel, making the Palestinian market an important destination for Israeli power generation. The unreliability of the electricity supply in the Gaza Strip, where most consumers rely on diesel generators, offers opportunities ' still, doing business is difficult as imports and entry are controlled by Israel. In the West Bank, the potential for PV uptake is significant but in practice limited as the most promising area for development is under the control of the Israeli military.

Qatar's power demand has been increasing by 6% on average for the past five years. The demand growth has, however, been quite volatile year-to-year, with a range of 1-11%. There is strong potential for off/mini-grids, mainly to power remote oil and gas operations. Solar makes the most sense to do this, as irradiation is plentiful. The main challenge would be cleaning the panels regularly, as dust storms are frequent. There is no formal power plant modernization program. Facilities than need rehabilitation and upgrades get attention on an ad-hoc basis.

Local content requirements are the primary hurdle to the deployment of clean energy. Another hindrance are rules limited foreign ownership of joint ventures to 49%, and the government's reluctance to issue sovereign payment guarantees, a concern in light of the possibility of Sonelgaz being restructured. In the throes of a political transition, Algeria is seen as a risky market. Similarly, past terrorist attacks have made investors think twice before financing projects in the country's southern regions.

The 2015 Electricity Law established the legal framework for independent power producers (IPPs), and the government is working with the African Development Bank to implement a variety of measures necessary to modernize the sector and attract investment, including PPAs and feed-in tariffs. In the meantime, IPPs are still rare in Angola, and PPAs are negotiated on a case-by-case basis. The sector suffers from a number of inefficiencies: non-payment from customers is a challenge, with over 80% not metered. In addition, the cost of electricity production and distribution is high, the average consumer tariff is low, and official estimates of total sector losses are over 50%, of which 6% is tied to technical losses in transmission, 22% to technical and commercial issues in distribution, and 36% to (non) collection. While Angola does not have official barriers that would hinder import of renewables equipment, the average cost of importing in terms of border and documentary compliance far exceed Sub-Saharan Africa averages, according to recent surveys. Angola will introduce a VAT regime in 2019 at a standard rate of 14%.

Up until mid-2018, CEB was the single buyer and producer for Benin, discouraging IPPs from playing in the market. The decision of the Government of Benin to increase national generation with IPPs will lead to downstream activity in the solar sector. Since there have been no large-scale projects to date, the energy value chain is limited. The lack of existing regulation, or of previous projects, means that project development steps and bureaucracy is unclear. Furthermore, the transmission grid is limited, making the development of large-scale project renewable energy projects particularly challenging.

Botswana, much like other Sub-Saharan countries, has introduced import duty exemptions for equipment and machinery including solar panels and inverters. The Manufacturing Investment Incentive is a broad policy to bolster the manufacturing sector. The incentives makes no special provision for the renewables industry, but do still present an opportunity to develop a manufacturing industry, provided that the local market becomes more stable. Offtaker risk poses a potential hurdle to this market, as the BPC has historically run at a loss. However, more recently the BPC has managed to reduce its losses to a minimum under the guidance of the newly-appointed CEO, Stefan Schwarzfischer. Unlike its neighbors, Botswana has little currency risk with the Pula strengthening against the dollar.

As one of the poorest countries in the world, there are multiple barriers to project development in Burkina Faso. The country is politically unstable, with a military coup causing unrest across the country in 2015. There are few incentives in place for development and a complex regulatory framework that impedes progress. In addition, the lack of transparency, purchasing power and financial stability further thwart the country's attractiveness to investors. As the state utility is heavily indebted, there has been insufficient investment in grid maintenance and fleet modernization. The main grid is consequently unreliable and congested and blackouts are a common and lengthy occurrence.

The country has faced difficulties attracting investment for energy infrastructure due to political instability and conflicts. The legal framework requires updating to attract private sector participation. The economic and political instability of the country has also affected human capital and the development of a skilled workforce. Bureaucracy and the purchasing power of the population are also an important barrier for clean-energy developers, along with the capital high risk derived from political instability.

The main barrier to private-sector participation is the extent of Eneo's concession for generation, which limits those who can produce electricity in any given area. Another barrier is the inconsistent implementation of import duties for renewables, as Cameroon does not have an import tariff waiver. Equally, the government's prioritization of hydro development has impeded solar deployment, which has been seen as too expensive. Of the 792MW of solar in Cameroon's project pipeline, just one megawatt-scale plant (Huawei's 20MW solar microgrid) has secured financing. Concerns over the impact of dry seasons on hydropower availability have encouraged the government to consider alternatives, including some demand response in the capital, Douala.

The dire security situation in the Central African Republic significantly inhibits any form of business project. Currently, the majority of the country is controlled by armed groups, with hardly any basic services available for large parts of the population. The risks for developers and asset owners are therefore high. In addition to the lack of stability in the market, the absence of major policies to incentivize clean energy growth, as well as a lack of sufficient finance and infrastructure to facilitate such growth, are key barriers. There are no exemptions for clean energy components or equipment. The government is considering whether to implement such measures, but this is unlikely to happen in the near future.

Chad's fragile security environment is an overarching barrier to project development. Additionally, the lack of incentivizing legal framework, finance and transparency further diminishes the country's attractiveness to investors. The grid is in need of improvement and expansion prior to adding significant new-build. This has slowed down the development of the Djermaya Solar plant, for example. The state utility SNE is unable to recover its costs due to the mandated price subsidies as outlined above, but seems to have been able to meet its contractual obligations so far.

The privatization of the former public utility SNE has caused upheaval in the power sector, sowing confusion with regards to the assets owned by E2C and the general functioning of the new private utility. Offtaker risk was already high when SNE was a public entity, so it is unclear how reliable the newly privatized E2C will be. In addition, following the issuance of the 2019 finance law, obtaining a generation licence now amounts to five million central African francs per megawatt installed ($9,000 per MW as per average 2018 conversion rate), which is a prohibitively high cost for developers. Fixed electricity tariffs that do not cover production costs further aggravate the issue of project viability. Finally, equipment required for renewable energy projects is taxable through both import tariffs and VAT ' increasing capital costs.

Offtaker risk for power projects in the DRC is very high as SNEL, the state-owned utility, is not solvent. SNEL owns 94% of total installed capacity. This means the prospects for wind and solar developers to build new projects in the country are not very good, due to the high offtaker risk, pricing, currency volatility and political uncertainty. Additionally, poor energy infrastructure, particularly in the area of power transmission and distribution systems, makes it difficult for new entrants to scale up power production across a wider network. The DRC does not yet have any meaningful renewable energy incentives in place. Given the lack of utility-scale energy projects built in recent years, developers would also face a substantial amount of red tape. The DRC has no manufacturing capacity of any scale for its hydro or other renewable energy projects, so local content requirements do not exist. Smaller-scale companies also face import duties on off-grid solar products, unless they are granted an exemption.

The government's preference for installing thermal and hydropower capacity over other renewables is the biggest obstacle facing the deployment of clean energy. In addition, the longstanding presence of several IPPs does not favor market entrants. Other barriers include arbitrary enforcement of customs exemptions, an official aversion to promoting off-grid solutions and the utility's single-buyer status. Such issues as high tax rates, red tape and a ponderous labor market are also cited by developers. Yet the market could change quickly with the commissioning of the first utility-scale PV projects starting in late-2019, and much-needed power market reform could well accompany the CIE's contract renewal the following year.

A variety of barriers impact clean energy deployment in Eritrea. One of the key obstacles to project development is the general security and political situation, although there are signs that it is improving following the peace talks with Ethiopia. The lack of regulatory framework in the power sector does little to counteract the country's overall lack of transparency. Importing renewables components and equipment in general is a cumbersome process. Given that clean energy is completely in its infancy in Eritrea, with no incentivizing policies nor a real renewable value chain in place, there is little to attract new projects.

Financing in general is a big challenge in Ethiopia. The rapid devaluation of the Ethiopian birr has led to currency risk, and there is a general lack of a domestic and foreign commercial banking presence in Ethiopia. Most financing to date has come from traditional players in the development finance sector, like the World Bank. The currency risk also leads to uncertainty around the credibility of Ethiopia Electric Power as an offtaker. While off-grid solar products in Ethiopia are expected to be exempt from value-add taxes like the rest of East Africa, enforcement of this policy is spotty, and many importers have been dinged with additional charges. This enforcement will need to be improved to grow the country's off-grid market.
